{"title_page": "Leah Moore", "text_new": "{{short description|Columnist and comics writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n|image =\n|imagesize =\n|caption =\n|birth_name =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|2|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Northampton]], England, United Kingdom\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality = English\n|area = Writer\n|alias =\n|notable works = ''[[Albion (comics)|Albion]]''<br/>''[[Wild Girl (comics)|Wild Girl]]''\n|awards =\n}}\n'''Leah Moore''' (born 4 February 1978) is a comics writer and columnist.\n\n==Career==\nMoore began writing for comics with stories for [[America's Best Comics]] in 2002. Since 2003 most of her comics work has been written with her husband [[John Reppion]], as Moore & Reppion. Together they have scripted comics and graphic novels for the likes of [[2000 AD (comics)|''2000 AD'']], [[Channel 4]] Education, [[Dark Horse Comics|Dark Horse]], [[DC Comics]], [[Dynamite Entertainment]], Electricomics, [[IDW Publishing|IDW]], and [[SelfMadeHero|Self Made Hero]]. Moore & Reppion were consulting writers for some of the mysteries featured in [[Frogwares]] Games multi platform adventure ''[[Sherlock Holmes: Crimes & Punishments|Sherlock Holmes - Crimes & Punishments]]'', 2014. Moore was the Project Manager and a contributing editor for the digital comics publishing and reading platform [http://electricomics.net/ Electricomics] from 2013 to 2016. Moore has written for [[Dynamite Entertainment]] ([[Gail Simone]]'s ''Swords of Sorrow'', ''[[Red Sonja]]''), [[Heavy Metal (magazine)|Heavy Metal Magazine]], 2000 AD (''Summer Special'' ''2018'')'','' and [[Shelly Bond]]'s [http://www.blackcrown.pub/ Black Crown Publishing] (''Femme Magnifique'', ''Black Crown Quarterly''). She has also written columns and articles for Lifetime TV online, The Big Issue, and Comic Heroes Magazine.<ref name=\"Electricomics\"/><ref name=\"Echo 2009\">{{cite web | last=Echo | first=Liverpool | title=Comic genius of Doctor Who's husband and wife writing team | website=liverpoolecho | date=2009-01-26 | url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/comic-genius-doctor-whos-husband-3462877 | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Coke 2019\">{{cite web | last=Coke | first=Travis Hedge | title=Strangely Dressed Ladies: Swords of Sorrow | website=Comic Watch | date=2019-10-30 | url=https://comic-watch.com/news/strangely-dressed-ladies-swords-of-sorrow | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"pastemagazine.com 2018\">{{cite web | title=A Young Girl\u2019s Magical Legacy is Darker Than it Seems in Conspiracy of Ravens | website=pastemagazine.com | date=2018-09-06 | url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/09/a-young-girls-magical-legacy-is-darker-than-it-see.html | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMoore was born to [[Alan Moore]] and Phyllis Moore in 1978 in [[Northampton]], England.  Her father is well known as a comics writer and Moore grew up familiar with that industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jun/06/alan-moore-digital-comics-open-source-electricomics-app|title=Alan Moore leading digital comics to open-source future|first=Subhajit|last=Banerjee|date=6 June 2014|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> She lives in Liverpool with her husband and children.<ref name=\"Electricomics\">{{cite web | title=TEAM | website=Electricomics | url=http://electricomics.net/about/team/ | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Echo 2009\"/><ref name=\"Bleeding Cool News And Rumors 2018\">{{cite web | title=Talking to Leah Moore and John Reppion About Conspiracy Of Ravens, Class Poverty and Judge Dredd Megazine #400 | website=Bleeding Cool News And Rumors | date=2018-10-02 | url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/10/02/leah-moore-john-reppion-conspiracy-of-ravens-judge-dredd-megazine-400/ | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"SelfMadeHero\">{{cite web | title=Creators | website=SelfMadeHero | url=https://www.selfmadehero.com/creators/leah-moore | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Comics===\n*''[[Wild Girl (comics)|Wild Girl]]'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Shawn McManus]] and [[J.H. Williams III]], [[Wildstorm]], 2006)\n*''[[Albion (comics)|Albion]]'' (plotted by [[Alan Moore]], with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Shane Oakley]], Wildstorm, 2006, [[trade paperback (comics)|tpb]], Wildstorm, 176 pages, December 2006, {{ISBN|1-4012-0994-7}}, [[Titan Books]], 144 pages, January 2007, {{ISBN|1-84576-351-3}})\n*Accent Anthologies (with co-author [[John Reppion]]):<ref>[http://www.accentukcomics.com/ Accent Comics]</ref>\n*''Witchblade'': \"Shades of Gray\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Stephen Segovia]], [[Top Cow]]/[[Dynamite Entertainment]], 2007)\n*''[[Raise the Dead (comics)|Raise the Dead]]'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and pencil by Hugo Petrus and inks by [[Marc Rueda]], 4-issue mini-series, Dynamite Entertainment, 2007, tpb, 120 pages, February 2008, {{ISBN|1-933305-56-8}})\n*''[[Savage Tales]]'': \"Battle for Atlantis\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Pablo Marcos]], in ''Savage Tales'' #1\u20133, Dynamite Entertainment, 2007)\n*''[[Gene Simmons House of Horrors]]'': \"Into The Woods\"  (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Jeff Zornow]], [[IDW Publishing]], 2007, tpb, 192 pages, April 2008, {{ISBN|1-60010-209-3}})\n*''[[Space Doubles]]'': \"Project: Obeah\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Jeremy Dale (comics)|Jeremy Dale]] and [[Jason Roth]], [[Th3rd World Studios]], 2007)\n*''Nevermore'': \"[[The Black Cat (short story)|The Black Cat]]\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[James Fletcher (comics)|James Fletcher]], Eye Classics, [[Self Made Hero]], October 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-9552856-8-4}})<ref>[http://www.selfmadehero.com/classical_eye/nevermore.html ''Nevermore'' at Selfmadehero] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070922075214/http://www.selfmadehero.com/classical_eye/nevermore.html |date=22 September 2007 }}</ref>\n* \"Deadeye\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[Matt Timson]], in ''[[Popgun (comics)|Popgun]]'' No. 1, ''Popgun'' No. 2, [[Image Comics]], 2007/2008)\n*''[[Darkness (comics)|Darkness]] vs. Eva'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[Edgar Salazar]])<ref>[http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=13152 In & Out of the Dark Ages: Moore & Reppion on \"Darkness vs. Eva\"], [[Comic Book Resources]], 26 February 2008</ref><ref>[http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=150642 Moore & Reppion Darkness vs. Eva] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316122439/http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=150642 |date=16 March 2009 }}, [[Newsarama]], 19 March 2008</ref>\n*''[[Doctor Who (comics)|Doctor Who]]'': \"The Whispering Gallery\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[Ben Templesmith]], [[one-shot (comics)|one-shot]], [[IDW Publishing]])\n*''The Complete [[Dracula]]'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[Colton Worley]], 5-issue limited series, Dynamite Entertainment 2009)\n*''[[The Trial of Sherlock Holmes]]'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]], Dynamite Entertainment 2009)\n* ''The Thrill Electric'' with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[WindFlower Studio]], October 2011, \n*''[[Sherlock Holmes]] \u2013 The Liverpool Demon'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]]), Dynamite Entertainment, 2013\n\n===Books===\n* ''Tolkien's Middle-Earth: A Portrait of a Mythology'', 2002\n* ''Tom Strong'', 2010\n* ''Kismet'', 2013\n* ''Guarded'', 2014 \n* ''Swords of Sorrow'', 2015\n* ''Black Crown'', 2017\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official homepage}}\n* [http://forbiddenplanet.co.uk/blog/?p=1260 July 2006 interview about ''Albion'' and future projects], by [[Forbidden Planet (bookstore)|Forbidden Planet]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060720212613/http://www.dynamiteentertainment.com/htmlfiles/moorereppionpress020306.html Dynamite Entertainment announcement of their signing up]\n\n{{Alan Moore}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Leah}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:English comics writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Northampton]]\n[[Category:Female comics writers]]\n[[Category:Alan Moore]]\n[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Columnist and comics writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n|image =\n|imagesize =\n|caption =\n|birth_name =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1978|2|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Northampton]], England, United Kingdom\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality = English\n|area = Writer\n|alias =\n|notable works = ''[[Albion (comics)|Albion]]''<br/>''[[Wild Girl (comics)|Wild Girl]]''\n|awards =\n}}\n'''Leah Moore''' (born 4 February 1978) is a comics writer and columnist.\n\n==Career==\nMoore began writing for comics with stories for [[America's Best Comics]] in 2002. Since 2003 most of her comics work has been written with her husband [[John Reppion]], as Moore & Reppion. Together they have scripted comics and Graphic Novels for the likes of [[2000 AD (comics)|2000 AD]], [[Channel 4]] Education, [[Dark Horse Comics|Dark Horse]], [[DC Comics]], [[Dynamite Entertainment]], Electricomics, [[IDW Publishing|IDW]], and [[SelfMadeHero|Self Made Hero]]. Moore & Reppion were consulting writers for some of the mysteries featured in [[Frogwares]] Games multi platform adventure ''[[Sherlock Holmes: Crimes & Punishments|Sherlock Holmes - Crimes & Punishments]]'', 2014. Moore was the Project Manager and a contributing editor for the digital comics publishing and reading platform [http://electricomics.net/ Electricomics] from 2013 to 2016. Moore has written for [[Dynamite Entertainment]] ([[Gail Simone]]'s ''Swords of Sorrow'', ''[[Red Sonja]]''), [[Heavy Metal (magazine)|Heavy Metal Magazine]], [[2000 AD (comics)|2000 AD]] (''Summer Special'' ''2018'')'','' and [[Shelly Bond]]'s [http://www.blackcrown.pub/ Black Crown Publishing] (''Femme Magnifique'', ''Black Crown Quarterly''). She has also written columns and articles for Lifetime TV online, The Big Issue, and Comic Heroes Magazine.<ref name=\"Electricomics\"/><ref name=\"Echo 2009\">{{cite web | last=Echo | first=Liverpool | title=Comic genius of Doctor Who's husband and wife writing team | website=liverpoolecho | date=2009-01-26 | url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/comic-genius-doctor-whos-husband-3462877 | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Coke 2019\">{{cite web | last=Coke | first=Travis Hedge | title=Strangely Dressed Ladies: Swords of Sorrow | website=Comic Watch | date=2019-10-30 | url=https://comic-watch.com/news/strangely-dressed-ladies-swords-of-sorrow | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"pastemagazine.com 2018\">{{cite web | title=A Young Girl\u2019s Magical Legacy is Darker Than it Seems in Conspiracy of Ravens | website=pastemagazine.com | date=2018-09-06 | url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/09/a-young-girls-magical-legacy-is-darker-than-it-see.html | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMoore was born to [[Alan Moore]] and Phyllis Moore in 1978 in [[Northampton]], England.  Her father is well known as a comics writer and Moore grew up familiar with that industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jun/06/alan-moore-digital-comics-open-source-electricomics-app|title=Alan Moore leading digital comics to open-source future|first=Subhajit|last=Banerjee|date=6 June 2014|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> She lives in Liverpool with her husband and children.<ref name=\"Electricomics\">{{cite web | title=TEAM | website=Electricomics | url=http://electricomics.net/about/team/ | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Echo 2009\"/><ref name=\"Bleeding Cool News And Rumors 2018\">{{cite web | title=Talking to Leah Moore and John Reppion About Conspiracy Of Ravens, Class Poverty and Judge Dredd Megazine #400 | website=Bleeding Cool News And Rumors | date=2018-10-02 | url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/10/02/leah-moore-john-reppion-conspiracy-of-ravens-judge-dredd-megazine-400/ | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"SelfMadeHero\">{{cite web | title=Creators | website=SelfMadeHero | url=https://www.selfmadehero.com/creators/leah-moore | access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Comics===\n*''[[Wild Girl (comics)|Wild Girl]]'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Shawn McManus]] and [[J.H. Williams III]], [[Wildstorm]], 2006)\n*''[[Albion (comics)|Albion]]'' (plotted by [[Alan Moore]], with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Shane Oakley]], Wildstorm, 2006, [[trade paperback (comics)|tpb]], Wildstorm, 176 pages, December 2006, {{ISBN|1-4012-0994-7}}, [[Titan Books]], 144 pages, January 2007, {{ISBN|1-84576-351-3}})\n*Accent Anthologies (with co-author [[John Reppion]]):<ref>[http://www.accentukcomics.com/ Accent Comics]</ref>\n*''Witchblade'': \"Shades of Gray\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Stephen Segovia]], [[Top Cow]]/[[Dynamite Entertainment]], 2007)\n*''[[Raise the Dead (comics)|Raise the Dead]]'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and pencil by Hugo Petrus and inks by [[Marc Rueda]], 4-issue mini-series, Dynamite Entertainment, 2007, tpb, 120 pages, February 2008, {{ISBN|1-933305-56-8}})\n*''[[Savage Tales]]'': \"Battle for Atlantis\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Pablo Marcos]], in ''Savage Tales'' #1\u20133, Dynamite Entertainment, 2007)\n*''[[Gene Simmons House of Horrors]]'': \"Into The Woods\"  (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Jeff Zornow]], [[IDW Publishing]], 2007, tpb, 192 pages, April 2008, {{ISBN|1-60010-209-3}})\n*''[[Space Doubles]]'': \"Project: Obeah\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[Jeremy Dale (comics)|Jeremy Dale]] and [[Jason Roth]], [[Th3rd World Studios]], 2007)\n*''Nevermore'': \"[[The Black Cat (short story)|The Black Cat]]\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]], and art by [[James Fletcher (comics)|James Fletcher]], Eye Classics, [[Self Made Hero]], October 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-9552856-8-4}})<ref>[http://www.selfmadehero.com/classical_eye/nevermore.html ''Nevermore'' at Selfmadehero] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070922075214/http://www.selfmadehero.com/classical_eye/nevermore.html |date=22 September 2007 }}</ref>\n* \"Deadeye\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[Matt Timson]], in ''[[Popgun (comics)|Popgun]]'' No. 1, ''Popgun'' No. 2, [[Image Comics]], 2007/2008)\n*''[[Darkness (comics)|Darkness]] vs. Eva'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[Edgar Salazar]])<ref>[http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=13152 In & Out of the Dark Ages: Moore & Reppion on \"Darkness vs. Eva\"], [[Comic Book Resources]], 26 February 2008</ref><ref>[http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=150642 Moore & Reppion Darkness vs. Eva] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316122439/http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=150642 |date=16 March 2009 }}, [[Newsarama]], 19 March 2008</ref>\n*''[[Doctor Who (comics)|Doctor Who]]'': \"The Whispering Gallery\" (with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[Ben Templesmith]], [[one-shot (comics)|one-shot]], [[IDW Publishing]])\n*''The Complete [[Dracula]]'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[Colton Worley]], 5-issue limited series, Dynamite Entertainment 2009)\n*''[[The Trial of Sherlock Holmes]]'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]], Dynamite Entertainment 2009)\n* ''The Thrill Electric'' with co-author [[John Reppion]] and art by [[WindFlower Studio]], October 2011, \n*''[[Sherlock Holmes]] \u2013 The Liverpool Demon'' (with co-author [[John Reppion]]), Dynamite Entertainment, 2013\n\n===Books===\n* ''Tolkien's Middle-Earth: A Portrait of a Mythology'', 2002\n* ''Tom Strong'', 2010\n* ''Kismet'', 2013\n* ''Guarded'', 2014 \n* ''Swords of Sorrow'', 2015\n*