{"title_page": "Michelle Gayle", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Michelle Gayle\n|image = Michelle_Gayle_in_Swindon.jpg\n|caption =\n|background = solo_singer\n|birth_name = Michelle Patricia Gayle\n|alias =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1971|02|02}}\n|death_date =\n|origin = London, England, United Kingdom\n|genre = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]]\n|occupation = Singer, songwriter, author, actress\n|years_active = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Mark Bright]]|1996|2007|reason=div}}\n|label = [[RCA]] <small>(1993\u20131997)</small><br>[[EMI]] <small>(1997\u20131999)</small><br>N2 Records <small>(2003\u20132005)</small>\n|associated_acts =\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''Michelle Patricia Gayle''' (born 2 February 1971) is a British singer, songwriter, actress and author. Gayle had success as a [[Contemporary R&B|soul and R&B]] singer in the 1990s. She achieved seven [[Top 40]] [[single (music)|singles]] in the [[UK Singles Chart]], her two biggest hits to date being \"Sweetness\" (number 4, September 1994) and \"Do You Know\" (number 6, February 1997).<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited\n| location= London\n| isbn= 978-1-904994-10-7\n| page= 223}}</ref> She released two Top 40 albums through [[RCA Records]] but they parted company in 1997, and although Gayle has recorded other albums, they have not been released.\n\nAs an actress, Gayle is best known for her work on television, in particular playing [[Hattie Tavernier]] in [[BBC]]'s ''[[EastEnders]]'' from 1990\u20131993. She has also had various roles in film and theatre and played [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]] in the West End musical ''[[Beauty and the Beast (theatrical production)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' in 1999. She has taken part in several celebrity-based reality television shows, and, in June 2007, she became a panellist for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s topical chatshow ''[[Loose Women]]''.\n\nGayle branched into writing and the rights to her first novel were acquired by [[Walker Books]] in 2010. The book, ''Pride and Premiership'', was published on 5 May 2011.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peet |first=Mal |title=Pride and Premiership: Amazon.co.uk: Michelle Gayle: Books |date= |id= {{ASIN|1406330884|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\nShe was married to ex-footballer [[Mark Bright]] for ten years, but the couple separated in 2007.\n\n==Acting, presenting and personal appearances==\n\n===Acting===\n====1987-88====\nGayle was born in 1971 in the northwest part of London, in the [[Harlesden]] area.<ref>{{cite book |title=Soul Music A-Z |page=[https://archive.org/details/soulmusicaz00greg/page/119 119] |publisher=Da Capo Press |date=1995 |isbn=9780306806438 |author=Hugh Gregory |url=https://archive.org/details/soulmusicaz00greg/page/119 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=International Who's Who in Music |publisher=Melrose Press |date=1996 |page=[https://archive.org/details/internationalwho02tyle/page/209 209] |volume=2 |isbn=9780948875076 |url=https://archive.org/details/internationalwho02tyle/page/209 }}</ref> She attended the [[Barbara Speake Stage School]] in [[Acton, London|Acton]], west London, at a time when [[Naomi Campbell]], [[Amma Asante]] and [[Kwame Kwei-Armah]] were also attending.<ref name=\"barbara speak\">\"[http://film.guardian.co.uk/features/featurepages/0,,1345897,00.html From Grange Hill to the valleys]\", ''[[The Guardian]]''. URL last accessed on 2007-06-25.</ref> She first became publicly known when she appeared in the [[children's BBC]] television programme ''[[Grange Hill]]'' in [[Grange Hill (series 11)|1988]] and [[Grange Hill (series 12)|1989]] as Fiona Wilson, who was most notably part of a rap duo named Fresh 'n' Fly.<ref name=\"grange\">\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/ilove/years/1978/tv1.shtml I Love 1978]\", ''BBC''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05</ref>\n\n====1990-93====\nGayle later appeared as an extra in TV Drama ''[[London's Burning (TV series)|London's Burning]]'' and in the [[Children's ITV]] television programme ''[[Press Gang]]'' in 1990 as a background member of the news team, and that same year she won the role of [[Hattie Tavernier]] in the popular BBC soap opera ''[[EastEnders]]''. The introduction of the Tavernier family heralded the first time that an entire family had joined the programme all at once. Their introduction was also a well-intentioned attempt to portray a wider range of [[Black people|black]] characters than had previously been achieved on the show.<ref name=\"first10years\">{{cite book |last=Brake|first= Colin|authorlink= Colin Brake|title= EastEnders: The First 10 Years: A Celebration |year=1995|publisher=BBC Books|isbn=978-0-563-37057-4|title-link= EastEnders spin-offs#Non-fiction books}}</ref> Gayle's character remained in the show for three years as [[Ian Beale]]'s PA and was featured in an array of storylines including being abandoned by her fianc\u00e9 [[Steve Elliot]] ([[Mark Monero]]) and suffering a [[miscarriage]] as a result. However, music was always Gayle's first passion, and in 1993 she left ''EastEnders'' to pursue a singing career.<ref>\"[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/tm_headline=hard-at-work&method=full&objectid=18947321&siteid=66633-name_page.html HARD AT WORK]\", ''Daily Record''. URL last accessed on 2009-07-19</ref>\n\n====1999 onwards====\nIn 1999, Gayle played [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]], the lead female, in Disney's ''[[Beauty and the Beast (theatrical production)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and she returned to television acting in 2003, guest-starring in the BBC television dramas ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' and ''[[Holby City]]''. She went on to play the role of Lara in the [[Five (TV)|Five]] soap opera, ''[[Family Affairs]]'' (2005), and played the lead female character, Yvonne, in the film ''[[Joy Division (2006 film)|Joy Division]]'', which was released in November 2006. The film tells the story of a German boy who is orphaned in [[World War II]] and then groomed as a [[KGB]] sleeper. Gayle starred in [[Jason Barrett]]'s British feature film ''The Naked Poet'' as character Joanne, which was screened in London's Mayfair Hotel December 2011.\n\nOn stage, she played the role of Brenda in [[Angie Le Mar]]'s ''The Brothers'' at the [[Hackney Empire]] in April 2006, and she went on to play Jill in Pat Ashworth's ensemble stage production, ''Mum's the Word'', which toured the UK from February to June 2007.<ref name=\"Mum\u2019s the Word\">\"[http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/15886/mums-the-word-tour-2007 Mum\u2019s the Word]\", ''The Stage''. URL last accessed on 2007-02-11 {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> She has recently been filming the hit CBBC show ''[[Wolfblood]]'' as Imara.\n\nIn March 2018, she begun playing the role of as Alison in the musical ''Son of a Preacher Man'', which is based on the life of [[Dusty Springfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/westend/article/Alice-Barlow-and-Michelle-Gayle-to-Join-SON-OF-A-PREACHER-MAN-UK-Tour-in-2018-20171004|title=Alice Barlow and Michelle Gayle to Join SON OF A PREACHER MAN UK Tour in 2018|website=Broadway World|date=4 October 2017|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is currently playing the role of Hermione Granger in the West End production of [[Harry Potter and the Cursed Child]].\n\n===Presenting and reality television===\nGayle was a contestant on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s reality-television show ''[[Reborn in the USA]]'', competing against artists such as [[Elkie Brooks]], [[Sonia (singer)|Sonia]], [[Gina G]], [[Leee John]] and [[Tony Hadley]]. Gayle made it to the final and finished second behind Hadley. In 2004, Gayle presented the UMA Awards with ex-EastEnder [[Gary Beadle]],<ref name=\"bullets\">\"[http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=5450 BULLETS\u2019N\u2019BLING]\", ''The Voice''; URL last accessed on 2007-01-05 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228155912/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=5450 |date=28 February 2009 }}</ref> and in 2005, she appeared as a celebrity mentor on the [[Five (TV)|Five]] documentary ''Pushy Parents''.\n\nIn March 2006, she took part in the fourth series of the [[Channel 4]] reality-television show ''[[The Games (British TV)|The Games]]'' competing against various other celebrities in a series of sports events. Gayle came third in the competition and raised more than \u00a35,000 for her chosen charity, the [[Willow Foundation]].<ref name=\"willow\">\"[http://willowfoundation.org.uk/news_60.shtml Michelle Gayle raises \u00a35,000 for Willow Foundation]\", ''Willowfoundation''; URL last accessed on 2007-02-11 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927224155/http://willowfoundation.org.uk/news_60.shtml |date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> She later became a guest panellist on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s topical chatshow ''[[Loose Women]]'', in June 2007.\n\nIn June 2009, it was announced that Gayle would be one of several celebrities competing in ''[[Dancing on Wheels]]'', BBC's spin-off show to the popular reality television competition ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''. ''[[Dancing on Wheels]]'' paired able-bodied celebrities with those in wheelchairs. The winning pair represented the UK at the Wheelchair Dance Sport European Championships in Israel in October 2009.<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/5592883/Strictly-Come-Dancing-on-Wheels-new-wheelchair-version-of-dance-show-favourite.html Strictly Come Dancing 'on Wheels': new wheelchair version of dance show favourite]\", ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''; URL last accessed on 2009-07-11</ref> Gayle and partner Harry Maule reached the semi-finals, but were beaten in the dance-off by Diana Morgan-Hill and Olympic swimmer Mark Foster.\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===1993\u20131998===\nBefore she gained commercial success, Gayle sang with a rap duo called R-MOR-FUS, performing gigs at various clubs and low-key venues.<ref name=\"EEHandbook\">{{cite book |last= Kingsley|first= Hilary|title= The EastEnders Handbook |year=1990|publisher=BBC books|isbn=978-0-685-52957-7|title-link= EastEnders spin-offs#Non-fiction books}}</ref>\nIn 1993, while she was still on the cast of ''EastEnders'', Gayle signed with [[RCA Records]] and launched herself as a solo artist. He debut single \"Looking Up\" reached number 11 [[chart-topper|hit]]. By 1994, she had her biggest-selling single to date, \"Sweetness\", which reached number 4,<ref name=\"pop\">\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/entertainment/questionofpop/interview_michelle.shtml Michelle Gayle]\", ''BBC''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106203950/http://www.bbc.co.uk/entertainment/questionofpop/interview_michelle.shtml |date=6 November 2012 }}</ref> spent 16 weeks in the [[UK Singles Chart]] and was certified silver, selling more than 300,000 copies. Gayle had further chart success in 1994 with the number-26 hit \"I'll Find You\"; in 1995 with the number-16 \"Freedom\"; and the number-11 \"Happy Just to Be with You\" which sampled [[Chic (band)|Chic]]'s \"[[Good Times (Chic song)|Good Times]]\". These five singles were taken from Gayle's self-titled debut album ''[[Michelle Gayle (album)|Michelle Gayle]]'', which was released in 1994, peaked at number 30 in the [[UK Albums Chart]], and was certified [[music recording sales certification|gold]].\n\nGayle also appeared on the Childliners charity record \"[[The Gift of Christmas (song)|The Gift of Christmas]]\" in 1995, alongside acts such as [[Backstreet Boys]], [[Boyzone]], [[E.Y.C. (band)|E.Y.C.]], [[Sean Maguire]], [[Deuce (band)|Deuce]], [[Ultimate Kaos]], [[Let Loose]], [[East 17]], [[Peter Andre]], [[MN8]], [[Dannii Minogue]] and many more. It peaked at number 9.<ref>\"[https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/ Childliners]\", ''officialcharts.com''. URL last accessed on 2008-02-26</ref>\n\nGayle returned in 1997 with her sixth single, \"Do You Know\", which reached number 6.<ref name=\"pop\"/> This was followed by the song \"Sensational\", which reached number 14. Both singles were taken from Gayle's second album, ''[[Sensational (album)|Sensational]]'', which had multiple producers, and was recorded in both London and Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA83 |title=U.K.'s 1st Avenue Takes A More 'American' Tack |page=83 |magazine=Billboard |date=21 June 1997 |issn=0006-2510 |author1=Sally Stratton |author2=Paul Sexton}}</ref> Despite ''Sensational'' being praised by [[music journalism|critics]], the album had disappointing sales. It entered the album chart at number 17, but quickly fell out of the top 40 the following week. Due to poor album sales, Gayle left RCA. During the time she was signed to the label, Gayle received three [[BRIT Awards|BRIT Award]] nominations: two in 1995 for 'Best Single' and 'Best Female Artist', and one in 1998 for 'Best Female Artist'.\n\n===1999\u20132004===\nFollowing her departure from RCA, Gayle signed with [[EMI]]. She recorded an album for that label, but due to an artist rostering re-shuffle, she had left the company by 1999 before the album was released. After leaving EMI in 1999, Gayle took to the West End stage and played [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]] in [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney's]] ''[[Beauty and the Beast (theatrical production)|Beauty and the Beast]]''. After an extended break from show business to look after her son, Isaiah, Gayle began developing her music production company M Media Productions.<ref name=\"GOTTA\">\"[http://www.angloplugging.co.uk/viewPressRelease.cfm?pressReleaseID=862 GOTTA BE ME] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928151606/http://www.angloplugging.co.uk/viewPressRelease.cfm?pressReleaseID=862 |date=28 September 2007 }}\", ''anglo plugging''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05</ref> She also appeared on other artists' albums, including those of [[Ivan Matias]], [[Me One]], [[Shabba Ranks|Shabba]] and [[Lemon D]].{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}<ref name=\"underground\">\"[http://www.underground-soul.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=41&Itemid=37 Michelle Gayle written by Andrew Davis]\", ''Underground soul''. URL last accessed on 2007-02-11 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930125414/http://www.underground-soul.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=41&Itemid=37 |date=30 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Gayle accepted the offer to appear in the reality television series ''[[Reborn in the USA]]'', a televised singing competition where former British pop acts were transported to the US, with the hope of revitalising their music careers. Gayle finished second in the competition, taking runner-up position to [[Tony Hadley]] in the final. Following her success on the programme, Gayle began working on new material.<ref name=\"MICHELLEII\">\"[http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=3050 MICHELLE MARK II]\", ''The Voice''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228160248/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=3050 |date=28 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nGayle reinvented herself as a UK [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] artist,<ref name=\"pop\"/> and worked on material for her third album with New York record producer [[Terence Dudley (USA)|Terence Dudley]] \u2014 famous for working on [[50 Cent]]'s album ''[[Get Rich or Die Tryin' (album)|Get Rich or Die Tryin']]''.<ref name=\"GOTTA\"/> At the end of 2004, Gayle appeared on several TV shows promoting the release of her new single, \"Gotta Be Me\", but the single was pulled before its release. In an interview with ''[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]'' newspaper in April 2006, she divulged that she did make a new album, but her record company (N2 Records) folded.<ref name=\"lemar\">\"[http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=9060 LE MAR'S TALE]\", ''The Voice''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228155843/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=9060 |date=28 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Eurovision 2008===\nGayle was one of the participants of the pre-selection stage of ''[[Eurovision: Your Country Needs You|Eurovision \u2013 Your Decision]]'', which determined who the United Kingdom would send to the ''[[Eurovision Song Contest]]'' in [[Serbia]] on 24 May 2008. Gayle co-wrote her song, \"Woo (U Make Me)\", with Rashelle Davies and Morten Schjolin, and described it as \"pop in essence, but with a very cool 60's vibe to it\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/eurovision/2008/eyd/michellegayle.shtml \"Eurovision Your Decision]\", ''BBC''; URL last accessed on 2008-02-26 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303004004/http://www.bbc.co.uk/eurovision/2008/eyd/michellegayle.shtml |date=3 March 2008 }}</ref> Gayle came second in the public vote on 1 March 2008, behind [[Andy Abraham]].\n\n==Writing==\nDuring an interview with the ''Blackpool Gazette'' in February 2007, Gayle mentioned that she was in the process of writing her first novel. The plot involved an unpleasant TV talent-show judge who discovers he is dying. She said: \"It's sort of fiction but not fiction but it is made up and true, so when you read it you'll see it's fictional but also real,  and I hope it explains a few things about the pop business.\".<ref name=\"blackpool\">\"[http://www.blackpooltoday.co.uk/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleID=2034442&SectionID=143 Michelle's a mum on move]\", ''Blackpool Gazette''; URL last accessed on 2007-02-11 {{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> It was never published.\n\n[[Walker Books]] acquired the rights to Gayle's novel, ''Pride and Premiership'', in 2010 and the book was published on 5 May 2011.<ref>\"[https://archive.today/20120913041421/http://www.thebookseller.com/news/115035-walker-acquires-wag-series-from-michelle-gayle.html Walker acquires Wag title from Michelle Gayle]\", ''Bookseller.com''; URL last accessed on 2010-04-09</ref> The novel, aimed at a teen market, depicts the story of two girls who aspire to be [[WAGs]], or wives/girlfriends of football players. Gayle, who was once married to a professional footballer, has commented, \"In the time of [[Jane Austen]]\u2019s ''[[Pride & Prejudice]]'' a woman had to get married to support herself. We\u2019ve got to an age where a woman can support herself but still wants to marry a footballer to support her. I\u2019m not WAG-bashing or footballer-bashing, I just want girls to make informed decisions about their future.\"<ref>\"[http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-life-features/liverpool-style-city/2009/11/19/be-your-own-woman-92534-25196824/2/ Michelle Gayle: Don't aspire to be a WAG \u2013 be your own woman]\", ''Liverpool Daily Post''; URL last accessed on 2010-04-09 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124032314/http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-life-features/liverpool-style-city/2009/11/19/be-your-own-woman-92534-25196824/2/ |date=24 November 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGayle was married to ex-professional [[association football|footballer]] and football pundit [[Mark Bright]]<ref name=\"sport\">\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/static/tv_and_radio/passion_for_sport/stars/bright.stm Passion for sport]\", ''BBC''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05.</ref> for ten years, and had one son, Isaiah, with him. The couple separated in 2007 and officially divorced on 18 April 2008. Gayle is [[godparent|godmother]] to the daughter of the actress [[Jacqui Gordon-Lawrence]], who played her on-screen mother, [[Etta Tavernier]], in ''EastEnders''.<ref name=\"MICHELLEII\"/> Gayle is a [[teetotal]]ler<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/jul/04/newsstory.sport3|title=My wife [Michelle Gayle] doesn't drink at all. She's tea-total|last=Rookwood|first=Dan|date=4 July 2003|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2009-05-12}}</ref> and doesn't eat meat.<ref>''[[Come Dine With Me]]'' Channel 4 22 December 2010</ref> On 4 August 2011 it was announced on ''[[The Wright Stuff]]'' that she was pregnant. On Twitter, she announced the birth of her son, Luke, on 2 November 2011.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Year\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Information\n|-\n|<center>1994</center>\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Michelle Gayle (album)|Michelle Gayle]]'''''\n*Label: ([[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]])\n*Chart positions: #30 UK\n*UK certification: Gold\n|-\n|<center>1997</center>\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Sensational (album)|Sensational]]'''''\n*Label: ([[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]])\n*Chart positions: #17 UK\n|-\n|<center>2000</center>\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Looking Up (Michelle Gayle album)|Looking Up]]'''''\n*Label: ([[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]])\n|}<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n\n===Singles===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n!colspan=\"5\"| Chart peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:170px;\"| Album\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"| [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"| [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|NZ]]\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"| [[Dutch Top 40|NL]]\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"| [[Switzerland|SWI]]\n|-\n|| 1993\n| \"Looking Up\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|rowspan=\"5\"|<center> ''Michelle Gayle''</center>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1994\n| \"Sweetness\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 27\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 38\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 21\n|-\n| \"I'll Find You\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 26\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1995\n| \"Freedom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 16\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"Happy Just to Be with You\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 44\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 40\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1997\n| \"Do You Know?\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|<center> ''Sensational''</center>\n|-\n| \"Sensational\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 14\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n|| 2008\n| \"Woo (U Make Me)\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n||\n|-\n| colspan=\"11\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:8pt;\"| \"\u2014\" Denotes singles not released or did not chart in that particular country.\n|}\n\n===B-sides and other tracks===\n*\"Say What's on Your Mind\" (\"Sweetness\" [[A-side and B-side|B-side]]/''[[Michelle Gayle (album)|Michelle Gayle]]'' album track)\n*\"Tell Me\" (\"I'll Find You\" B-side)\n*\"I Thought I Was Your Lady\" (\"Happy Just to Be with You\" B-side)\n*\"Juicy\" (\"Sensational\" B-side)\n*\"Give Me a Try\" (\"Sensational\" B-side)\n*\"Sunshine After Rain\" (\"Sensational\" B-side)\n*\"Until You Come Back to Me\" (''Reborn in the USA'' album track)\n*\"Love Me Tender\" (''Reborn in the USA'' album track)\n*\"Got to Be Me\" (unreleased single)\n*\"Don't Want It\" (\"Got to Be Me\" unreleased B-side)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0310896|name=Michelle Gayle}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081013073634/http://www.myspace.com/michellegayle Official MySpace Page]\n\n{{commons category|Michelle Gayle}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gayle, Michelle}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Black British singers]]\n[[Category:British contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:English soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:Participants in British reality television series]]\n[[Category:Actresses from London]]\n[[Category:Black British actresses]]\n[[Category:English people of Saint Kitts and Nevis descent]]\n[[Category:English female pop singers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Barbara Speake Stage School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Michelle Gayle\n|image = Michelle_Gayle_in_Swindon.jpg\n|caption =\n|background = solo_singer\n|birth_name = Michelle Patricia Gayle\n|alias =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1971|02|02}}\n|death_date =\n|origin = London, England, United Kingdom\n|genre = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]]\n|occupation = Singer, songwriter, author, actress\n|years_active = 1988\u2013present\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Mark Bright]]|1996|2007|reason=div}}\n|label = [[RCA]] <small>(1993\u20131997)</small><br>[[EMI]] <small>(1997\u20131999)</small><br>N2 Records <small>(2003\u20132005)</small>\n|associated_acts =\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''Michelle Patricia Gayle''' (born 2 February 1971) is a British singer, songwriter, actress and author. Gayle had success as a [[Contemporary R&B|soul and R&B]] singer in the 1990s. She achieved seven [[Top 40]] [[single (music)|singles]] in the [[UK Singles Chart]], her two biggest hits to date being \"Sweetness\" (number 4, September 1994) and \"Do You Know\" (number 6, February 1997).<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited\n| location= London\n| isbn= 978-1-904994-10-7\n| page= 223}}</ref> She released two Top 40 albums through [[RCA Records]] but they parted company in 1997, and although Gayle has recorded other albums, they have not been released.\n\nAs an actress, Gayle is best known for her work on television, in particular playing [[Hattie Tavernier]] in [[BBC]]'s ''[[EastEnders]]'' from 1990\u20131993. She has also had various roles in film and theatre and played [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]] in the West End musical ''[[Beauty and the Beast (theatrical production)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' in 1999. She has taken part in several celebrity-based reality television shows, and, in June 2007, she became a panellist for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s topical chatshow ''[[Loose Women]]''.\n\nGayle branched into writing and the rights to her first novel were acquired by [[Walker Books]] in 2010. The book, ''Pride and Premiership'', was published on 5 May 2011.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peet |first=Mal |title=Pride and Premiership: Amazon.co.uk: Michelle Gayle: Books |date= |id= {{ASIN|1406330884|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\nShe was married to ex-footballer [[Mark Bright]] for 10 years but the couple separated in 2007.\n\n==Acting, presenting and personal appearances==\n\n===Acting===\n====1987-88====\nGayle was born in 1971 in the northwest part of London, in the [[Harlesden]] area.<ref>{{cite book |title=Soul Music A-Z |page=[https://archive.org/details/soulmusicaz00greg/page/119 119] |publisher=Da Capo Press |date=1995 |isbn=9780306806438 |author=Hugh Gregory |url=https://archive.org/details/soulmusicaz00greg/page/119 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=International Who's Who in Music |publisher=Melrose Press |date=1996 |page=[https://archive.org/details/internationalwho02tyle/page/209 209] |volume=2 |isbn=9780948875076 |url=https://archive.org/details/internationalwho02tyle/page/209 }}</ref> She attended the [[Barbara Speake Stage School]] in [[Acton, London|Acton]], west London, at a time when [[Naomi Campbell]], [[Amma Asante]] and [[Kwame Kwei-Armah]] were also attending.<ref name=\"barbara speak\">\"[http://film.guardian.co.uk/features/featurepages/0,,1345897,00.html From Grange Hill to the valleys]\", ''[[The Guardian]]''. URL last accessed on 2007-06-25.</ref> She first became publicly known when she appeared in the [[children's BBC]] television programme ''[[Grange Hill]]'' in [[Grange Hill (series 11)|1988]] and [[Grange Hill (series 12)|1989]] as Fiona Wilson, who was most notably part of a rap duo named Fresh 'n' Fly.<ref name=\"grange\">\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/ilove/years/1978/tv1.shtml I Love 1978]\", ''BBC''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05</ref>\n\n====1990-93====\nGayle later appeared as an extra in TV Drama ''[[London's Burning (TV series)|London's Burning]]'' and in the [[Children's ITV]] television programme ''[[Press Gang]]'' in 1990 as a background member of the news team, and that same year she won the role of [[Hattie Tavernier]] in the popular BBC soap opera ''[[EastEnders]]''. The introduction of the Tavernier family heralded the first time that an entire family had joined the programme all at once. Their introduction was also a well-intentioned attempt to portray a wider range of [[Black people|black]] characters than had previously been achieved on the show.<ref name=\"first10years\">{{cite book |last=Brake|first= Colin|authorlink= Colin Brake|title= EastEnders: The First 10 Years: A Celebration |year=1995|publisher=BBC Books|isbn=978-0-563-37057-4|title-link= EastEnders spin-offs#Non-fiction books}}</ref> Gayle's character remained in the show for three years as [[Ian Beale]]'s PA and was featured in an array of storylines including being abandoned by her fianc\u00e9 [[Steve Elliot]] ([[Mark Monero]]) and suffering a [[miscarriage]] as a result. However, music was always Gayle's first passion, and in 1993 she left ''EastEnders'' to pursue a singing career.<ref>\"[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/tm_headline=hard-at-work&method=full&objectid=18947321&siteid=66633-name_page.html HARD AT WORK]\", ''Daily Record''. URL last accessed on 2009-07-19</ref>\n\n====1999 onwards====\nIn 1999, Gayle played [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]], the lead female, in Disney's ''[[Beauty and the Beast (theatrical production)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', and she returned to television acting in 2003, guest-starring in the BBC television dramas ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' and ''[[Holby City]]''. She went on to play the role of Lara in the [[Five (TV)|Five]] soap opera, ''[[Family Affairs]]'' (2005), and played the lead female character, Yvonne, in the film ''[[Joy Division (2006 film)|Joy Division]]'', which was released in November 2006. The film tells the story of a German boy who is orphaned in [[World War II]] and then groomed as a [[KGB]] sleeper. Gayle starred in [[Jason Barrett]]'s British feature film ''The Naked Poet'' as character Joanne, which was screened in London's Mayfair Hotel December 2011.\n\nOn stage, she played the role of Brenda in [[Angie Le Mar]]'s ''The Brothers'' at the [[Hackney Empire]] in April 2006, and she went on to play Jill in Pat Ashworth's ensemble stage production, ''Mum's the Word'', which toured the UK from February to June 2007.<ref name=\"Mum\u2019s the Word\">\"[http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/15886/mums-the-word-tour-2007 Mum\u2019s the Word]\", ''The Stage''. URL last accessed on 2007-02-11 {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> She has recently been filming the hit CBBC show ''[[Wolfblood]]'' as Imara.\n\nIn March 2018, she begun playing the role of as Alison in the musical ''Son of a Preacher Man'', which is based on the life of [[Dusty Springfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/westend/article/Alice-Barlow-and-Michelle-Gayle-to-Join-SON-OF-A-PREACHER-MAN-UK-Tour-in-2018-20171004|title=Alice Barlow and Michelle Gayle to Join SON OF A PREACHER MAN UK Tour in 2018|website=Broadway World|date=4 October 2017|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is currently playing the role of Hermione Granger in the West End production of [[Harry Potter and the Cursed Child]].\n\n===Presenting and reality television===\nGayle was a contestant on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s reality-television show ''[[Reborn in the USA]]'', competing against artists such as [[Elkie Brooks]], [[Sonia (singer)|Sonia]], [[Gina G]], [[Leee John]] and [[Tony Hadley]]. Gayle made it to the final and finished second behind Hadley. In 2004, Gayle presented the UMA Awards with ex-EastEnder [[Gary Beadle]],<ref name=\"bullets\">\"[http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=5450 BULLETS\u2019N\u2019BLING]\", ''The Voice''; URL last accessed on 2007-01-05 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228155912/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=5450 |date=28 February 2009 }}</ref> and in 2005, she appeared as a celebrity mentor on the [[Five (TV)|Five]] documentary ''Pushy Parents''.\n\nIn March 2006, she took part in the fourth series of the [[Channel 4]] reality-television show ''[[The Games (British TV)|The Games]]'' competing against various other celebrities in a series of sports events. Gayle came third in the competition and raised more than \u00a35,000 for her chosen charity, the [[Willow Foundation]].<ref name=\"willow\">\"[http://willowfoundation.org.uk/news_60.shtml Michelle Gayle raises \u00a35,000 for Willow Foundation]\", ''Willowfoundation''; URL last accessed on 2007-02-11 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927224155/http://willowfoundation.org.uk/news_60.shtml |date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> She later became a guest panellist on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s topical chatshow ''[[Loose Women]]'', in June 2007.\n\nIn June 2009, it was announced that Gayle would be one of several celebrities competing in ''[[Dancing on Wheels]]'', BBC's spin-off show to the popular reality television competition ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''. ''[[Dancing on Wheels]]'' paired able-bodied celebrities with those in wheelchairs. The winning pair represented the UK at the Wheelchair Dance Sport European Championships in Israel in October 2009.<ref>\"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/5592883/Strictly-Come-Dancing-on-Wheels-new-wheelchair-version-of-dance-show-favourite.html Strictly Come Dancing 'on Wheels': new wheelchair version of dance show favourite]\", ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''; URL last accessed on 2009-07-11</ref> Gayle and partner Harry Maule reached the semi-finals, but were beaten in the dance-off by Diana Morgan-Hill and Olympic swimmer Mark Foster.\n\n==Musical career==\n\n===1993\u20131998===\nBefore she gained commercial success, Gayle sang with a rap duo called R-MOR-FUS, performing gigs at various clubs and low-key venues.<ref name=\"EEHandbook\">{{cite book |last= Kingsley|first= Hilary|title= The EastEnders Handbook |year=1990|publisher=BBC books|isbn=978-0-685-52957-7|title-link= EastEnders spin-offs#Non-fiction books}}</ref>\nIn 1993, while she was still on the cast of ''EastEnders'', Gayle signed with [[RCA Records]] and launched herself as a solo artist. He debut single \"Looking Up\" reached number 11 [[chart-topper|hit]]. By 1994, she had her biggest-selling single to date, \"Sweetness\", which reached number 4,<ref name=\"pop\">\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/entertainment/questionofpop/interview_michelle.shtml Michelle Gayle]\", ''BBC''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106203950/http://www.bbc.co.uk/entertainment/questionofpop/interview_michelle.shtml |date=6 November 2012 }}</ref> spent 16 weeks in the [[UK Singles Chart]] and was certified silver, selling more than 300,000 copies. Gayle had further chart success in 1994 with the number-26 hit \"I'll Find You\"; in 1995 with the number-16 \"Freedom\"; and the number-11 \"Happy Just to Be with You\" which sampled [[Chic (band)|Chic]]'s \"[[Good Times (Chic song)|Good Times]]\". These five singles were taken from Gayle's self-titled debut album ''[[Michelle Gayle (album)|Michelle Gayle]]'', which was released in 1994, peaked at number 30 in the [[UK Albums Chart]], and was certified [[music recording sales certification|gold]].\n\nGayle also appeared on the Childliners charity record \"[[The Gift of Christmas (song)|The Gift of Christmas]]\" in 1995, alongside acts such as [[Backstreet Boys]], [[Boyzone]], [[E.Y.C. (band)|E.Y.C.]], [[Sean Maguire]], [[Deuce (band)|Deuce]], [[Ultimate Kaos]], [[Let Loose]], [[East 17]], [[Peter Andre]], [[MN8]], [[Dannii Minogue]] and many more. It peaked at number 9.<ref>\"[https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/ Childliners]\", ''officialcharts.com''. URL last accessed on 2008-02-26</ref>\n\nGayle returned in 1997 with her sixth single, \"Do You Know\", which reached number 6.<ref name=\"pop\"/> This was followed by the song \"Sensational\", which reached number 14. Both singles were taken from Gayle's second album, ''[[Sensational (album)|Sensational]]'', which had multiple producers, and was recorded in both London and Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA83 |title=U.K.'s 1st Avenue Takes A More 'American' Tack |page=83 |magazine=Billboard |date=21 June 1997 |issn=0006-2510 |author1=Sally Stratton |author2=Paul Sexton}}</ref> Despite ''Sensational'' being praised by [[music journalism|critics]], the album had disappointing sales. It entered the album chart at number 17, but quickly fell out of the top 40 the following week. Due to poor album sales, Gayle left RCA. During the time she was signed to the label, Gayle received three [[BRIT Awards|BRIT Award]] nominations: two in 1995 for 'Best Single' and 'Best Female Artist', and one in 1998 for 'Best Female Artist'.\n\n===1999\u20132004===\nFollowing her departure from RCA, Gayle signed with [[EMI]]. She recorded an album for that label, but due to an artist rostering re-shuffle, she had left the company by 1999 before the album was released. After leaving EMI in 1999, Gayle took to the West End stage and played [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]] in [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney's]] ''[[Beauty and the Beast (theatrical production)|Beauty and the Beast]]''. After an extended break from show business to look after her son, Isaiah, Gayle began developing her music production company M Media Productions.<ref name=\"GOTTA\">\"[http://www.angloplugging.co.uk/viewPressRelease.cfm?pressReleaseID=862 GOTTA BE ME] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928151606/http://www.angloplugging.co.uk/viewPressRelease.cfm?pressReleaseID=862 |date=28 September 2007 }}\", ''anglo plugging''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05</ref> She also appeared on other artists' albums, including those of [[Ivan Matias]], [[Me One]], [[Shabba Ranks|Shabba]] and [[Lemon D]].{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}<ref name=\"underground\">\"[http://www.underground-soul.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=41&Itemid=37 Michelle Gayle written by Andrew Davis]\", ''Underground soul''. URL last accessed on 2007-02-11 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930125414/http://www.underground-soul.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=41&Itemid=37 |date=30 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Gayle accepted the offer to appear in the reality television series ''[[Reborn in the USA]]'', a televised singing competition where former British pop acts were transported to the US, with the hope of revitalising their music careers. Gayle finished second in the competition, taking runner-up position to [[Tony Hadley]] in the final. Following her success on the programme, Gayle began working on new material.<ref name=\"MICHELLEII\">\"[http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=3050 MICHELLE MARK II]\", ''The Voice''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228160248/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=3050 |date=28 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nGayle reinvented herself as a UK [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] artist,<ref name=\"pop\"/> and worked on material for her third album with New York record producer [[Terence Dudley (USA)|Terence Dudley]] \u2014 famous for working on [[50 Cent]]'s album ''[[Get Rich or Die Tryin' (album)|Get Rich or Die Tryin']]''.<ref name=\"GOTTA\"/> At the end of 2004, Gayle appeared on several TV shows promoting the release of her new single, \"Gotta Be Me\", but the single was pulled before its release. In an interview with ''[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]'' newspaper in April 2006, she divulged that she did make a new album, but her record company (N2 Records) folded.<ref name=\"lemar\">\"[http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=9060 LE MAR'S TALE]\", ''The Voice''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228155843/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/content.php?show=9060 |date=28 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Eurovision 2008===\nGayle was one of the participants of the pre-selection stage of ''[[Eurovision: Your Country Needs You|Eurovision \u2013 Your Decision]]'', which determined who the United Kingdom would send to the ''[[Eurovision Song Contest]]'' in [[Serbia]] on 24 May 2008. Gayle co-wrote her song, \"Woo (U Make Me)\", with Rashelle Davies and Morten Schjolin, and described it as \"pop in essence, but with a very cool 60's vibe to it\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/eurovision/2008/eyd/michellegayle.shtml \"Eurovision Your Decision]\", ''BBC''; URL last accessed on 2008-02-26 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303004004/http://www.bbc.co.uk/eurovision/2008/eyd/michellegayle.shtml |date=3 March 2008 }}</ref> Gayle came second in the public vote on 1 March 2008, behind [[Andy Abraham]].\n\n==Writing==\nDuring an interview with the ''Blackpool Gazette'' in February 2007, Gayle mentioned that she was in the process of writing her first novel. The plot involved an unpleasant TV talent-show judge who discovers he is dying. She said: \"It's sort of fiction but not fiction but it is made up and true, so when you read it you'll see it's fictional but also real,  and I hope it explains a few things about the pop business.\".<ref name=\"blackpool\">\"[http://www.blackpooltoday.co.uk/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleID=2034442&SectionID=143 Michelle's a mum on move]\", ''Blackpool Gazette''; URL last accessed on 2007-02-11 {{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> It was never published.\n\n[[Walker Books]] acquired the rights to Gayle's novel, ''Pride and Premiership'', in 2010 and the book was published on 5 May 2011.<ref>\"[https://archive.today/20120913041421/http://www.thebookseller.com/news/115035-walker-acquires-wag-series-from-michelle-gayle.html Walker acquires Wag title from Michelle Gayle]\", ''Bookseller.com''; URL last accessed on 2010-04-09</ref> The novel, aimed at a teen market, depicts the story of two girls who aspire to be [[WAGs]], or wives/girlfriends of football players. Gayle, who was once married to a professional footballer, has commented, \"In the time of [[Jane Austen]]\u2019s ''[[Pride & Prejudice]]'' a woman had to get married to support herself. We\u2019ve got to an age where a woman can support herself but still wants to marry a footballer to support her. I\u2019m not WAG-bashing or footballer-bashing, I just want girls to make informed decisions about their future.\"<ref>\"[http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-life-features/liverpool-style-city/2009/11/19/be-your-own-woman-92534-25196824/2/ Michelle Gayle: Don't aspire to be a WAG \u2013 be your own woman]\", ''Liverpool Daily Post''; URL last accessed on 2010-04-09 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124032314/http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-life-features/liverpool-style-city/2009/11/19/be-your-own-woman-92534-25196824/2/ |date=24 November 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGayle was married to ex-professional [[association football|footballer]] and football pundit [[Mark Bright]]<ref name=\"sport\">\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/static/tv_and_radio/passion_for_sport/stars/bright.stm Passion for sport]\", ''BBC''. URL last accessed on 2007-01-05.</ref> for 10 years, and had one son, Isaiah, with him. The couple separated in 2007 and officially divorced on 18 April 2008. Gayle is [[godparent|godmother]] to the daughter of the actress [[Jacqui Gordon-Lawrence]], who played her on-screen mother, [[Etta Tavernier]], in ''EastEnders''.<ref name=\"MICHELLEII\"/> Gayle is a [[teetotal]]ler<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/jul/04/newsstory.sport3|title=My wife [Michelle Gayle] doesn't drink at all. She's tea-total|last=Rookwood|first=Dan|date=4 July 2003|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2009-05-12}}</ref> and doesn't eat meat.<ref>''[[Come Dine With Me]]'' Channel 4 22 December 2010</ref> On 4 August 2011 it was announced on ''[[The Wright Stuff]]'' that she was pregnant. On Twitter, she announced the birth of her son, Luke, on 2 November 2011.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Year\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Information\n|-\n|<center>1994</center>\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Michelle Gayle (album)|Michelle Gayle]]'''''\n*Label: ([[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]])\n*Chart 