1 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Black British singers]]\n[[Category:British contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:English soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:Participants in British reality television series]]\n[[Category:Actresses from London]]\n[[Category:Black British actresses]]\n[[Category:English people of Saint Kitts and Nevis descent]]\n[[Category:English female pop singers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Barbara Speake Stage School]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelle_Gayle"}
{"title_page": "Penoscrotal transposition", "text_new": "'''Penoscrotal transposition'''(PST) is a group of congenital defects involving an [[Transposition (birth defect)|abnormal spatial arrangement]] of [[penis]] and [[scrotum]].\n== Types ==\nThere are two types of penoscrotal transposition.<ref>{{Cite journal |pmc = 4236992|year = 2014|last1 = Manjunath|first1 = K.|title = M-Plasty for Correction of Incomplete Penoscrotal Transposition|journal = World Journal of Plastic Surgery|volume = 3|issue = 2|pages = 138\u2013141|last2 = Venkatesh|first2 = M.|pmid = 25489538}}</ref>\n* Complete penoscrotal transposition\n* Incomplete penoscrotal transposition\n\nIn incomplete penoscrotal transposition, penis is located in the middle of the scrotum, but in complete transposition, penis is located in the perineum. <ref name=\"Turk J Obstet Gynecol\"> {{cite journal |pmc = 5558323|year = 2017 |last1=Beyaz\u0131t |first1= Fatma |last2=Pek |first2=Eren  |last3 =Aylan\u00e7 |first3= Hakan  |title= A rare case of complete penoscrotal transposition with hypospadias in a newborn |url= |journal= Turk J Obstet Gynecol.|issue= 14(1)|pages= 74-75|doi= 10.4274/tjod.88262|access-date=|pmid = 28913140}}</ref>\n== Cause ==\n\n== Treatment ==\nGold standard of PST treatment is surgical repair.<ref name=\"Turk J Obstet Gynecol\"/> Repair technique of penoscrotal transposition included a Glenn\u2013Anderson technique, which is developed by F. Glenn and E. Everett Anderson.<ref>https://www.researchgate.net/publication/18417427_Surgical_Correction_of_Incomplete_Penoscrotal_Transposition</ref><ref>https://www.auajournals.org/article/S0022-5347(05)65708-4/abstract</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Congenital malformations of urinary system}}\n{{Male congenital anomalies of genital organs}}{{Med-stub}}\n[[Category:Congenital disorders of urinary system]]\n[[Category:Congenital disorders of male genital organs]]\n[[Category:Penis]]\n", "text_old": "'''Penoscrotal transposition'''(PST) is a group of congenital defects involving an [[Transposition (birth defect)|abnormal spatial arrangement]] of [[penis]] and [[scrotum]].\n== Types ==\nThere are two types of penoscrotal transposition.<ref>{{Cite journal |pmc = 4236992|year = 2014|last1 = Manjunath|first1 = K.|title = M-Plasty for Correction of Incomplete Penoscrotal Transposition|journal = World Journal of Plastic Surgery|volume = 3|issue = 2|pages = 138\u2013141|last2 = Venkatesh|first2 = M.|pmid = 25489538}}</ref>\n* Complete penoscrotal transposition\n* Incomplete penoscrotal transposition\n\nIn incomplete penoscrotal transposition, penis is located in the middle of the scrotum, but in complete transposition, penis is located in the perineum. <ref name=\"Turk J Obstet Gynecol\"> {{cite journal |pmc = PMC5558323|year = 2017 |last1=Beyaz\u0131t |first1= Fatma |last2=Pek |first2=Eren  |last3 =Aylan\u00e7 |first3= Hakan  |title= A rare case of complete penoscrotal transposition with hypospadias in a newborn |url= |journal= Turk J Obstet Gynecol.|issue= 14(1)|pages= 74-75|doi= 10.4274/tjod.88262|access-date=|pmid = 28913140}}</ref>\n== Cause ==\n\n== Treatment ==\nGold standard of PST treatment is surgical repair.<ref name=\"Turk J Obstet Gynecol\"/> Repair technique of penoscrotal transposition included a Glenn\u2013Anderson technique, which is developed by F. Glenn and E. Everett Anderson.<ref>https://www.researchgate.net/publication/18417427_Surgical_Correction_of_Incomplete_Penoscrotal_Transposition</ref><ref>https://www.auajournals.org/article/S0022-5347(05)65708-4/abstract</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Congenital malformations of urinary system}}\n{{Male congenital anomalies of genital organs}}{{Med-stub}}\n[[Category:Congenital disorders of urinary system]]\n[[Category:Congenital disorders of male genital organs]]\n[[Category:Penis]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix PMC warnings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penoscrotal_transposition"}
{"title_page": "Ski-BASE jumping", "text_new": "{{Prose|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Ski jumping pictogram.svg|thumb|Ski-BASE Jumping involves free-falling through the air prior to releasing a parachute]]\n\n'''Ski-BASE jumping''' is the recreational sport of skiing at a high speed off of a cliff or mountain and free-falling through the air, using a parachute to descend to the ground. Ski-BASE jumping combines the two sports of [[skiing]] and [[BASE jumping]]. Participants often perform tricks or manoeuvres during the freefall and remove their skis mid-air in order to safely deploy the parachute and land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adventure.howstuffworks.com/outdoor-activities/snow-sports/extreme-skiing.htm|title=How Extreme Skiing Works|date=2009-10-05|website=HowStuffWorks|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Ski-BASE_Jumping_image.png|thumb|Ski-BASE Jumping - Glen Anderson]]\n\nSki-BASE jumping is different to other forms of parachuting or BASE jumping as it requires an advanced skiing ability alongside traditional BASE jumping skills. Such BASE jumps are largely executed in alpine conditions, and it is considered a highly dangerous [[Extreme sports|sport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/ez3yem/action-sports-after-death|title=Action Sports After Death|last=Rogge|first=Mike|date=2015-09-11|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== History and notable jumps ==\n\n* The first ski-BASE jump was performed by [[Rick Sylvester]] on January 30, 1972 at a cliff face located in Yosemite, El Capitan, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Story of the First Base Jump in Ski History|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> The jump location was situated 3,200 feet above the valley floor. The jump was filmed by a camera crew and featured within a film titled 'Earth Rider', which starred Sylvester's jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Story of the First Base Jump in Ski History|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n* In 1976, Sylvester performed another ski-BASE jump in [[Mount Asgard]], Canada as a stunt double in the July 1976 James Bond film '[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me']], starring Roger Moore. The stunt was completed only once due to bad weather, with a single camera successfully capturing suitable footage for the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/james-bond-spectre/best-stunts-stories-car-moments/|title=The 5 Best Bond Stunts \u2013 and the stories behind them|date=2015-10-08|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The stunt formed part of the opening scene of the film with a running time of 2 minutes 41 seconds.\n* In 2003, professional skier [[Shane McConkey]] ski-BASE jumped from the cliff 'Lover's Leap' in Lake Tahoe, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/episodes/history-of-ski-base-ultimate-rush-s01-e07|title=History of Ski-Base Ultimate Rush|last=|first=|date=|website=www.redbull.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> Later that year McConkey executed another ski-BASE jump in [[Bella Coola, British Columbia|Bella Coola]], British Columbia.<ref>{{Citation|title=History of Ski Base|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/episodes/history-of-ski-base-ultimate-rush-s01-e07|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n* On April 21, 2004, freestyle skiers Shane McConkey and J.T Holmes ski-BASE jumped from [[La Clusaz]], France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/episodes/history-of-ski-base-ultimate-rush-s01-e07|title=History of Ski Base Ultimate Rush|last=|first=|date=|website=www.redbull.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> McConkey and Holmes further pioneered the sport by ski-BASE jumping from the Eiger North Face, Switzerland in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.planetmountain.com/english/News/shownews1.lasso%3Fl%3D2%26keyid=43341|title=The Eiger jump by JT Holmes|website=PlanetMountain.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> McConkey performed a double-flip prior to releasing his parachute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d55f774c-30e2-11de-8196-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> This jump was featured in 2015 as part of the 60 Minutes documentary 'Taking on the Eiger'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/taking-on-the-eiger-anderson-cooper-60-minutes/|title=Taking on the Eiger|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* On February 25, 2007 Shane McConkey performed the first ski-BASE jump using a wingsuit at Gridsetskolten, Norway. This pioneered the sport of [[Wingsuit flying|'wingsuit]] ski-BASE jumping'.<ref>{{Citation|title=History of Ski Base|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/episodes/history-of-ski-base-ultimate-rush-s01-e07|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> During that year McConkey also ski-BASE jumped off of the [[Silver Legacy Resort & Casino|Silver Legacy]] Hotel in Reno, Nevada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2013/03/25/shane-mcconkey-movie-by-red-bull-matchstick-premieres-at-tribeca-fest/|title=Shane McConkey movie by Red Bull, Matchstick premieres at Tribeca Fest|date=2013-03-25|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n*In 2011, French skier [[Matthias Giraud]] executed a ski-BASE jump in the French Alps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/8498220/Skier-hurtles-off-cliff-followed-by-avalanche.html|title=Skier hurtles off cliff followed by avalanche|last=May 2011|first=6:00PM BST 06|date=2011-05-06|website=www.telegraph.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> During the jump, Giraud triggered an avalanche behind him. The jump was filmed by photographer Stefan Laude using GoPro Hero camera.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Auletta|first=Kate|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/matthias-giraud-extreme-s_n_852594|title=Matthias Giraud, Extreme Skier, Jumps Off Cliff, Films Avalanche (VIDEO)|date=2011-04-22|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> Giraud's achievements are listed on his website www.superfrenchie.com<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://superfrenchie.com/|title=Matthias \"Super Frenchie\" Giraud {{!}} Skiing & BASE Jumping|website=Super Frenchie|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> wherein he is accredited as the first person to: ski-BASE jump off [[Mount Hood|Mt Hood]] in Oregon, ski-BASE jump off Engineer Mountain in Silverton, Colorado, ski-BASE jump off [[Aiguille Croche]] in Megeve, France, ski-BASE jump off Ajax Peak in Telluride, Colorado, ski-BASE jump off Ingram Peak in Telluride, Colorado, ski-BASE jump off Petite Balm in Tignes, France, ski-BASE jump off [[Castle Rock, Colorado|Castle Rock]] in Durango, Colorado and ski-BASE jump off [[Pointe d'Areu|Point d'Areu]] in France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://superfrenchie.com/about/|title=About|website=Super Frenchie|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n*In 2011, professional BASE jumper Erik Roner performed the first ski-BASE jump in Macedonia. The jump is featured in Season 4 Episode 8 of the 'Behind the Line' series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freeskier.com/videos/macedonia-ski-base-jump-behind-line-season-4-episode-8|title=Macedonia Ski-BASE Jump - Behind The Line Season 4 Episode 8|date=2012-03-02|website=FREESKIER|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* In 2012, Red Bull Media House and Matchstick Productions released the documentary 'History of Ski Base' as part of the series [[Ultimate Rush]]. It was produced by Murray Wais and Steve Winter and has a running time of 23 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/shows/ultimate-rush|title=Ultimate Rush Red Bull Series|last=|first=|date=|website=www.redbull.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The episode primarily features ski-BASE jumpers Shane McConkey and J.T Holmes.\n*In 2014, professional freestyle skier [[Mike Wilson (skier)|Mike Wilson]] executed a ski-BASE jump from the [[Perrine Bridge]] in Twin Falls, Idaho, USA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jointheteem.com/friday-freakout-skydiving/friday-freakout-mike-wilson-mutiny-rail-slide-ski-base-jump/|title=Friday Freakout: Insane Ski Rail Slide To BASE Jump {{!}} TEEM|date=2014-01-10|website=TEEM {{!}} #JoinTheTeem|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> The jump was performed during summer and required ice to be imported in order to create the ramp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jointheteem.com/friday-freakout-skydiving/friday-freakout-mike-wilson-mutiny-rail-slide-ski-base-jump/|title=Friday Freakout: Insane Ski Rail Slide To BASE Jump {{!}} TEEM|date=2014-01-10|website=TEEM {{!}} #JoinTheTeem|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> Wilson performed a railing grind along the barrier of the bridge prior to the jump. He executed the jump twice, after slipping and falling the first time due to a technical error.<ref>{{Citation|title=Skiing + Bridge + Parachute = Outrageous BASE Jumps|url=https://video.nationalgeographic.com/video/passing-time/0000014e-5031-d37e-a7de-ffb1b5ae0000|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> The jump was filmed by company Stept Productions for the action film 'Mutiny'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snowbrains.com/friday-fun-mike-wilsons-railslide-base-jump/|title=Friday Fun: Mike Wilson\u2019s Railslide + BASE Jump|last=SnowBrains|date=2014-01-17|website=SnowBrains|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n* Norwegian freestyle skier [[Karina Hollekim]] is considered to be the first female to perform a ski-BASE jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pro-motivate.com/speaker/karina-hollekim/|title=Karina Hollekim Ski BASE Jumper By ProMotivate Speakers Agency|website=Promotivate|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Her father was a Norwegian ski instructor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Booth|first=Frances|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3634233/Karina-Hollekim-The-lady-who-can-fly.html|title=Karina Hollekim: The lady who can fly|date=2007-09-28|access-date=2020-02-14|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The American female skier Suz Graham is also currently recognized as one of the only active females to participate in the sport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://xgames.espn.com/article/9430525/suz-graham-world-lone-female-ski-base-jumper|title=Suz Graham is world's lone female ski BASE jumper.|website=X Games|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> Graham has performed over 25 ski-BASE jumps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1809216/catching-skier-and-base-jumper-suzanne-graham|title=Catching Up with Skier and BASE Jumper Suzanne Graham|date=2011-01-17|website=Outside Online|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> She has also featured as a stunt double performing a ski-BASE jump for the music video 'Winter Game' by Japanese band 'Girl Next Door'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1809216/catching-skier-and-base-jumper-suzanne-graham|title=Catching Up with Skier and BASE Jumper Suzanne Graham|date=2011-01-17|website=Outside Online|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* Alaskan athlete Pryce Brown ski-BASE jumped from the [[Stawamus Chief]], British Columbia in December 26, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://matadornetwork.com/life/ski-base-jumping-off-squamish-chief-might-craziest-thing-2015/|title=Ski BASE jumping off The Squamish Chief might the craziest thing of 2015|website=Matador Network|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The granite cliff is situated 2,303 feet above ground.\n*In March 2018, BASE jumpers Richard Grove, Mike Bickley and Miles Daisher ski-BASE jumped from the Rock Springs Buttress outside of [[Jackson Hole Mountain Resort]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/video/base-jump/watch-ski-base-jumpers-send-it-to-another-galaxy-off-the-rock-springs-buttr|title=Rock Springs Buttress Ski-Base Jump|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The jump was filmed by Tim Schwartz using GoPro and drone cameras.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/video/base-jump/watch-ski-base-jumpers-send-it-to-another-galaxy-off-the-rock-springs-buttr|title=Rock Springs Buttress Ski-Base Jump|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* French skier [[Matthias Giraud]] achieved the record of the highest ski-BASE jump on June 24, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snow-forecast.com/whiteroom/man-skis-off-mont-blanc-cliff-and-lives/|title=Man Skis Off Mont Blanc Cliff and Lives|date=2019-06-26|website=The Whiteroom|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Matthais skied from [[Mont Blanc]], situated in the Western European Alps and 4359 metres above sea level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackmail.ski/en/adventures/giraud-bases-the-mont-blanc/|title=Giraud bases the Mont Blanc|date=2019-08-06|website=the black mail|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n== Equipment ==\nSki-BASE jumping usually requires the following equipment:\n\n* Mountaineering tools to assist with reaching the slope. (A helicopter may also be used to access inaccessible areas)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theinertia.com/mountain/matthias-giraud-tried-to-ski-base-jump-off-the-matterhorn-and-it-went-horribly-wrong/|title=Matthias Giraud Tried to Ski-BASE Jump Off the Matterhorn and It Went Horribly Wrong|last=Mountain|first=The Inertia|website=The Inertia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* Ski equipment: skis, poles, helmet, clothing. The skiing equipment also often requires a specialised mechanism to allow the automatic release of the skis to prevent the skier becoming flipped upside down during free-fall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/action/freeskiing/blog/_/post/4021403|title=MSP: McConkey Never Threw His Chute|website=X Games|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* BASE jumping equipment: BASE container and BASE parachutes. BASE jumping typically involves a single parachute, as it is considered to be a safer and less complex system than accommodating a reserve parachute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asylumbase.com/pages/resources/faq/|title=Asylum Designs -|website=www.asylumbase.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> BASE containers are used to secure the parachute around the back of the participant and cost between $1000 and $1500 USD.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apexbase.com/product-category/containers/|title=BASE Jumping Containers: Summit, Summit Lite, TL2, DPw|website=Apex BASE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> BASE parachutes or canopies are eject from the container to assist with landing and cost over $2500 USD.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apexbase.com/product-category/canopies/|title=BASE Jumping Canopies: FLiK II, Lynx, Lobo, & Rook|website=Apex BASE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* In order to begin participating in ski-BASE jumping, interested participants usually are required to gain necessary skills by completing a number of skydives in order to learn to fly and a control a parachute. This allows for practicing using relevant equipment where the margin of error is greater than in a standard BASE jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asylumbase.com/pages/resources/faq/|title=Asylum Designs -|website=www.asylumbase.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Professional freestyle skier Max Kuszaj identifies the risks of wind resistance and weight of the skis during the jump in causing participants to flip around and make contact with the cliff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2009/2/19/20302758/base-jumping-on-skis-utah-is-haven-for-extreme-sport|title=BASE jumping on skis \u2014 Utah is haven for extreme sport|last=News|first=Deseret|date=2009-02-19|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n*Key manufacturing companies of ski-BASE jumping equipment include Apex Base, a Southern Californian organisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apexbase.com/about/|title=ABOUT|website=Apex BASE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Fatalities ==\n{{See also|Shane McConkey}}\n\nWhilst no studies have been performed concerning the mortality rate within the sport of ski-BASE jumping, a 2002 study of the fatality risk for BASE jumping estimates a death rate of 1 per 60 participants (Westman, Rosen, Beggren, Bjornstig 2008, p. 63).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301214219/http://bjsportmed.com/content/42/6/431.abstract|title=Parachuting from fixed objects: descriptive study of 106 fatal events in BASE jumping 1981\u20132006 -- Westman et al. 42 (6): 431 -- British Journal of Sports Medicine|date=2012-03-01|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Val Lasties exit.JPG|thumb|The site where Shane McConkey was fatally injured during a ski-BASE jump in 2009.]]\nFamous pioneer of ski-BASE jumping Shane McConkey died in an accident during a ski-BASE jump at the mountain Sass Pordoi in the [[Dolomites|Dolomites,]] Italy in 2009 when he was unable to release his skis before deploying his parachute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theinertia.com/inspired/the-gnarliest-line-ever-skied/|title=The Gnarliest Line Ever Skied|last=Carberry|first=Joe|website=The Inertia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> The mountain was 600 metres above ground level and located next to the renowned ski resort of Corvora. After performing a double-back flip from the cliff face, he was flipped upside down due to a technical issue with releasing his skis. McConkey was unable to release the parachute prior to reaching the ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d55f774c-30e2-11de-8196-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> He was 39 years old. McConkey had already BASE jumped the same cliff the year before and was yet to attempt a ski-BASE jump from the mountain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tahoequarterly.com/ski-ride-2018/shane-mcconkeys-lasting-legacy|title=Shane McConkey\u2019s Lasting Legacy|date=2018-10-05|website=Tahoe Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent documentary outlining his life and death was released in 2013, titled [[McConkey (film)|McConkey.]] The documentary premiered in April 2013 at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2013/03/25/shane-mcconkey-movie-by-red-bull-matchstick-premieres-at-tribeca-fest/|title=Shane McConkey movie by Red Bull, Matchstick premieres at Tribeca Fest|date=2013-03-25|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> In an interview recorded close to the time of his death, McConkey described his experience with ski-BASE jumping as 'I'm getting maximum enjoyment out of life and I'll never stop'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tahoequarterly.com/ski-ride-2018/shane-mcconkeys-lasting-legacy|title=Shane McConkey\u2019s Lasting Legacy|date=2018-10-05|website=Tahoe Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, professional freestyle skier Max Kuzsaj suffered near-fatal injuries during a ski-BASE jump at 'Echo' Mountain in Utah. He was hospitalised after being blown into the cliff during the jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2009/2/19/20302758/base-jumping-on-skis-utah-is-haven-for-extreme-sport|title=BASE jumping on skis \u2014 Utah is haven for extreme sport|last=News|first=Deseret|date=2009-02-19|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nNorwegian BASE jumper Egil Kulseth was killed after ski-BASE jumping from Holmenkollen ski jump in Oslo, Norway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-oslo-police-suspect-base-jumping-death-at-ski-jump-2014sep01-story.html|title=Oslo police suspect base jumping death at ski jump|date=2014-09-01|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nSki-BASE jumper Erik Roner also perished whilst performing a ski-BASE jump in Lake Tahoe, California in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2573261-erik-roner-action-sports-athlete-ski-base-jumper-dies-at-37|title=Erik Roner, Action Sports Athlete, Ski BASE Jumper, Dies at 39|last=Fitzgerald|first=Matt|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Roner was known for ski-BASE jumping from well-known locations including Cody Peak in [[Jackson Hole]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powder.com/stories/erik-roner-dies-in-parachuting-accident/|title=Erik Roner Dies in Parachuting Accident|date=2015-09-28|website=POWDER Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Legal issues ==\nThe primary legal issue of ski-BASE jumping is related to its the legality of performing such a jump within particular locations.\n\nThe application to perform the first ski-BASE jump by Rick Sylvester at the Yosemite Valley was rejected by National Park authorities who banned participants from using the space.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Story of the First Base Jump in Ski History|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> They illegally skied against the orders of the National Park in order to complete the jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Story of the First Base Jump in Ski History|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> The jump was performed at 11am on January 30, 1972 and required a helicopter to airlift the camera crew and skiers to the slope. A large orange banner had also been placed on the valley floor in order to mark the landing position for Rick Sylvester. Although the crew had been threatened with imprisonment prior to completing the stunt, they were never caught.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Insane Story Of Skiing\u2019s First BASE Jump - Hot Dog! The Legacy|last=Dietzel|first=Christian W.|website=www.tetongravity.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\nSince 1979, over 6,000 illegal jumps have been performed in and around the Yosemite National Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/page/Mag15lastbase/frank-gambalie-lived-died-base-jumping-espn-magazine-archives|title=The Mag Archive: Frank Gambalie lived, died for BASE jumping|date=2012-07-10|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\nSki-BASE Jumping is banned across all 55 US National Parks, with moderate fines enforced for trespassers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/page/Mag15lastbase/frank-gambalie-lived-died-base-jumping-espn-magazine-archives|title=The Mag Archive: Frank Gambalie lived, died for BASE jumping|date=2012-07-10|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Few places exist that allow ski-BASE jumps to be legally performed. Perrine Bridge in Twin Falls, Idaho is one of the only bridges within the USA that allows ski-BASE jumps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snowbrains.com/friday-fun-mike-wilsons-railslide-base-jump/|title=Friday Fun: Mike Wilson\u2019s Railslide + BASE Jump|last=SnowBrains|date=2014-01-17|website=SnowBrains|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> Utah, USA also contains various sites that ski-BASE jumps are able to be executed legally from, forming part of the Bureau of Land Management land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2009/2/19/20302758/base-jumping-on-skis-utah-is-haven-for-extreme-sport|title=BASE jumping on skis \u2014 Utah is haven for extreme sport|last=News|first=Deseret|date=2009-02-19|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> These sites include [[Little Cottonwood Canyon]], Albion Basin, [[Provo Canyon]] and [[Rock Canyon (Provo, Utah)|Rock Canyon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2009/2/19/20302758/base-jumping-on-skis-utah-is-haven-for-extreme-sport|title=BASE jumping on skis \u2014 Utah is haven for extreme sport|last=News|first=Deseret|date=2009-02-19|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nProfessional skier Matthias Giraud estimates that there are between 20 and 30 participants of ski-BASE jumping worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mensjournal.com/adventure/skiing-deadliest-mountains/|title=Skiing the Deadliest Mountains|date=2011-12-01|website=Men's Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\nThere are various films and documentaries that contain ski-BASE jumping. Some include:\n\n* [[McConkey (film)|McConkey]] (film)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mcconkeymovie.com/|title=McConkey {{!}} Now Available|website=McConkey {{!}} Now Available|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> was produced by [[Matchstick Productions]] and distributed by [[Red Bull]] Media House. It was released in 2013 and includes segments of interviews from famous athletes such as Tony Hawk. The documentary details the life and death of ski-BASE jumper [[Shane McConkey|Shane McConkey.]]\n\n* [[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]. The Spy Who Loved Me is a 1977 film directed by Lewis Gilbert and produced by Eon Productions. It featured [[Rick Sylvester]] performing a ski-BASE jump from [[Mount Asgard]], Canada as a stunt double for James Bond. The ski-BASE jump is included as part of the opening scene of the film.\n\n* History of Ski Base - Red Bull [[Ultimate Rush]] Season 1 Episode 7. The documentary episode is produced by Red Bull Media House and Matchstick Productions and focuses on the development of the ski-BASE jumping sport. The documentary notably focuses on the contributions of the two famous ski-BASE jumping participants JT Holmes and [[Shane McConkey]].\n\n* 60 Minutes - Taking on the Eiger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/taking-on-the-eiger-anderson-cooper-60-minutes/|title=Taking on the Eiger|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The 60 minutes documentary aired on November 29, 2015 and features ski-BASE jumper JT Holmes completing the first ski-BASE jump at the cliff face of the [[Eiger]], Switzerland.\n* In 2007, Shane McConkey re-enacted the ski-BASE jumping opening scene from the 1977 film [[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]] and published the recording online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d55f774c-30e2-11de-8196-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n*The first female to complete a ski-BASE jump, Karina Hollekim, starred in her biographical film '20 Seconds of Joy'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213232343/http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainculture/festivals/2007/film/awards/twenty_seconds_of_joy.asp|title=Banff Mountain Film Festival|date=2008-02-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> It contains footage of her ski-BASE jumping career and was screened at the 2007 Banff Mountain Film Festival. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213232343/http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainculture/festivals/2007/film/awards/twenty_seconds_of_joy.asp|title=Banff Mountain Film Festival|date=2008-02-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The film received the People's Choice Award against over 53 other finalist films and the Best Film on Mountainsports Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213232343/http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainculture/festivals/2007/film/awards/twenty_seconds_of_joy.asp|title=Banff Mountain Film Festival|date=2008-02-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The German film was directed by documentary filmmaker Jens Hoffmann and produced by Clenonice Comino, with a running time of 60 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213232343/http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainculture/festivals/2007/film/awards/twenty_seconds_of_joy.asp|title=Banff Mountain Film Festival|date=2008-02-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n*In 2012, media company Teton Gravity released a documentary featuring Erik Roner's ski-BASE jump in Macedonia, as part of the 2011 ski film 'One For the Road'. The documentary is featured within Season 4 Episode 8 of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/video/ski/Macedonia-Ski-B-A-S-E-Jump-Behind-The-Line-Season4-Epsiode8-1690957|title=Behind the Line Season 4 Episode 8 - Teton Gravity|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n*In 2014, Stept Productions created the action film 'Mutiny', featuring professional American freestyle skier [[Mike Wilson (skier)|Mike Wilson]] ski-BASE jumping from the [[Perrine Bridge]] in Idaho.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snowbrains.com/friday-fun-mike-wilsons-railslide-base-jump/|title=Friday Fun: Mike Wilson\u2019s Railslide + BASE Jump|last=SnowBrains|date=2014-01-17|website=SnowBrains|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==  See also ==\n* [[BASE jumping]]\n* [[Extreme skiing]]\n* [[Ski flying]]\n* [[Ski jumping]]\n* [[Shane McConkey]]\n* [[Rick Sylvester]]\n* [[Karina Hollekim]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Extreme Sports}} \n\n[[Category:Types of skiing]]\n[[Category:Jumping sports]]\n[[Category:Parachuting]]\n", "text_old": "{{Prose|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Ski jumping pictogram.svg|thumb|Ski-BASE Jumping involves free-falling through the air prior to releasing a parachute]]\n\n'''Ski-BASE jumping''' is the recreational sport of skiing at a high speed off of a cliff or mountain and free-falling through the air, using a parachute to descend to the ground. Ski-BASE jumping combines the two sports of [[skiing]] and [[BASE jumping]]. Participants often perform tricks or manoeuvres during the freefall and remove their skis mid-air in order to safely deploy the parachute and land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adventure.howstuffworks.com/outdoor-activities/snow-sports/extreme-skiing.htm|title=How Extreme Skiing Works|date=2009-10-05|website=HowStuffWorks|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Ski-BASE_Jumping_image.png|thumb|Ski-BASE Jumping - Glen Anderson]]\n\nSki-BASE jumping is different to other forms of parachuting or BASE jumping as it requires an advanced skiing ability alongside traditional BASE jumping skills. Such BASE jumps are largely executed in alpine conditions, and it is considered a highly dangerous [[Extreme sports|sport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/ez3yem/action-sports-after-death|title=Action Sports After Death|last=Rogge|first=Mike|date=2015-09-11|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== History and notable jumps ==\n\n* The first ski-BASE jump was performed by [[Rick Sylvester]] on January 30, 1972 at a cliff face located in Yosemite, El Capitan, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Story of the First Base Jump in Ski History|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> The jump location was situated 3,200 feet above the valley floor. The jump was filmed by a camera crew and featured within a film titled 'Earth Rider', which starred Sylvester's jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Story of the First Base Jump in Ski History|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n* In 1976, Sylvester performed another ski-BASE jump in [[Mount Asgard]], Canada as a stunt double in the July 1976 James Bond film '[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me']], starring Roger Moore. The stunt was completed only once due to bad weather, with a single camera successfully capturing suitable footage for the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/james-bond-spectre/best-stunts-stories-car-moments/|title=The 5 Best Bond Stunts \u2013 and the stories behind them|date=2015-10-08|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The stunt formed part of the opening scene of the film with a running time of 2 minutes 41 seconds.\n* In 2003, professional skier [[Shane McConkey]] ski-BASE jumped from the cliff 'Lover's Leap' in Lake Tahoe, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/episodes/history-of-ski-base-ultimate-rush-s01-e07|title=History of Ski-Base Ultimate Rush|last=|first=|date=|website=www.redbull.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> Later that year McConkey executed another ski-BASE jump in [[Bella Coola, British Columbia|Bella Coola]], British Columbia.<ref>{{Citation|title=History of Ski Base|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/episodes/history-of-ski-base-ultimate-rush-s01-e07|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n* On April 21, 2004, freestyle skiers Shane McConkey and J.T Holmes ski-BASE jumped from [[La Clusaz]], France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/episodes/history-of-ski-base-ultimate-rush-s01-e07|title=History of Ski Base Ultimate Rush|last=|first=|date=|website=www.redbull.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> McConkey and Holmes further pioneered the sport by ski-BASE jumping from the Eiger North Face, Switzerland in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.planetmountain.com/english/News/shownews1.lasso%3Fl%3D2%26keyid=43341|title=The Eiger jump by JT Holmes|website=PlanetMountain.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> McConkey performed a double-flip prior to releasing his parachute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d55f774c-30e2-11de-8196-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> This jump was featured in 2015 as part of the 60 Minutes documentary 'Taking on the Eiger'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/taking-on-the-eiger-anderson-cooper-60-minutes/|title=Taking on the Eiger|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* On February 25, 2007 Shane McConkey performed the first ski-BASE jump using a wingsuit at Gridsetskolten, Norway. This pioneered the sport of [[Wingsuit flying|'wingsuit]] ski-BASE jumping'.<ref>{{Citation|title=History of Ski Base|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/episodes/history-of-ski-base-ultimate-rush-s01-e07|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> During that year McConkey also ski-BASE jumped off of the [[Silver Legacy Resort & Casino|Silver Legacy]] Hotel in Reno, Nevada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2013/03/25/shane-mcconkey-movie-by-red-bull-matchstick-premieres-at-tribeca-fest/|title=Shane McConkey movie by Red Bull, Matchstick premieres at Tribeca Fest|date=2013-03-25|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n*In 2011, French skier [[Matthias Giraud]] executed a ski-BASE jump in the French Alps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/8498220/Skier-hurtles-off-cliff-followed-by-avalanche.html|title=Skier hurtles off cliff followed by avalanche|last=May 2011|first=6:00PM BST 06|date=2011-05-06|website=www.telegraph.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> During the jump, Giraud triggered an avalanche behind him. The jump was filmed by photographer Stefan Laude using GoPro Hero camera.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Auletta|first=Kate|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/matthias-giraud-extreme-s_n_852594|title=Matthias Giraud, Extreme Skier, Jumps Off Cliff, Films Avalanche (VIDEO)|date=2011-04-22|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> Giraud's achievements are listed on his website www.superfrenchie.com<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://superfrenchie.com/|title=Matthias \"Super Frenchie\" Giraud {{!}} Skiing & BASE Jumping|website=Super Frenchie|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> wherein he is accredited as the first person to: ski-BASE jump off [[Mount Hood|Mt Hood]] in Oregon, ski-BASE jump off Engineer Mountain in Silverton, Colorado, ski-BASE jump off [[Aiguille Croche]] in Megeve, France, ski-BASE jump off Ajax Peak in Telluride, Colorado, ski-BASE jump off Ingram Peak in Telluride, Colorado, ski-BASE jump off Petite Balm in Tignes, France, ski-BASE jump off [[Castle Rock, Colorado|Castle Rock]] in Durango, Colorado and ski-BASE jump off [[Pointe d'Areu|Point d'Areu]] in France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://superfrenchie.com/about/|title=About|website=Super Frenchie|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n*In 2011, professional BASE jumper Erik Roner performed the first ski-BASE jump in Macedonia. The jump is featured in Season 4 Episode 8 of the 'Behind the Line' series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freeskier.com/videos/macedonia-ski-base-jump-behind-line-season-4-episode-8|title=Macedonia Ski-BASE Jump - Behind The Line Season 4 Episode 8|date=2012-03-02|website=FREESKIER|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* In 2012, Red Bull Media House and Matchstick Productions released the documentary 'History of Ski Base' as part of the series [[Ultimate Rush]]. It was produced by Murray Wais and Steve Winter and has a running time of 23 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/shows/ultimate-rush|title=Ultimate Rush Red Bull Series|last=|first=|date=|website=www.redbull.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The episode primarily features ski-BASE jumpers Shane McConkey and J.T Holmes.\n*In 2014, professional freestyle skier [[Mike Wilson (skier)|Mike Wilson]] executed a ski-BASE jump from the [[Perrine Bridge]] in Twin Falls, Idaho, USA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jointheteem.com/friday-freakout-skydiving/friday-freakout-mike-wilson-mutiny-rail-slide-ski-base-jump/|title=Friday Freakout: Insane Ski Rail Slide To BASE Jump {{!}} TEEM|date=2014-01-10|website=TEEM {{!}} #JoinTheTeem|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> The jump was performed during summer and required ice to be imported in order to create the ramp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jointheteem.com/friday-freakout-skydiving/friday-freakout-mike-wilson-mutiny-rail-slide-ski-base-jump/|title=Friday Freakout: Insane Ski Rail Slide To BASE Jump {{!}} TEEM|date=2014-01-10|website=TEEM {{!}} #JoinTheTeem|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> Wilson performed a railing grind along the barrier of the bridge prior to the jump. He executed the jump twice, after slipping and falling the first time due to a technical error.<ref>{{Citation|title=Skiing + Bridge + Parachute = Outrageous BASE Jumps|url=https://video.nationalgeographic.com/video/passing-time/0000014e-5031-d37e-a7de-ffb1b5ae0000|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> The jump was filmed by company Stept Productions for the action film 'Mutiny'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snowbrains.com/friday-fun-mike-wilsons-railslide-base-jump/|title=Friday Fun: Mike Wilson\u2019s Railslide + BASE Jump|last=SnowBrains|date=2014-01-17|website=SnowBrains|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n* Norwegian freestyle skier [[Karina Hollekim]] is considered to be the first female to perform a ski-BASE jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pro-motivate.com/speaker/karina-hollekim/|title=Karina Hollekim Ski BASE Jumper By ProMotivate Speakers Agency|website=Promotivate|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Her father was a Norwegian ski instructor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Booth|first=Frances|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3634233/Karina-Hollekim-The-lady-who-can-fly.html|title=Karina Hollekim: The lady who can fly|date=2007-09-28|access-date=2020-02-14|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The American female skier Suz Graham is also currently recognized as one of the only active females to participate in the sport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://xgames.espn.com/article/9430525/suz-graham-world-lone-female-ski-base-jumper|title=Suz Graham is world's lone female ski BASE jumper.|website=X Games|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> Graham has performed over 25 ski-BASE jumps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1809216/catching-skier-and-base-jumper-suzanne-graham|title=Catching Up with Skier and BASE Jumper Suzanne Graham|date=2011-01-17|website=Outside Online|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> She has also featured as a stunt double performing a ski-BASE jump for the music video 'Winter Game' by Japanese band 'Girl Next Door'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1809216/catching-skier-and-base-jumper-suzanne-graham|title=Catching Up with Skier and BASE Jumper Suzanne Graham|date=2011-01-17|website=Outside Online|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* Alaskan athlete Pryce Brown ski-BASE jumped from the [[Stawamus Chief]], British Columbia in December 26, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://matadornetwork.com/life/ski-base-jumping-off-squamish-chief-might-craziest-thing-2015/|title=Ski BASE jumping off The Squamish Chief might the craziest thing of 2015|website=Matador Network|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The granite cliff is situated 2,303 feet above ground.\n*In March 2018, BASE jumpers Richard Grove, Mike Bickley and Miles Daisher ski-BASE jumped from the Rock Springs Buttress outside of [[Jackson Hole Mountain Resort]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/video/base-jump/watch-ski-base-jumpers-send-it-to-another-galaxy-off-the-rock-springs-buttr|title=Rock Springs Buttress Ski-Base Jump|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The jump was filmed by Tim Schwartz using GoPro and drone cameras.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/video/base-jump/watch-ski-base-jumpers-send-it-to-another-galaxy-off-the-rock-springs-buttr|title=Rock Springs Buttress Ski-Base Jump|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* French skier [[Matthias Giraud]] achieved the record of the highest ski-BASE jump on June 24, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snow-forecast.com/whiteroom/man-skis-off-mont-blanc-cliff-and-lives/|title=Man Skis Off Mont Blanc Cliff and Lives|date=2019-06-26|website=The Whiteroom|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Matthais skied from [[Mont Blanc]], situated in the Western European Alps and 4359 metres above sea level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackmail.ski/en/adventures/giraud-bases-the-mont-blanc/|title=Giraud bases the Mont Blanc|date=2019-08-06|website=the black mail|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n== Equipment ==\nSki-BASE jumping usually requires the following equipment:\n\n* Mountaineering tools to assist with reaching the slope. (A helicopter may also be used to access inaccessible areas)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theinertia.com/mountain/matthias-giraud-tried-to-ski-base-jump-off-the-matterhorn-and-it-went-horribly-wrong/|title=Matthias Giraud Tried to Ski-BASE Jump Off the Matterhorn and It Went Horribly Wrong|last=Mountain|first=The Inertia|website=The Inertia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* Ski equipment: skis, poles, helmet, clothing. The skiing equipment also often requires a specialised mechanism to allow the automatic release of the skis to prevent the skier becoming flipped upside down during free-fall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/action/freeskiing/blog/_/post/4021403|title=MSP: McConkey Never Threw His Chute|website=X Games|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* BASE jumping equipment: BASE container and BASE parachutes. BASE jumping typically involves a single parachute, as it is considered to be a safer and less complex system than accomodating a reserve parachute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asylumbase.com/pages/resources/faq/|title=Asylum Designs -|website=www.asylumbase.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> BASE containers are used to secure the parachute around the back of the participant and cost between $1000 and $1500 USD.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apexbase.com/product-category/containers/|title=BASE Jumping Containers: Summit, Summit Lite, TL2, DPw|website=Apex BASE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> BASE parachutes or canopies are eject from the container to assist with landing and cost over $2500 USD.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apexbase.com/product-category/canopies/|title=BASE Jumping Canopies: FLiK II, Lynx, Lobo, & Rook|website=Apex BASE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n* In order to begin participating in ski-BASE jumping, interested participants usually are required to gain necessary skills by completing a number of skydives in order to learn to fly and a control a parachute. This allows for practicing using relevant equipment where the margin of error is greater than in a standard BASE jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asylumbase.com/pages/resources/faq/|title=Asylum Designs -|website=www.asylumbase.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Professional freestyle skier Max Kuszaj identifies the risks of wind resistance and weight of the skis during the jump in causing participants to flip around and make contact with the cliff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2009/2/19/20302758/base-jumping-on-skis-utah-is-haven-for-extreme-sport|title=BASE jumping on skis \u2014 Utah is haven for extreme sport|last=News|first=Deseret|date=2009-02-19|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n*Key manufacturing companies of ski-BASE jumping equipment include Apex Base, a Southern Californian organisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apexbase.com/about/|title=ABOUT|website=Apex BASE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Fatalities ==\n{{See also|Shane McConkey}}\n\nWhilst no studies have been performed concerning the mortality rate within the sport of ski-BASE jumping, a 2002 study of the fatality risk for BASE jumping estimates a death rate of 1 per 60 participants (Westman, Rosen, Beggren, Bjornstig 2008, p. 63).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301214219/http://bjsportmed.com/content/42/6/431.abstract|title=Parachuting from fixed objects: descriptive study of 106 fatal events in BASE jumping 1981\u20132006 -- Westman et al. 42 (6): 431 -- British Journal of Sports Medicine|date=2012-03-01|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Val Lasties exit.JPG|thumb|The site where Shane McConkey was fatally injured during a ski-BASE jump in 2009.]]\nFamous pioneer of ski-BASE jumping Shane McConkey died in an accident during a ski-BASE jump at the mountain Sass Pordoi in the [[Dolomites|Dolomites,]] Italy in 2009 when he was unable to release his skis before deploying his parachute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theinertia.com/inspired/the-gnarliest-line-ever-skied/|title=The Gnarliest Line Ever Skied|last=Carberry|first=Joe|website=The Inertia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> The mountain was 600 metres above ground level and located next to the renowned ski resort of Corvora. After performing a double-back flip from the cliff face, he was flipped upside down due to a technical issue with releasing his skis. McConkey was unable to release the parachute prior to reaching the ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d55f774c-30e2-11de-8196-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> He was 39 years old. McConkey had already BASE jumped the same cliff the year before and was yet to attempt a ski-BASE jump from the mountain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tahoequarterly.com/ski-ride-2018/shane-mcconkeys-lasting-legacy|title=Shane McConkey\u2019s Lasting Legacy|date=2018-10-05|website=Tahoe Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent documentary outlining his life and death was released in 2013, titled [[McConkey (film)|McConkey.]] The documentary premiered in April 2013 at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2013/03/25/shane-mcconkey-movie-by-red-bull-matchstick-premieres-at-tribeca-fest/|title=Shane McConkey movie by Red Bull, Matchstick premieres at Tribeca Fest|date=2013-03-25|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> In an interview recorded close to the time of his death, McConkey described his experience with ski-BASE jumping as 'I'm getting maximum enjoyment out of life and I'll never stop'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tahoequarterly.com/ski-ride-2018/shane-mcconkeys-lasting-legacy|title=Shane McConkey\u2019s Lasting Legacy|date=2018-10-05|website=Tahoe Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, professional freestyle skier Max Kuzsaj suffered near-fatal injuries during a ski-BASE jump at 'Echo' Mountain in Utah. He was hospitalised after being blown into the cliff during the jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2009/2/19/20302758/base-jumping-on-skis-utah-is-haven-for-extreme-sport|title=BASE jumping on skis \u2014 Utah is haven for extreme sport|last=News|first=Deseret|date=2009-02-19|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nNorwegian BASE jumper Egil Kulseth was killed after ski-BASE jumping from Holmenkollen ski jump in Oslo, Norway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-oslo-police-suspect-base-jumping-death-at-ski-jump-2014sep01-story.html|title=Oslo police suspect base jumping death at ski jump|date=2014-09-01|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nSki-BASE jumper Erik Roner also perished whilst performing a ski-BASE jump in Lake Tahoe, California in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2573261-erik-roner-action-sports-athlete-ski-base-jumper-dies-at-37|title=Erik Roner, Action Sports Athlete, Ski BASE Jumper, Dies at 39|last=Fitzgerald|first=Matt|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Roner was known for ski-BASE jumping from well-known locations including Cody Peak in [[Jackson Hole]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.powder.com/stories/erik-roner-dies-in-parachuting-accident/|title=Erik Roner Dies in Parachuting Accident|date=2015-09-28|website=POWDER Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Legal issues ==\nThe primary legal issue of ski-BASE jumping is related to its the legality of performing such a jump within particular locations.\n\nThe application to perform the first ski-BASE jump by Rick Sylvester at the Yosemite Valley was rejected by National Park authorities who banned participants from using the space.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Story of the First Base Jump in Ski History|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> They illegally skied against the orders of the National Park in order to complete the jump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Story of the First Base Jump in Ski History|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> The jump was performed at 11am on January 30, 1972 and required a helicopter to airlift the camera crew and skiers to the slope. A large orange banner had also been placed on the valley floor in order to mark the landing position for Rick Sylvester. Although the crew had been threatened with imprisonment prior to completing the stunt, they were never caught.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/story/ski/hot-dog-the-legacy-the-story-of-the-first-base-jump-in-ski-history|title=The Insane Story Of Skiing\u2019s First BASE Jump - Hot Dog! The Legacy|last=Dietzel|first=Christian W.|website=www.tetongravity.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\nSince 1979, over 6,000 illegal jumps have been performed in and around the Yosemite National Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/page/Mag15lastbase/frank-gambalie-lived-died-base-jumping-espn-magazine-archives|title=The Mag Archive: Frank Gambalie lived, died for BASE jumping|date=2012-07-10|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\nSki-BASE Jumping is banned across all 55 US National Parks, with moderate fines enforced for trespassers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/page/Mag15lastbase/frank-gambalie-lived-died-base-jumping-espn-magazine-archives|title=The Mag Archive: Frank Gambalie lived, died for BASE jumping|date=2012-07-10|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Few places exist that allow ski-BASE jumps to be legally performed. Perrine Bridge in Twin Falls, Idaho is one of the only bridges within the USA that allows ski-BASE jumps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snowbrains.com/friday-fun-mike-wilsons-railslide-base-jump/|title=Friday Fun: Mike Wilson\u2019s Railslide + BASE Jump|last=SnowBrains|date=2014-01-17|website=SnowBrains|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> Utah, USA also contains various sites that ski-BASE jumps are able to be executed legally from, forming part of the Bureau of Land Management land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2009/2/19/20302758/base-jumping-on-skis-utah-is-haven-for-extreme-sport|title=BASE jumping on skis \u2014 Utah is haven for extreme sport|last=News|first=Deseret|date=2009-02-19|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> These sites include [[Little Cottonwood Canyon]], Albion Basin, [[Provo Canyon]] and [[Rock Canyon (Provo, Utah)|Rock Canyon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseret.com/2009/2/19/20302758/base-jumping-on-skis-utah-is-haven-for-extreme-sport|title=BASE jumping on skis \u2014 Utah is haven for extreme sport|last=News|first=Deseret|date=2009-02-19|website=Deseret News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nProfessional skier Matthias Giraud estimates that there are between 20 and 30 participants of ski-BASE jumping worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mensjournal.com/adventure/skiing-deadliest-mountains/|title=Skiing the Deadliest Mountains|date=2011-12-01|website=Men's Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\nThere are various films and documentaries that contain ski-BASE jumping. Some include:\n\n* [[McConkey (film)|McConkey]] (film)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mcconkeymovie.com/|title=McConkey {{!}} Now Available|website=McConkey {{!}} Now Available|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> was produced by [[Matchstick Productions]] and distributed by [[Red Bull]] Media House. It was released in 2013 and includes segments of interviews from famous athletes such as Tony Hawk. The documentary details the life and death of ski-BASE jumper [[Shane McConkey|Shane McConkey.]]\n\n* [[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]. The Spy Who Loved Me is a 1977 film directed by Lewis Gilbert and produced by Eon Productions. It featured [[Rick Sylvester]] performing a ski-BASE jump from [[Mount Asgard]], Canada as a stunt double for James Bond. The ski-BASE jump is included as part of the opening scene of the film.\n\n* History of Ski Base - Red Bull [[Ultimate Rush]] Season 1 Episode 7. The documentary episode is produced by Red Bull Media House and Matchstick Productions and focuses on the development of the ski-BASE jumping sport. The documentary notably focuses on the contributions of the two famous ski-BASE jumping participants JT Holmes and [[Shane McConkey]].\n\n* 60 Minutes - Taking on the Eiger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/taking-on-the-eiger-anderson-cooper-60-minutes/|title=Taking on the Eiger|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The 60 minutes documentary aired on November 29, 2015 and features ski-BASE jumper JT Holmes completing the first ski-BASE jump at the cliff face of the [[Eiger]], Switzerland.\n* In 2007, Shane McConkey re-enacted the ski-BASE jumping opening scene from the 1977 film [[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]] and published the recording online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d55f774c-30e2-11de-8196-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n*The first female to complete a ski-BASE jump, Karina Hollekim, starred in her biographical film '20 Seconds of Joy'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213232343/http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainculture/festivals/2007/film/awards/twenty_seconds_of_joy.asp|title=Banff Mountain Film Festival|date=2008-02-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> It contains footage of her ski-BASE jumping career and was screened at the 2007 Banff Mountain Film Festival. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213232343/http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainculture/festivals/2007/film/awards/twenty_seconds_of_joy.asp|title=Banff Mountain Film Festival|date=2008-02-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The film received the People's Choice Award against over 53 other finalist films and the Best Film on Mountainsports Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213232343/http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainculture/festivals/2007/film/awards/twenty_seconds_of_joy.asp|title=Banff Mountain Film Festival|date=2008-02-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The German film was directed by documentary filmmaker Jens Hoffmann and produced by Clenonice Comino, with a running time of 60 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213232343/http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainculture/festivals/2007/film/awards/twenty_seconds_of_joy.asp|title=Banff Mountain Film Festival|date=2008-02-13|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n*In 2012, media company Teton Gravity released a documentary featuring Erik Roner's ski-BASE jump in Macedonia, as part of the 2011 ski film 'One For the Road'. The documentary is featured within Season 4 Episode 8 of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tetongravity.com/video/ski/Macedonia-Ski-B-A-S-E-Jump-Behind-The-Line-Season4-Epsiode8-1690957|title=Behind the Line Season 4 Episode 8 - Teton Gravity|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tetongravity.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n*In 2014, Stept Productions created the action film 'Mutiny', featuring professional American freestyle skier [[Mike Wilson (skier)|Mike Wilson]] ski-BASE jumping from the [[Perrine Bridge]] in Idaho.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://snowbrains.com/friday-fun-mike-wilsons-railslide-base-jump/|title=Friday Fun: Mike Wilson\u2019s Railslide + BASE Jump|last=SnowBrains|date=2014-01-17|website=SnowBrains|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==  See also ==\n* [[BASE jumping]]\n* [[Extreme skiing]]\n* [[Ski flying]]\n* [[Ski jumping]]\n* [[Shane McConkey]]\n* [[Rick Sylvester]]\n* [[Karina Hollekim]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Extreme Sports}} \n\n[[Category:Types of skiing]]\n[[Category:Jumping sports]]\n[[Category:Parachuting]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ski-BASE_jumping"}
{"title_page": "Galmudug Security Force", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Galmudug Security Force\n| native_name =\n| image =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| dates = 2006-present\n| country = {{flag|Somalia}}\n* {{flag|Galmudug}}\n| countries =\n| allegiance =\n| branch =\n| type = [[Law enforcement agency|Law enforcement]], [[Counter-Terrorism]]\n| role =\n| size = 5,754 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://amisom-au.org/2019/02/amisom-hands-over-operational-readiness-assessment-findings-to-the-somali-government//|title=AMISOM hands over Operational Readiness Assessment findings to the Somali government|publisher=Amisom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/harunmaruf/status/1111749993214459904?s=21/|title=The New study ORA|publisher=harun maruf}}</ref>\n| command_structure =\n| garrison =[[Dhusamareb]]\n| garrison_label =\n| nickname = GSF\n| patron =\n| motto =\n| colors = <!-- or | colours = -->\n| colors_label = <!-- or | colours_label = -->\n| march =\n| mascot =\n| anniversaries = 14 October \n| equipment =\n| equipment_label =\n| battles = [[Battle of Bandiradley]]<br>[[Somalia War (2006\u20132009)]]<br>[[Anti-piracy measures in Somalia]]\n| decorations =\n| battle_honours =\n| battle_honours_label =\n| disbanded =\n| flying_hours =\n| website =\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander = General [[Hassan Farah Kaarshe]]<ref>http://mudug24.com/2017/02/16/dhageyso-taliyaha-ugu-sareeya-daraawiishta-galmudug-oo-kasoo-horjeestay-ciidanka-duulaanka-ku-ah-xarar-dheere/</ref>\n| commander1 =\n| commander1_label =\n| commander2 =\n| commander2_label =\n| commander3 =\n| commander3_label =\n| commander4 =\n| commander4_label =\n| commander5 =\n| commander5_label =\n| commander6 =\n| commander6_label =\n| commander7 =\n| commander7_label =\n| commander8 =\n| commander8_label =\n| commander9 =\n| commander9_label =\n| notable_commanders =\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol =\n| identification_symbol_label =\n| identification_symbol_2 =\n| identification_symbol_2_label =\n| identification_symbol_3 =\n| identification_symbol_3_label =\n| identification_symbol_4 =\n| identification_symbol_4_label =\n| identification_symbol_5 =\n| identification_symbol_5_label =\n<!-- Aircraft -->\n| aircraft_attack =\n| aircraft_bomber =\n| aircraft_electronic =\n| aircraft_fighter =\n| aircraft_helicopter =\n| aircraft_helicopter_attack =\n| aircraft_helicopter_cargo =\n| aircraft_helicopter_multirole =\n| aircraft_helicopter_observation =\n| aircraft_helicopter_transport =\n| aircraft_helicopter_trainer =\n| aircraft_helicopter_utility =\n| aircraft_interceptor =\n| aircraft_patrol =\n| aircraft_recon =\n| aircraft_trainer =\n| aircraft_transport =\n| aircraft_tanker =\n| aircraft_general =\n}}\n\nThe '''Galmudug Security Force''' ('''GSF''') consists of the [[armed forces]] of the autonomous [[Galmudug]] region in central [[Somalia]]. \n\nAccording to operational readiness assessment carried out in [[Galmudug]], [[Puntland]], [[Jubaland]] and [[South West State of Somalia]] conducted by amisom team who were sent by the federal government of Somalia to carry out a new study on the regional forces, Galmudug has the largest regional forces with the heaviest weaponry including tanks and anti-tanks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amisom-au.org/2019/02/amisom-hands-over-operational-readiness-assessment-findings-to-the-somali-government//|title=AMISOM hands over Operational Readiness Assessment findings to the Somali government|publisher=Amisom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/harunmaruf/status/1111752149812371458?s=21/|title= Operational readiness assessment |publisher=Harun maruf}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 14 August 2006, Galmudug declared autonomy in central [[Somalia]] thus establishing its own security force. On 23 December 2006, the newly formed security forces took part of the [[Battle of Bandiradley]] led by [[Abdi Hasan Awale Qeybdiid|Colonel Abdi Qeybdiid]] alongside Ethiopian and [[Puntland]] forces. Galmudug was one of the principle opponents of the [[Islamic Courts Union]] till the ICU was dissolved on 27 December 2006.<ref name=\"SIFAEBMCIB\">{{cite web |title= SIFAEBMCIB |url= http://www.shabelle.net/news/ne1825.htm |publisher= web.archive.org |accessdate= 9 August 2017 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200541/http://www.shabelle.net/news/ne1825.htm |archivedate= 27 September 2007 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> On 18 January 2018, [[Ahlu Sunna Waljama'a|Ahlu Sunna]] merged its forces and administration into Galmudug State's regional government and security forces.<ref>http://radiodalsan.com/en/aswj-galmudug-merger-will-boost-war-on-alshabaab-farmaajo-says/{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Galmudug Darawish Force==\n[[File:GalmudugSecurityForce.jpeg|thumb|A platoon in marching in [[Dhusamareb]].]]\nGalmudug Darawish Force are military units that operate under the sole authority of Galmudug state government. They are under the command of the [[List of Presidents of Galmudug|Galmudug state President]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hornobserver.com/articles/238/Galmudug-Statement-on-the-American-Airstrike-against-its-armed-forces|title=Galmudug Statement on the American Airstrike against its armed forces|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://radioshabelle.com/galmudug-puntland-trade-blames-mudug-conflict/|title=Galmudug And Puntland States Trade Blames Over Mudug Conflict|publisher=}}</ref> Galmudug Darawish Force is the Main force that is keeping [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]] militants at bay in central [[Somalia]]. \n\n[[File:CapturedASchildsoldiers.jpeg|thumb|right|Captured [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]] child soldiers.]]\nOn March 2016, Galmudug Darawish Force engaged in a intensive fighting against Al-Shabaab militia who fled from Puntland areas. The fighting which lasted 4 days resulted in Galmudug Darawish Force killing  115 militants and capturing 110 militants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://somaliupdate.com/articles/8385/SOMALIA-Galmudug-Declares-115-Al-Shabaab-Militants-Killed-Operation-Concluded|title=SOMALIA: Galmudug Declares 115 Al-Shabaab Militants Killed, Operation Concluded|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://somaliagenda.com/galmudug-declares-concluded-fight-al-shabaab-militia-fled-puntland-areas/|title=GALMUDUG DECLARES THAT IT CONCLUDED THE FIGHT AGAINST AL-SHABAAB MILITIA THAT FLED FROM PUNTLAND AREAS|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Galmudug Police Force==\nThe Galmudug Security Force operates its own [[Police Force]].<ref name=\"SGHOAAMTP\">{{cite web |title=SGHOAAMTP |url= http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/02/somalia-galmudug-hands-over-arrested-al-shabab-member-to-puntland/ |publisher= www.raxanreeb.com |accessdate= 9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Galmudug Maritime Force==\nThe Galmudug Maritime Force's responsibility is safeguarding Somalia's marine resources from [[Piracy in Somalia|piracy]], [[illegal fishing]], and any other illegal activity off of the coast of Somalia.<ref name=\"GFNP\">{{cite web |title=GFNP |url= http://www.marsecreview.com/2017/04/galmudug-forces-nab-pirates/ |publisher= www.marsecreview.com |accessdate= 15 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nGalmudug maritime Force have been receiving multiple training courses from the [[European Union]] and [[NATO]] Anti-piracy Force. \n\nOn 10 October 2017, Dutch and Swedish sailors on board [[HNLMS Rotterdam (L800)|HNLMS Rotterdam]] have conducted medical training with local Galmudug Security Forces. The local interaction was in support of a mutual partnership to improve maritime skills.\n\nOn completion of the medical training, members of the Galmudug Maritime Force were presented with certificates during an upper deck ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eunavfor.eu/dutch-and-swedish-sailors-train-galmadug-coast-guard/|title=Dutch and Swedish Sailors Train Galmudug Security Forces|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 October 2017, another unit of Galmudug maritime force received medical and security training from the Spanish sailors on board EU Naval Force ship [[Spanish patrol vessel Rayo (P-42)|ESPS Rayo]] in order to strengthen maritime security in the region. The two teams then got to work on engine maintenance drills before meeting with local Security Forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eunavfor.eu/esps-rayo-welcomes-galmadug-coast-guard/|title=ESPS Rayo welcomes Galmudug Security Forces|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==National Intelligence and Security Agency==\nThe National Intelligence and Security Agency (NISA) is Somalia's National Intelligence And Security Agency, it has a branch in Galmudug state where it provides intelligence services for the Galmudug security force and sometimes works alongside them.<ref name=\"GANFFANVTEM\">{{Cite web |title= GANFFANVTEM |url= http://nepjournal.com/galmudug-and-nisa-forces-foil-attack-nab-vehicle-transporting-explosive-materials/ |publisher= nepjournal.com |accessdate= 15 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Military of Somalia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Galmudug]]\n[[Category:Military of Somalia]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Somalia]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2006]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Galmudug Security Force\n| native_name =\n| image =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| dates = 2006-present\n| country = {{flag|Somalia}}\n* {{flag|Galmudug}}\n| countries =\n| allegiance =\n| branch =\n| type = \n| role =\n| size = \n| command_structure =\n| garrison =[[Dhusamareb]]\n| garrison_label =\n| nickname = \n| patron =\n| motto =\n| colors = <!-- or | colours = -->\n| colors_label = <!-- or | colours_label = -->\n| march =\n| mascot =\n| anniversaries = \n| equipment =\n| equipment_label =\n| battles = [[Battle of Bandiradley]]<br>[[Somalia War (2006\u20132009)]]<br>[[Anti-piracy measures in Somalia]]\n| decorations =\n| battle_honours =\n| battle_honours_label =\n| disbanded =\n| flying_hours =\n| website =\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander = General [[Hassan Farah Kaarshe]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://mudug24.com/2017/02/16/dhageyso-taliyaha-ugu-sareeya-daraawiishta-galmudug-oo-kasoo-horjeestay-ciidanka-duulaanka-ku-ah-xarar-dheere/ | title=Dhageyso Taliyaha ugu sareeya Daraawiishta Galmudug oo kasoo horjeestay Ciidanka Duulaanka ku ah Xarar-dheere.. | date=16 February 2017 | publisher=Mudug24 | accessdate=26 January 2020 }}</ref>\n| commander1 =\n| commander1_label =\n| commander2 =\n| commander2_label =\n| commander3 =\n| commander3_label =\n| commander4 =\n| commander4_label =\n| commander5 =\n| commander5_label =\n| commander6 =\n| commander6_label =\n| commander7 =\n| commander7_label =\n| commander8 =\n| commander8_label =\n| commander9 =\n| commander9_label =\n| notable_commanders =\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol =\n| identification_symbol_label =\n| identification_symbol_2 =\n| identification_symbol_2_label =\n| identification_symbol_3 =\n| identification_symbol_3_label =\n| identification_symbol_4 =\n| identification_symbol_4_label =\n| identification_symbol_5 =\n| identification_symbol_5_label =\n}}\nThe '''Galmudug Security Force''' ('''GSF''') consists of the [[armed forces]] of the autonomous [[Galmudug]] region in central [[Somalia]]. \n\nAccording to operational readiness assessment carried out in [[Galmudug]], [[Puntland]], [[Jubaland]] and [[South West State of Somalia]] conducted by amisom team who were sent by the federal government of Somalia to carry out a new study on the regional forces, Galmudug has the largest regional forces with the heaviest weaponry including tanks and anti-tanks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amisom-au.org/2019/02/amisom-hands-over-operational-readiness-assessment-findings-to-the-somali-government//|title=AMISOM hands over Operational Readiness Assessment findings to the Somali government|publisher=Amisom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/harunmaruf/status/1111752149812371458?s=21/|title= Operational readiness assessment |publisher=Harun maruf}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 14 August 2006, Galmudug declared autonomy in central [[Somalia]] thus establishing its own security force. On 23 December 2006, the newly formed security forces took part of the [[Battle of Bandiradley]] led by [[Abdi Hasan Awale Qeybdiid|Colonel Abdi Qeybdiid]] alongside Ethiopian and [[Puntland]] forces. Galmudug was one of the principle opponents of the [[Islamic Courts Union]] till the ICU was dissolved on 27 December 2006.<ref name=\"SIFAEBMCIB\">{{cite web |title= SIFAEBMCIB |url= http://www.shabelle.net/news/ne1825.htm |publisher= web.archive.org |accessdate= 9 August 2017 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200541/http://www.shabelle.net/news/ne1825.htm |archivedate= 27 September 2007 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> On 18 January 2018, [[Ahlu Sunna Waljama'a|Ahlu Sunna]] merged its forces and administration into Galmudug State's regional government and security forces.<ref>http://radiodalsan.com/en/aswj-galmudug-merger-will-boost-war-on-alshabaab-farmaajo-says/{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nA 2019 AMISOM Operational Readiness Assessment counted 5,754<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amisom-au.org/2019/02/amisom-hands-over-operational-readiness-assessment-findings-to-the-somali-government//|title=AMISOM hands over Operational Readiness Assessment findings to the Somali government|publisher=Amisom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/harunmaruf/status/1111749993214459904?s=21/|title=The New study ORA|publisher=harun maruf}}</ref> 'regional fighters' in Galmudug. \n\n==Galmudug Darawish Force==\n[[File:GalmudugSecurityForce.jpeg|thumb|A platoon in marching in [[Dhusamareb]].]]\nGalmudug Darawish Force are military units that operate under the sole authority of Galmudug state government. They are under the command of the [[List of Presidents of Galmudug|Galmudug state President]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hornobserver.com/articles/238/Galmudug-Statement-on-the-American-Airstrike-against-its-armed-forces|title=Galmudug Statement on the American Airstrike against its armed forces|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://radioshabelle.com/galmudug-puntland-trade-blames-mudug-conflict/|title=Galmudug And Puntland States Trade Blames Over Mudug Conflict|publisher=}}</ref> Galmudug Darawish Force is the Main force that is keeping [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]] militants at bay in central [[Somalia]]. \n\n[[File:CapturedASchildsoldiers.jpeg|thumb|right|Captured [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]] child soldiers.]]\nOn March 2016, Galmudug Darawish Force engaged in a intensive fighting against Al-Shabaab militia who fled from Puntland areas. The fighting which lasted 4 days resulted in Galmudug Darawish Force killing  115 militants and capturing 110 militants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://somaliupdate.com/articles/8385/SOMALIA-Galmudug-Declares-115-Al-Shabaab-Militants-Killed-Operation-Concluded|title=SOMALIA: Galmudug Declares 115 Al-Shabaab Militants Killed, Operation Concluded|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://somaliagenda.com/galmudug-declares-concluded-fight-al-shabaab-militia-fled-puntland-areas/|title=GALMUDUG DECLARES THAT IT CONCLUDED THE FIGHT AGAINST AL-SHABAAB MILITIA THAT FLED FROM PUNTLAND AREAS|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Galmudug Police Force==\nThe Galmudug Security Force operates its own [[Police Force]].<ref name=\"SGHOAAMTP\">{{cite web |title=SGHOAAMTP |url= http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/02/somalia-galmudug-hands-over-arrested-al-shabab-member-to-puntland/ |publisher= www.raxanreeb.com |accessdate= 9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Training with Europeans ==\nThe Galmudug Security Force have been receiving multiple training courses from the [[European Union]] and [[NATO]] Anti-piracy Force. \n\nOn 10 October 2017, Dutch and Swedish sailors on board [[HNLMS Rotterdam (L800)|HNLMS Rotterdam]] have conducted medical training with local Galmudug Security Forces. The local interaction was in support of a mutual partnership to improve maritime skills.\n\nOn completion of the medical training, members of the Galmudug forces were presented with certificates during an upper deck ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eunavfor.eu/dutch-and-swedish-sailors-train-galmadug-coast-guard/|title=Dutch and Swedish Sailors Train Galmudug Security Forces|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 October 2017, another unit of the Galmudug forces received medical and security training from the Spanish sailors on board EU Naval Force ship [[Spanish patrol vessel Rayo (P-42)|ESPS Rayo]] in order to strengthen maritime security in the region. The two teams then got to work on engine maintenance drills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eunavfor.eu/esps-rayo-welcomes-galmadug-coast-guard/|title=ESPS Rayo welcomes Galmudug Security Forces|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==National Intelligence and Security Agency==\nThe National Intelligence and Security Agency (NISA) is Somalia's National Intelligence And Security Agency, it has a branch in Galmudug state where it provides intelligence services for the Galmudug security force and sometimes works alongside them.<ref name=\"GANFFANVTEM\">{{Cite web |title= GANFFANVTEM |url= http://nepjournal.com/galmudug-and-nisa-forces-foil-attack-nab-vehicle-transporting-explosive-materials/ |publisher= nepjournal.com |accessdate= 15 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Military of Somalia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Galmudug]]\n[[Category:Military of Somalia]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Somalia]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2006]]\n", "name_user": "Ayanl3", "label": "safe", "comment": "The size of GSF is mentioned in both sources, although it is not mentioned numerically in the first source it is mentioned as the largest among all other states.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galmudug_Security_Force"}
{"title_page": "Ellen Atkinson", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Ellen Atkinson\n| image         = Ellen Campbell Atkinson and Edwin Atkinson.png\n| caption       = Ellen Campbell Atkinson and Edwin Atkinson at their wedding in Echuca, 3 May 1911.\n| birth_name    = Ellen Campbell\n| other_names   = Aunty Ellen\n| birth_date    = August 1894<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n| birth_place   = Madowla Park, near [[Echuca]], Victoria, Australia<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n| death_date    = {{Death date|1965|04|30|df=y}}, age 71<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n| death_place   = [[Mooroopna]], Victoria, Australia<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n| resting_place = Mooroopna Cemetery\n| nationality   = Australian\n| occupation    = Aboriginal community leader<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Edwin Atkinson|{{date|1911-05-03}}|{{date|1952-11-02}}|end=d.}}<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n| children      = 4<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Ellen Campbell Atkinson''' ({{nee|Campbell}}; 1894-1965) was an [[Australian Aboriginal]] community leader. Born in Madowla Park, near [[Echuca]] in Victoria, Atkinson and her family were forced to move frequently, either through the necessity of finding work, or forcibly by authorities. She converted to [[Christianity]] when the [[Aborigines' Inland Mission]] (AIM) visited the [[Cummeragunja Reserve]], where she was living, and served the mission for many years in roles such as organist and deacon. Atkinson supported key Aboriginal activists including [[William Ferguson (Australian Aboriginal leader)|William Ferguson]], [[William Cooper (Aboriginal Australian)|William Cooper]], [[Jack Patten]] and [[Thomas Shadrach James]], and participated in the [[Cummeragunja walk-off]]. At the end of her life she finally saw the building of her church, which she found bittersweet as her husband [[Edwin Atkinson|Edwin \"Eddy\" Atkinson]], who was also a key figure in the church community, had not lived to see the culmination of his life's work.\n\n==Early life==\nAtkinson's father, Alick Campbell, was a \"[[Half-caste#Australia|half-caste]]\" Aboriginal stockman<ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/> and a widower who had followed his first wife, Emma Jackson Patterson, from Ganawarra Station (near [[Kerang]]) to [[Coranderrk]]. When his first wife died he married Elizabeth Briggs Charles, and Ellen was born at Madowla Park, near Echuca, in August 1894.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/><ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/> Atkinson had sixteen siblings: seven from Alick's previous marriage, seven from Elizabeth's previous marriage and three full sisters, though one, Jemima, died at birth.<ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/> \n\nThe Campbell family had a dislocated history. Ellen\u2019s mother was born to John Briggs and his \"quarter-caste Aboriginal\" wife, [[Louisa Briggs|Louisa]].<ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/> Loiusa's mother, Mary&mdash;herself a \"half-caste\" Aborigine&mdash;and grandmother, Marjorie, had been kidnapped in 1833 from [[Point Nepean]] by sealers before Mary later married John Strugnell, a former [[chimney sweeper]] who had been [[Penal transportation|transported]] to Australia in 1818 at the age of 17.<ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/> Louisa married John Briggs in Tasmania in 1844, and later moved to [[Elmhurst, Victoria|Mount Cole]]<ref name=\"genealogy\"/> where John worked on the [[Goldfields region of Victoria]] as a shepherd whilst Louisa worked as a [[midwife]].<ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/>\n\nBefore Ellen was born, Alick Campbell had found it increasingly hard to get adequate work, so returned to Ganawarra Station. In the meantime, the Campbell family had been forced out of Coranderrk to the [[Maloga Mission]], which was across the [[Murray River]]. After Alick became sick, he requested food and provisions for his 15 children, which was denied because the [[Board for the Protection of Aborigines]] accused him of spending his money on alcohol, though they eventually sent him blankets.<ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/> The family were to later settle in the Cummeragunja Reserve in New South Wales on condition Alick would declare they would never again seek the aid of the Board or return to Victoria.<ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/> This was not their preferred home as Louisa was living in Corranderk, however even when a Member of the Legislative Assembly of NSW supported the Campbell's petitions to return to Corranderk, he was told that it was forbidden as it was against the law.<ref name=\"barwick-p179\"/> At Cummerangunja the Campbell children received a basic education by preacher, teacher and doctor [[Thomas Shadrach James]].<ref name=\"barwick-p182\"/>\n\n==Married life and conversion to Christianity==\nEllen married Edwin \"Eddy\" Atkinson on 3 May 1911 in Christ Church, Echuca.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/> Edwin Atkinson's father, also named Eddy, was born in Cummeragunja and made a great impression on Ellen, who described him as a \"skilled shearer, clever carpenter and a 'leader of his people{{' \"}}.<ref name=\"barwick-p180\"/> Eddy was living in Cummeragunja at the time and Ellen was working at Strathmerton pastoral station, and before her marriage was in danger of being taken away from her family by authorities.<ref name=\"barwick-p181\"/> Life on Cummeragunja was difficult as, though farming there was well run and highly productive, in 1907 the authorities revoked the blocks under the pretence that they were mismanaged.<ref name=\"goodall-p126\"/> When the non-sectarian Christian Aborigines' Inland Mission (AIM) visited Cummeragunja, both Eddy and Ellen converted to Christianity and became deacons and organists in an independent church that sprung up there.<ref name=\"barwick-p182\"/> Eddy took over from his uncle, [[Doug Nicholls]], when he retired in 1922 and was to be an unpaid preacher and pastor to a congregation amongst a dwindling populace as the authorities started to increasingly disperse residents of the reserve under the increased powers of the ''[[Aborigines Protection Act 1909|Aborigines Protection Act]]''.<ref name=\"barwick-p182\"/>\n\nThe couple had four children, born between 1919 and 1927.<ref name=\"barwick-p182\"/> During this time the couple managed on an increasingly subsistence living as farming at Cummeragunja had been ceased, and, forced to make ends meet, would travel to Victoria in season to work as fruit-pickers.<ref name=\"barwick-p182\"/> Atkinson told Aboriginal researcher [[Diane Barwick]] that family was important and would support each other, saying that \"We've had nothing this week&mdash;and we've had nothing before. But we've never begged; we've battled along. Our families always help each other.\"<ref name=\"barwick-p182\"/>\n\nThe Atkinsons were active in the [[Barham, New South Wales|Barham]] mission. Eddy was first mentioned in AIM's monthly newsletter in July 1921 as addressing services there,<ref name=\"AIM-1921-p4\"/> and in May 1925 was made a \"native helper\" before being appointed a \"Native Missionary\" in 1928.<ref name=\"barwick-p185\"/><ref name=\"austdictbio\"/> Ellen would be the organist whilst Eddy led the congregation.<ref name=\"barwick-p185\"/> By 1929, AIM had reported that the Atkinsons had a \"flock of over 200 people\".<ref name=\"AIM-1929-p10\"/> After 1930 Eddy became very sick and W. B. Payne took over from him. The Atkinsons were increasingly involved in preaching and pastoral care, and Eddy spoke at a number of AIM conventions from 1930 to 1935, including the Barham, Goolagong,<ref name=\"barwick-pp185-186\"/> and Moonah Cullah station conventions,<ref name=\"AIM-March-1932\"/> though were unable to get to a later Moonah Cullah convention as Eddy was injured when his horse had an accident.<ref name=\"AIM-December-1932\"/> The Atkinsons' ministry with AIM came to a halt in 1935, however, after Payne spoke out about the \"indifferences of churches to Australian aborigines\".<ref name=\"mercury-1935-p7\"/> Payne was then removed and the Atkinsons ceased working for AIM. Payne and the Atkinsons moved to the [[Churches of Christ in Australia|Church of Christ]], bringing over a number of their congregation, which caused some consternation for AIM, who wrote that \"[on reaching Cummeragunja with the Memorial Van] Mr Long was confronted with a serious situation, through one, who was our representative, dividing the Native Church and taking with him a portion of it.\"<ref name=\"djenidi-2008-p218\"/> The Atkinsons and Paynes remained good friends and the Atkinsons' daughter Daisy was taken in by the Paynes so that she could get an education, which she could not get at Cummeragunja.<ref name=\"barwick-p186\"/>\n\n==Cummerangunja walk-off and aftermath==\nIn 1934 a new manager, J. G. Danvers, was appointed to Cummerangunja. Danvers had previously been the manager of Brewarrina Aboriginal Mission Station and had previously worked with [[Indigenous people of New Guinea|Papuan people]] in Papua New Guinea.<ref name=\"western-age-1934-p4\"/> Danvers ignored the policies of the time and provided much needed rations to the Aboriginal community,<ref name=\"barwick-p187\"/> however he was promoted to the Menindle Aboriginal reserve where he again stood up for the Aboriginal population there, but was later sacked after allegedly \"giving information to the Press\".<ref name=\"inverall-times-1938-p1\"/><ref name=\"armidale-express-1938-p1\"/> After Danvers left, life for the Aborigines living in Cummerangunja steadily worsened and, despite lobbying by Eddy Atkinson's uncle, [[William Cooper (Aboriginal Australian)|William Cooper]], conditions did not change. The [[Australian Aborigines' League]] was eventually established by Cooper in Sydney, and later a division was formed in Melbourne by [[William Ferguson (Australian Aboriginal leader)|William Ferguson]], who was a father-in-law to one of the Atkinsons' nieces.<ref name=\"barwick-p187\"/> (Ferguson was to later write a letter of protest to ''[[Daily Liberal|The Dubbo Liberal and Macquarie Advocate]]'' protesting the dismissal of Danvers from the Menindle reserve.<ref name=\"ferguson-letter-dubbo-liberal-p4\"/>) Despite a Select Committee conducting an inquiry into the reserves in 1937, nothing changed. Matters reached a head when [[Jack Patten]], who had become president of the Sydney league, warned the Aboriginal community at Cummerangunja that the Board planned to turn it into a closed compound, control their earnings and take away children. Patten formed these conclusions after he had read extracts of the Committee's report. As a result, 170 people who were part of the Atkinsons' community crossed the Murray to camp at Burmah in what was known as the [[Cummeragunja walk-off]] and Patten was charged with \"inciting Aborigines to leave their reserve\".<ref name=\"argus-1939-p2\"/><ref name=\"shepparton-advertiser-1939-p2\"/>\n\nFourteen days later, the Atkinsons moved with their community to Burmah. They had been entrusted with money for food for those who left, and the new manager of Cummerangunja, a Mr A. J. McQuigan, had threatened Eddy and ordered him to \"remain neutral and not to help the people who had left\".<ref name=\"barwick-p188\"/> The Atkinsons eventually moved to [[Mooroopna]] in 1941, following many in their community who moved there as work was more readily available because it was a fruit growing centre.<ref name=\"barwick-p189\"/> They later moved to Melbourne, yet again following and ministering to their community&mdash;many of who had found paid work in factories.<ref name=\"barwick-p189\"/> Some time after they moved back to Cummerangunja and continued to support Ferguson and James, who continued making deputations to the Minister for the Interior.<ref name=\"barwick-p191\"/> In the meantime the division between AIM and the Church of Christ had been healed in 1943 when they both conducted joint services praying for the men serving in [[World War II]].<ref name=\"barwick-p189\"/> The Atkinsons later moved their ministry to Mooroopna. After many lost their homes from severe flooding in March 1950, the government built a three-roomed weatherboard hut and, as parishioners guaranteed the Atkinsons' rent, they moved into this as their rental home in April of 1951.<ref name=\"barwick-p191-192\"/>\n\n==Later life and death==\nOn 2 November, 1952 Eddy Atkinson died. Atkinson told Diane Barwick that \"Eddy worked so hard for the people [and] the doctor told me his heart just gave out.\"<ref name=\"barwick-p192\"/> After her husband's death, Atkinson urged the Church of Christ leadership to accept her son, Geoff, as pastor but was largely ignored and Doug Nicholls was made the pastor. Eventually there was a split in the church as  James started his own independent church. According to Barwick, \"this division of her family and community grieved Ellen. She was grateful for the genuine kindness of some clergymen and wanted Eddy's church to survive as his memorial. But she also resented the paternalism and regretted that Geoff was not helped to carry on his father's work.\"<ref name=\"barwick-p192\"/>\n\nThe Aboriginal community had many people living on a patch of land in Mooroopna that was high enough to escape flooding&mdash;this patch of land was known as Daish's paddock. By 1946 James had secured promises to transfer ownership of the 150 acres of land to his community to build houses,<ref name=\"shepparton-advertiser-1946-p5\"/> instead it was converted into a rubbish tip.<ref name=\"atkinson-the-age-2006\"/> By 1956 there were proposals to integrate those living in Mooroopna into Housing Commission homes, but this resulted in sustained and vitriolic opposition from non-Aboriginal residents of nearby townships. Later, however, McCallum notes that a press clipping (of unknown origin) at the time recorded that \"Speakers at public meetings 'slated the \"filthy\", \"unhygenic\", \"disgraceful\" and \"Communist breeding\" conditions of Daish's paddock and in some cases condemned the local municipal bodies for their tolerance of a vice ridden and degrading environment{{' \"}}, resulting in plans for a proposed subdivision of twenty-two rowed blocks<ref name=\"mccallum-2017-p231-232\"/> (building and land on what was Daish's paddock is now managed by the Rumbalara Aboriginal Co-operative). Later, after the police committed twenty-four children as state wards, Atkinson lamented that \"It would have been better to help their parents keep them. Those mothers were doing their best. You can't keep children clean on a rubbish tip, when you have to carry every drop of water half a mile.\"<ref name=\"barwick-p192\"/>\n\nPopulation growth from the housing development allowed the Church of Christ to donate enough money to allow the building of an Aboriginal church, by voluntary labour, that adjoined the Atkinsons' house. When it was opened, Barwick reported that Atkinson \"had wept when they handed her the keys: 'It was the church they promised Eddy.{{' \"}} The opening was attended by over 300 people and was officiated by Doug Nicholls.<ref name=\"barwick-pp176-177\"/>\n\nIn 1960 the late [[anthropologist]], historian and Aboriginal-rights activist [[Diane Barwick]] met and spent four months interviewing Atkinson. In her article \"Aunty Ellen: The Pastor's Wife\" she wrote that \"I did not plan, all those years ago, to write her life story. I do so now as a tribute to a woman who deeply influenced my life.\"<ref name=\"barwick-p174\"/> Barwick recounted that her time with Atkinson was at first reserved, but changed in time. She wrote that,\n\n{{quote|At first our conversations were limited to the topics appropriate between strangers. I was shy and afraid of being impertinent; she was kind yet implacable in her skilful management of interviews. She had played an important role in interpreting ''koories''{{'}} (Aborigines') needs to ''gubba'' (European) sympathisers during forty years of church work. Initially she saw me as yet another inquiring ''gubba'' to be instructed and gently manipulated as a potential resource for her community. But our relationship changed, just because I was a young girl without relatives and needed help. Her people have, I think, a special kindness for waifs and strays bereft of family, perhaps because their own identity is based upon kinship ties.<ref name=\"barwick-p176\"/>}}\n\nAtkinson remained a prominent community leader until her death on 30 August 1965 at Mooroopna. She was buried in Mooroopna local cemetery.<ref name=\"austdictbio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"austdictbio\">{{ref|white-1993|\u03b1}} White 1993</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"barwick-p179\">{{ref|barwick-1995|\u03b2}} Barwick 1995, p. 179</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"genealogy\">{{ref|mollison-1978|\u03b3}} Mollison 1978</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"barwick-p180\">{{ref|barwick-1995|\u03b2}} Barwick 1995, p. 180</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"barwick-p181\">{{ref|barwick-1995|\u03b2}} Barwick 1995, p. 181</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"barwick-p182\">{{ref|barwick-1995|\u03b2}} Barwick 1995, p. 182</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"goodall-p126\">{{ref|goodall-1996|\u03b4}} Goodall 1996, p. 126</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AIM-1921-p4\">{{cite news|url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/sites/default/files/docs/digitised_collections/our_aim/v14s11_a_0.pdf|department=The Harvest Field|title=Barham|last=Crebbin|first=M. I.|date={{date|1921-07-18}}|work=Our AIM|publisher=Aborigines' Inland Mission|publication-place=Sydney}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AIM-1929-p10\">{{cite news|url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/sites/default/files/docs/digitised_collections/our_aim/v22s7_a_2_0.pdf|title=No. 1 Motor Van on Victorian Border|last=Tomkins|first=G.|date={{date|1929-03-26}}|work=Our AIM|publisher=Aborigines' Inland Mission|publication-place=Sydney}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AIM-March-1932\">{{cite news|url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/sites/default/files/docs/digitised_collections/our_aim/v26s7_a_0.pdf|title=A Visit to Cummeragunja|date={{dat