ory:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Palm Beach Gardens, Florida]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Haven, Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Palillo"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in the United States}}\n{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n<!--NOTE: Please discuss on talk page before putting a \"current event\" template here. This is intended for short-term use only per advice at Template:Current-->\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak USA per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million residents by state\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = United States\n| first_case      = [[Everett, Washington]]<!--no source, not mentioned in the article-->\n| arrival_date    = January 15, 2020<ref name= NEJMFirstCase/><br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=15|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheikh |first1=Knvul |last2=Rabin |first2=Roni Caryn |title=The Coronavirus: What Scientists Have Learned So Far |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/what-is-coronavirus.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 20,608 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\">{{cite web| last = Johns Hopkins CSSE| title = Coronavirus COVID19 (2019-nCoV)| work = Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases| format = ArcGIS| accessdate = April 8, 2020| url = https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6}}</ref><br /> 18,559 ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] confirmed)<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\">{{cite news |title=Cases in U.S. |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/cases-in-us.html |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |agency=Center for Disease Control}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 529,951 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\"/><br /> 492,416 ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] confirmed)<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 32,091 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a new infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}), spread to the United States in January 2020. Cases have occurred in all fifty [[U.S. state]]s, the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]], and all inhabited [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territories]] except [[American Samoa]].<ref name=\"mariana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|title=Saipan confirms two COVID-19 positive cases|date=March 28, 2020|website=samoanews.com|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|04|11|df=US}}, the U.S. has the most confirmed active cases and deaths in the world.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first known case of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} in the U.S. was confirmed on January 20, 2020, in a 35-year-old returnee from [[Wuhan]], China, five days earlier.<ref name=NEJMFirstCase>{{cite journal |vauthors=Holshue ML, DeBolt C, Lindquist S, Lofy KH, et al |title=First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=382 |issue=10 |pages=929\u2013936 |date=March 2020 |pmid=32004427 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa2001191 |pmc=7092802 }}</ref> The [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] was established on January 29.<ref name=\"Jan29WH\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-regarding-presidents-coronavirus-task-force/|date=January 29, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|publisher=[[White House]]|title=Statement from the Press Secretary Regarding the President's Coronavirus Task Force}}</ref> Two days later, the [[Trump administration]] declared a [[public health emergency (United States)|public health emergency]] and announced restrictions on travelers arriving from China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/01/31/801686524/trump-declares-coronavirus-a-public-health-emergency-and-restricts-travel-from-c |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=January 31, 2020 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |title=Trump Declares Coronavirus A Public Health Emergency And Restricts Travel From China |author=Aubrey, Allison}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/04/trumps-snowballing-china-travel-claim |title=Trump\u2019s Snowballing China Travel Claim |author=Lori Robertson |date=April 10, 2020 |website=[[FactCheck.org]] |access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>  On February 26, a person with \"no known exposure to the virus through travel or close contact with a known infected individual\" was confirmed by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) in northern California.<ref name=HomeGrown>{{cite news |url= https://www.sacbee.com/news/california/article240674471.html |work= [[The Sacramento Bee]] | title= First U.S. coronavirus case of unknown origin confirmed in Northern California, CDC says |author= Smith, Darrell and Cathie Anderson |date= February 26, 2020 |accessdate= March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe federal government's response to the pandemic was initially slow;<ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/28/trump-coronavirus-politics-us-health-disaster|title=The missing six weeks: how Trump failed the biggest test of his life|date=March 28, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=McCarthy|first2=Tom|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> a manufacturing defect rendered a supply of CDC-developed test kits unusable, regulatory rules prevented academic laboratories and hospitals from using their own tests,<ref name=\"WangMarch22\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> while President [[Donald Trump]] also dismissed the threat that COVID-19 posed (repeatedly making optimistic statements and claiming the outbreak was under control).<ref name=\"BlakeMarch17\" /> By the start of March, the government began to heighten its response; the [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) began allowing public health agencies, hospitals, and private companies to develop tests and perform [[COVID-19 testing|testing]], and loosened its requirements to allow anyone with a doctor's order to be tested.<ref name=WangMarch22/> As of March 25, at least 418,000 tests had been conducted,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Subramaniam |first1=Tara |last2=Lybrand |first2=Holmes |title=Fact Check: US has done more coronavirus tests than South Korea, but not per person |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/coronavirus-testing-trump-south-korea-fact-check/index.html |publisher=CNN}}</ref> and by April{{nbsp}}2 the number had reached 1,280,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/interactives/2020/coronavirus-testing-by-state-chart-of-new-cases/|title=Live tracker: How many coronavirus cases have been reported in each U.S. state?|last=Jin|first=Beatrice|date=March 30, 2020|work=Politico|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Although it has surpassed [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]] in the total number of tests performed, it has still performed fewer tests [[per capita]] than South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/09/politics/trump-coronavirus-tests/index.html|title=Trump says more than 2 million coronavirus tests have been done in the US, and claims mass testing not needed|last=Vazquez|first=Maegan|last2=Klein|first2=Betsy|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe CDC warned that widespread transmission of the disease may force large numbers of people to seek healthcare, which may overload healthcare systems and lead to otherwise preventable deaths.<ref name=\"CDC COVID-19 Situation Summary\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/summary.html |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation Summary |last=CDC |publisher=CDC |accessdate=March 7, 2020|date=March 7, 2020 }}</ref> Since March 19, 2020, the U.S. [[United States Department of State|Department of State]] has advised U.S. citizens to avoid all international travel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/ea/travel-advisory-alert-global-level-4-health-advisory-issue.html|title=Global Level 4 Health Advisory\u2014Do Not Travel|website=travel.state.gov}}</ref> On March 16, the White House advised against any gatherings of more than 10 people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liptak |first1=Kevin |title=White House advises public to avoid groups of more than 10, asks people to stay away from bars and restaurants |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/politics/white-house-guidelines-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In mid-March 2020, the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (FEMA) told the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] (USACE) to plan to construct new facilities, including leased hotels and other buildings, and to convert them for use as hospitals and [[intensive care unit]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48927-rep-defazio-fema-asks-army-corps-to-help-build-emergency-health-facilities|title=Rep. DeFazio: FEMA Asks Army Corps to Help Build Emergency Health Facilities|last1=Ichniowski|first1=Tom|last2=Rubin|first2=Debra K.|date=March 18, 2020|work=Engineering News-Record|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/balajis/status/1242029099310133248|title=Ok. It's just one clip. But it's by far the most intelligent thing I've heard any government official say in the last few months. Further increases likelihood the military will take over COVID19 response in the near future. |website=twitter.com/usarmy|first=Balaji S.|last=Srinivasan|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}</ref> [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|State and local responses]] to the outbreak have included prohibitions and cancellation of large-scale gatherings (including cultural events, exhibitions, and sporting events), and the closure of schools and other educational institutions.<ref name=\"nyt sports\">{{Cite news|last=Deb|first=Sopan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/11/sports/basketball/warriors-coronavirus-fans.html|title=Sports Leagues Bar Fans and Cancel Games Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 11, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020|last2=Cacciola|first2=Scott|issn=0362-4331|last3=Stein|first3=Marc}}</ref> <!-- THE FOLLOWING SENTENCE HAS BEEN AFFIRMED BY AN RFC. DO NOT REMOVE WITHOUT CONSENSUS. -->There have been [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United_States|incidents of xenophobia and racism]] against [[Chinese Americans]] and other [[Asian Americans]].<ref name=\"NYT Racism\">{{cite news |last1=Tavernise |first1=Sabrina |last2=Oppel Jr |first2=Richard A. |title=Spit On, Yelled At, Attacked: Chinese-Americans Fear for Their Safety |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/chinese-coronavirus-racist-attacks.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On April 11, 2020, Wyoming became the 50th state to declare a disaster, thus for the first time in history, all 50 U.S. states have simultaneously been under emergency declarations.<ref>https://k2radio.com/president-trump-declares-disaster-in-wyoming-due-to-coronavirus/</ref> The same day, the United States became the country with the most confirmed COVID-19 deaths.<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/04/11/coronavirus-us-more-covid-19-deaths-than-italy-any-country/5121962002/</ref><ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/04/11/coronavirus-latest-news/</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/us/coronavirus-live-updates.html</ref><ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/overtake-italy-coronavirus-deaths-live-updates-200410232614536.html</ref>\n\n==Current number of non-repatriated cases by state and territory==\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\"><!--serious rendering issues in current article with it floated to the right-->{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States cases by state}}</div>\n\nThe CDC publishes official numbers every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday, reporting several categories of cases: individual travelers, people who contracted the disease from other people within the U.S., and repatriated citizens who returned to the U.S. from crisis locations, such as [[Wuhan]], where the disease originated, and the cruise ship ''Diamond Princess''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-in-us.html|title=International Locations with Confirmed COVID-19 Cases|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222072600/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-in-us.html|archive-date=February 22, 2020|access-date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHowever, multiple sources,<ref>examples of sources: [https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-we-dont-know-how-many-americans-are-infected-with-coronavirusand-might-never-know-11586005200], [https://www.dailyastorian.com/coronavirus/lack-of-testing-clouds-virus-picture-on-the-north-coast/article_b6253d02-7876-11ea-828a-bf59009219b5.html], [https://www.sacbee.com/news/coronavirus/article241306066.html], [https://www.healthline.com/health-news/how-many-coronavirus-cases-are-there], [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/us/coronavirus-deaths-undercount.html], [https://www.geekwire.com/2020/scientists-find-86-percent-coronavirus-infections-go-unreported/], [https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/graphics/2020/03/10/us-coronavirus-map-tracking-united-states-outbreak/4945223002/], [https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/experts-think-were-flattening-the-coronavirus-curve-but-hospitalizations-havent-peaked-yet/], [https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/26/health/number-of-cases-testing-data-intl/index.html]. Retrieved 10 April 2020.</ref> note that statistics on confirmed coronavirus cases are misleading, since the shortage of tests<ref name=\"factcheck.org\" /><ref>Farah Stockman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/us/coronavirus-testing-challenges.html \"Sick People Across the U.S. Say They Are Being Denied the Coronavirus Test\"], New York Times, March 12, 2020; Sheila Kaplan and Katie Thomas, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/health/coronavirus-testing-us.html \"Despite Promises, Testing Delays Leave Americans 'Flying Blind'], New York Times, April 6, 2020. Retrieved 10 April 2020.</ref><ref name=\"McFall_testing\"/> means that the actual number of cases is much higher than the number of cases confirmed.<ref>Quote: \"Confirmed coronavirus cases in the U.S. crossed 200,000 on Thursday, but experts agree the actual number of infected people is much higher. The lack of reliable data\u2014a persistent problem since the pandemic began\u2014has made it impossible to determine the actual size of the outbreak, hampering the U.S. response.\" Source: Jeff J. Roberts, [https://fortune.com/2020/04/03/coronavirus-data-stats-private-sector-covid-19/ \"Can the private sector provide better coronavirus data? Experts are skeptical\"], Fortune, April 3, 2020 . Retrieved 10 April 2020.</ref> Likewise, the number of deaths confirmed to be due to coronavirus is likely to be undercounted for the same reason.<ref name=\"Kliff+Bosman\" /><ref>Mark Abdelmalek, Josh Margolin, Aaron Katersky and Eden David, [https://abcnews.go.com/Health/coronavirus-death-toll-us-worse-numbers/story?id=70018321 \"Coronavirus death toll in US likely worse than numbers say\"], ABC News, April 7, 2020. Retrieved 10 April 2020.</ref><ref>Emma Brown, Beth Reinhard and Aaron C. Davis, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/coronavirus-death-toll-americans-are-almost-certainly-dying-of-covid-19-but-being-left-out-of-the-official-count/2020/04/05/71d67982-747e-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html \"Coronavirus death toll: Americans are almost certainly dying of covid-19 but being left out of the official count\"], Washington Post, April 5, 2020. Retrieved 10 April 2020.</ref>\n\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\">{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States medical cases chart}}</div>\n\n==Background and preparations==\n===Reports predicting global pandemics===\n\n[[File:Alex Azar declares PHED for Coronavirus.jpg|thumb|[[Alex Azar]] signs a public health emergency declaration]]\n[[File:President Trump Holds a News Conference on the Coronavirus - 49659235436.jpg|thumb|[[Debbie Birx]], White House coronavirus response coordinator, speaks at a White House press conference]]\n\nThe United States along with more than a hundred other countries have been subjected to pandemics and epidemics throughout their history, including the 1918 [[Spanish flu]], the 1957 [[Asian Flu]], and the 1968 [[Hong Kong flu]] pandemics.<ref name=\"abc7\">{{cite news |last1=Miguel |first1=Ken |title=Here's a look at some of history's worst pandemics that have killed millions |url=https://abc7news.com/5974174/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=ABC 7 News |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lileks |first1=James |title=How the news media played down the pandemics of yore, from Spanish flu to Swine flu |url=http://www.startribune.com/how-the-news-media-played-down-the-pandemics-of-yore-from-spanish-flu-to-swine-flu/568899732/?refresh=true |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=Star Tribune |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Jeremy |title=The Coronavirus Is No 1918 Pandemic |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/03/were-not-facing-second-spanish-flu/607354/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In the most recent pandemic prior to COVID-19, the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 swine flu]] took the lives of more than 12,000 Americans and hospitalized another 200,000.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shrestha|first=Sundar S.|last2=Swerdlow|first2=David L.|last3=Borse|first3=Rebekah H.|last4=Prabhu|first4=Vimalanand S.|last5=Finelli|first5=Lyn|last6=Atkins|first6=Charisma Y.|last7=Owusu-Edusei|first7=Kwame|last8=Bell|first8=Beth|last9=Mead|first9=Paul S.|last10=Biggerstaff|first10=Matthew|last11=Brammer|first11=Lynnette|date=January 1, 2011|title=Estimating the burden of 2009 pandemic influenza A (H1N1) in the United States (April 2009 \u2013 April 2010)|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|volume=52 Suppl 1|pages=S75\u201382|doi=10.1093/cid/ciq012|issn=1537-6591|pmid=21342903|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"briefing\" /><ref name=\"abc7\" /> Because of this pandemic and the 2014 [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|Ebola epidemic]], which saw only a small number of Americans infected,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lupkin |first1=Sydney |title=Ebola in America: Timeline of the Deadly Virus |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/ebola-america-timeline/story?id=26159719 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=ABC News |date=November 17, 2014}}</ref> the [[Obama Administration]] increased planning and analysis that focused on deficiencies in the government's response to outbreaks.<ref name=\"briefing\" /> In 2017, outgoing Obama administration officials briefed incoming Trump administration officials on how to respond to pandemics by using simulated scenarios, although by the time of the COVID-19 outbreak in the U.S., around {{nowrap|two-thirds}} of Trump administration officials at the briefing had left the administration.<ref name=\"briefing\">{{cite news |last1=Toosi |first1=Nahal |last2=Lippman |first2=Daniel |last3=Diamond |first3=Dan |title=Before Trump's inauguration, a warning: 'The worst influenza pandemic since 1918' |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/16/trump-inauguration-warning-scenario-pandemic-132797 |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=[[Politico]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn unpublished draft plan by the Pentagon of January 6, 2017, a few weeks before Trump took office, included predictions of a pandemic similar to COVID-19.<ref>USNORTHCOM Branch Plan 3560: Pandemic Influenza and Infectious Disease Response, 6 January 2017. Available on [https://www.scribd.com/document/454422848/Pentagon-Influenza-Response Scribd]; retrieved April 7, 2020).</ref> It predicted shortages of \"hospital beds, specialized equipment such as mechanical ventilators, and pharmaceuticals readily available to adequately treat their populations during clinically severe pandemic\". Some commentators felt Trump was, or should have been, aware of warnings given in the plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/19/trump-keeps-saying-nobody-could-have-foreseen-coronavirus-we-keep-finding-out-about-new-warning-signs/|title=Analysis {{!}} Trump keeps saying 'nobody' could have foreseen coronavirus. We keep finding out about new warning signs.|last=reporter|first=Aaron Blake closeAaron BlakeSenior political|last2=FixEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollow|first2=writing for The|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Intelligence Community]], in its annual ''[[US World Wide Threat Assessment]]'' report of 2017 and 2018, stated new types of microbes that are \"easily transmissible between humans\" remained \"a major threat\".<ref>[https://www.dni.gov/files/documents/Newsroom/Testimonies/SSCI%20Unclassified%20SFR%20-%20Final.pdf \"Worldwide Threat Assessment of the US Intelligence Community\"], Senate Select Committee on Intelligence, May 11, 2017</ref> Similarly, for the 2019 ''Worldwide Threat Assessment'', the U.S. intelligence agencies warned that \"the United States and the world will remain vulnerable to the next flu pandemic or large-scale outbreak of a contagious disease that could lead to massive rates of death and disability, severely affect the world economy, strain international resources, and increase calls on the United States for support.\"<ref name=threats>[https://www.dni.gov/files/ODNI/documents/2019-ATA-SFR---SSCI.pdf \" \"Worldwide Threat Assessment of the US Intelligence Community\"] Senate Select Committee on Intelligence, January 29, 2019</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dilanian |first1=Ken |title=U.S. intel agencies warned of rising risk of outbreak like coronavirus |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-warned-rising-risk-outbreak-coronavirus-n1144891 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Reider |first1=Rem |title=Contrary to Trump's Claim, A Pandemic Was Widely Expected at Some Point |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/contrary-to-trumps-claim-a-pandemic-was-widely-expected-at-some-point/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[Factcheck.org]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther countries also use the ''Worldwide Threat Assessment'' reports in formulating their own plans for a possible pandemic, recognizing that even a genetically modified disease could create a pandemic which would kill thousands or potentially millions.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/rise-of-biological-chemical-weapons/ \"The rise of biological and chemical weapons\"], ''The Telegraph'' (UK), July 14, 2018</ref> In 2019, the first annual report by the Global Preparedness Monitoring Board, organized by the [[World Bank]] and the WHO, also describes the threat of a global pandemic potentially killing tens of millions.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/sep/18/a-deadly-virus-could-kill-80-million-people-in-hours-experts-warn \"Experts warn world 'grossly unprepared' for future pandemics\"], ''The Guardian'' (UK), Sept. 18, 2019</ref><ref>[https://apps.who.int/gpmb/assets/annual_report/GPMB_annualreport_2019.pdf \"A World at Risk\"], Global Preparedness Monitoring Board, Sept. 2019</ref> Three years earlier, [[Margaret Chan]], then head of the WHO, addressed health officials from 200 countries, emphasizing that emerging diseases, climate change, new global transportation networks and the failure of an increasing number of antibiotics make the planet ripe for the next pandemic.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2016/05/23/479199256/whos-stern-warning-the-world-is-not-prepared-to-cope-with-pandemics \"WHO's Stern Warning: The World 'Is Not Prepared To Cope' With Pandemics\"], ''NPR'', May 23, 2016</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2020, ABC News reported that in late November 2019, the [[National Center for Medical Intelligence]] (NCMI) warned about a contagion spreading in Wuhan and \"concluded it could be a cataclysmic event\" and repeated this at briefings through December for policy and decision-makers across the federal government, as well as the NSC at the White House. The warning reportedly appeared in the [[President's Daily Brief]] in early January 2020, which would have had to go through weeks of vetting and analysis. The ABC story also stated that other intelligence bulletins released after the NCMI report claimed that China was not sharing crucial information about the epidemic with other countries.<ref name=\"ABCReport\">Josh Margolin and James Gordon Meek ''[https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/intelligence-report-warned-coronavirus-crisis-early-november-sources/story?id=70031273 Intelligence report warned of coronavirus crisis as early as November: Sources; \"Analysts concluded it could be a cataclysmic event,\" a source says.]'' April 8, 2020 ABC News</ref> \n\nIn a rare public comment immediately after this story broke, the Pentagon responded by denying that any such NCMI report existed. The head of the NCMI, Dr. R. Shane Day, said in a statement that the story of a November report was \"not correct.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/news/pentagon-bashes-bombshell-abc-report-denies-u-s-intel-identified-coronavirus-threat-in-november/|title=Pentagon Bashes Bombshell ABC Report, Denies U.S. Intel Identified Coronavirus Threat in November|last=Hoonhout|first=Tobias|date=2020-04-09 |website=[[National Review]] |language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=\"ABCReport\" /> Vice Chairman of the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] John Hyten subsequently stated that he saw no U.S. intelligence reports on the COVID-19 outbreak until January. Discussing the ABC News claim, Hyten said: \"We went back and looked at everything in November and December. The first indications we have were the reports out of China in late December that were in the public forum.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dunleavy |first1=Jerry |title=Pentagon denies existence of November coronavirus intelligence report warning of 'cataclysmic event' |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/pentagon-denies-existence-of-november-coronavirus-intelligence-report-warning-of-cataclysmic-event |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=[[Washington Examiner]] |date=April 9, 2020}}{{rs?|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Defense Department Briefing on Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?471080-1/defense-department-briefing-coronavirus-response |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=C-SPAN |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Preparations===\n\nA number of organizations in the U.S. have been involved for years preparing the country and other nations for epidemics and pandemics. Among those is the [[Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations]], co-founded by the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]], [[Wellcome Trust]], the [[European Commission]]. Since 2017 it has tried to produce a platform approach for dealing with emerging epidemic disease such as Covid-19, which would enable rapid vaccine development and immunity research in response to outbreaks.<ref name=wsj-prep>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/preparing-for-the-next-pandemic-11585936915 \"Preparing for the Next Pandemic\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', April 3, 2020</ref><ref>Gates, Bill. [https://www.gatesnotes.com/Health/Preparing-for-the-Next-Epidemic \"Preparing for the next epidemic: a first step\"], ''GatesNotes'', Jan. 18, 2017</ref> According to [[Sue Desmond-Hellmann]], former chancellor of the [[University of California, San Francisco]], there is no substitute for federal preparedness, especially for having a stockpile of protective equipment that health care workers need to safely treat patients, and to prepare for \"surge capacity\" with equipment like ventilators.<ref name=wsj-prep/>\n\nWhile the U.S. established the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] in 2003 as an emergency repository for antibiotics, vaccines and other critical medical supplies, it has not adequately served its role in the current pandemic.<ref name=wsj-prep/> According to the Trust for America's Health, in 2017, public health represented just 2.5% of all U.S. health spending ($274 per person), which Desmond-Hellman feels is too small a portion and an under-investment to cover prevention, preparedness, and community recovery during a pandemic.<ref name=wsj-prep/> She explained:\n{{quote|For future epidemics to be managed more effectively, we must have better information, and that means having well-funded, well-trained and well-prepared public health experts\u2014trained in statistics, epidemiology, and laboratory and clinical medicine\u2014at the CDC and in the states.<ref name=wsj-prep/>}}\n\nIn February 2020, when there were only a dozen cases in the U.S., and before anyone had died, the CDC advised Americans to prepare for an epidemic to contain the virus before it spreads throughout the U.S. [[Nancy Messonnier]], a director at the CDC, explained that with no vaccine or treatment available, Americans must be prepared to take other precautions.<ref>[https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-epidemic-how-to-prepare.html \"A US coronavirus outbreak is almost inevitable. Here's how you can prepare.\"], ''Live Science'', Feb. 27, 2020</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Global Health Security Index]], an American-British assessment which ranks the health security capabilities in 195 countries, the U.S. in 2020 is the \"most prepared\" nation.<ref>[https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2020/02/these-are-the-countries-best-prepared-for-health-emergencies/ \"These are the countries best prepared for health emergencies\"], ''World Economic Forum'', Feb. 12, 2020</ref><ref name=cfr>[https://www.cfr.org/in-brief/what-global-health-survey-found-months-coronavirus-pandemic \"What a Global Health Survey Found Months Before the Coronavirus Pandemic\"], Council on Foreign Relations, March 24, 2020</ref> While the U.S., like many countries, did face criticism at the beginning or during the outbreak, the high quality of the laboratories in the U.S. and its skilled epidemiological workforce, were its highest attributes.<ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/politics/us-was-most-prepared-country-in-the-world-for-pandemics-johns-hopkins-study-found-in-2019 \"US was more prepared for pandemic than any other country, Johns Hopkins study found\"], ''Fox News'', March 24, 2020</ref> China, which ranked fifty-first, scored lowest in compliance with international norms for failing to complete several internationally recognized health security plans. It made a number of serious errors at the outset of the outbreak, notably in Wuhan, where it failed to communicate. Local authorities withheld information about the virus from the public and the central government and silenced doctors who spoke out.<ref name=cfr/> A study by England's [[University of Southampton]] suggests the number of coronavirus cases could have been reduced by 95% had China moved to contain the virus three weeks sooner.<ref name=wsj-info>Editorial Board, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/world-health-coronavirus-disinformation-11586122093 \"World Health Coronavirus Disinformation\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', April 5, 2020</ref>\n\nThe WHO has been criticized for not acting promptly and by failing to provide available information. The Editorial Board of the ''Wall Street Journal'', is among those who feel the world would have been \"better prepared\" had the WHO declared a \"Public Health Emergency\" weeks before it did, since the virus had by then spread to other countries and had already taken on the attributes of a pandemic.<ref name=wsj-info/> Brazil's Health Minister likewise felt that the WHO was too slow in declaring the global coronavirus outbreak a pandemic, which it did six weeks later, thereby complicating Brazil's ability to fully prepare for and curb the spread of the virus after it arrived.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-11/who-s-pandemic-declaration-came-too-late-brazil-says \"WHO's Pandemic Declaration Came Too Late, Brazil Says\"], 'Bloomberg'', March 11, 2020</ref> By the time it was declared a pandemic on March 11, 2020, the virus had already spread across all continents except Antarctica, to 110 countries, leaving less time for some countries to fully prepare their emergency health organizations.<ref>[https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2020/3/9/21163412/who-coronavirus-covid19-pandemic-world-health-organization \"Why the WHO waited to call the coronavirus a pandemic\"], ''Vox'', March 11, 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.nationalgeographic.com/science/2020/02/how-coronavirus-could-become-pandemic-and-why-it-matters/#close \"Coronavirus is officially a pandemic. Here's why that matters.\"], ''National Geographic'', March 11, 2020</ref>\n\nWhile some countries and cities did take the risk of a pandemic seriously enough to prepare years ahead of time, there was often a failure to follow through due to financial constraints or from making decisions without proper support of health or science professionals. New York City, for instance, took preparatory steps more than a decade ago, but then discontinued them in favor of other priorities.<ref>[https://nypost.com/2020/04/07/nycs-pandemic-preparations-that-started-and-stopped/ \"NYC's pandemic preparations that started\u2014and stopped\"], ''New York Post'', April 7, 2020</ref>\n\nWith the current pandemic, once cases began spreading throughout the nation, federal and state agencies began taking urgent steps to prepare for a surge of hospital patients. Among the actions was establishing additional places for patients in case hospitals became overwhelmed. That included transforming buildings normally used for sports and entertainment events by turning them into field hospitals. The [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]], for instance, was cancelled and the fairgrounds where it is normally held was turned into a medical center.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-30/coronavirus-event-companies-coachella-pivot-covid-19-testing \"They were supposed to build stages for Coachella. Now they're building coronavirus triage tents\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', March 30, 2020</ref> To prepare housing for homeless persons, states such as California have procured private hotels and motels as emergency shelters and isolation spaces.<ref>[https://sfist.com/2020/03/16/california-to-use-hotels-and-motels-to-shelter-homeless-during-pandemic/ \"California to Use Hotels and Motels to Shelter Homeless During Pandemic\"], ''[[SFist]]'', March 16, 2020</ref>\n\nManpower from the military and volunteer armies were called up to help construct the emergency facilities.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/photos-field-hospitals-built-globe-coronavirus-pandemic-spreads/story?id=69962474 \"Field hospitals built around the globe as coronavirus pandemic spreads\"], ''ABC News'', April 4, 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/connecticut-national-guard-sets-up-temporary-hospitals-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/2248512/ \"Connecticut National Guard Sets Up Temporary Hospitals Amid Coronavirus Pandemic\"], ''NBC'', April 1, 2020</ref> In addition, unoccupied former clinics and hospitals were being converted with retired and active physicians and nurses were brought in. The CEO of [[Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center]] in Boston, saw the problem:\n{{quote|Anybody with eyes in their head, anybody who is watching what is happening in New York and Washington and elsewhere would be foolish not to get ready now. We are not wasting any time to get as prepared as possible for the surge that is almost certainly coming.<ref>[https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/27/coronavirus-specialty-hospital-conversions-patient-beds \"Emptied Clinics And Hospitals Prepare For New Purpose In COVID-19 Pandemic\"], ''Common Health'', March 27, 2020</ref>}}\n\n===Pandemic simulation tests===\n\nScenario testing can help create models of potential epidemics and pandemics, which can be achieved through large-scale computer simulations. The models can incorporate mitigation measures, seasonality, randomness, and other factors that can vary during a real epidemic. Similar tests are used by the insurance industry to understand risks posed by infrequent natural disasters such as hurricanes and earthquakes.<ref name=NCBI/> \n\nThe Trump administration simulated a series of pandemic outbreaks from China in 2019 and found that the U.S. government response was \"underfunded, underprepared, and uncoordinated\". Among the conclusions of the test was the lack of certain medical supplies to meet demand due to their needing to be imported. It led President Trump to issue an executive order to make flu vaccines more readily available and of higher quality, and he provided additional funds for the pandemic threats program in the HHS.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sanger|first=David E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Before Virus Outbreak, a Cascade of Warnings Went Unheeded|date=March 19, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 20, 2020|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|issn=0362-4331|last3=Sullivan|first3=Eileen|last4=Crowley|first4=Michael}}</ref> White House economists published a study in September 2019 that warned a pandemic could kill half a million Americans and devastate the economy.<ref> ''[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/business/coronavirus-economy-trump.html White House Economists Warned in 2019 a Pandemic Could Devastate America]'' March 31, 2020 New York Times</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the WHO also ran a simulation exercise of a global pandemic response involving more than 40 countries, although the results appear to be unavailable.<ref>[https://www.who.int/ihr/eoc-exercise/en/ \"Simulation exercise puts global pandemic readiness to the test\"], World Health Organization, Dec. 3, 2018</ref>\n\n===Centralized biodefense strategy===\n\nCiting lessons learned from the swine flu pandemic, Ebola outbreak, and the [[2001 anthrax attacks]], President Trump released a [[National Biodefense Strategy]] on September 18, 2018 in response to a Congressional directive.<ref name=\"statement\">{{cite web |last1=Trump |first1=Donald |title=Statement from the President on the National Biodefense Strategy and National Security Presidential Memorandum |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-president-national-biodefense-strategy-national-security-presidential-memorandum/ |publisher=The White House |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"UPI\">{{cite news |last1=Brokaw |first1=Sommer |title=Trump signs presidential memo on national biodefense |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2018/09/18/Trump-signs-presidential-memo-on-national-biodefense/2071537290820/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |agency=United Press International |date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/4c21af485a7d4ccebb22f7316b55d014/White-House-sets-'new-direction'-in-biodefense-strategy|title=White House Sets 'New Direction' in Biodefense Strategy|date=September 18, 2018|agency=Associated Press|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=BartholomewOmberg>Rachel Bartholomew & Kristin Omberg, [https://thebulletin.org/2019/01/making-sense-of-the-2018-national-biodefense-strategy/ Making sense of the 2018 National Biodefense Strategy], ''Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists'' (January 18, 2019).</ref> According to Trump, the new strategy was designed to strengthen the nation's defenses against disease outbreaks and bioterrorism and to make responses to them more efficient and better coordinated.<ref name=\"statement\" /><ref name=\"UPI\" /> Concurrently, he released a National Security Presidential Memorandum that appointed the Secretary of HHS [[Alex Azar]] to oversee implementation of the government's new biodefense strategy and directed [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[John Bolton]] to assist in reviewing and improving the nation's biodefenses.<ref name=\"Owermohle\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/09/18/trump-hhs-biodefense-827973|title=Trump puts HHS in charge of defense against biological threats|last=Owermohle|first=Sarah|website=Politico|access-date=December 31, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Memo\">{{cite web |last1=Trump |first1=Donald |title=Presidential Memorandum on the Support for National Biodefense |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/presidential-memorandum-support-national-biodefense/ |publisher=The White House |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"statement\" /> At a time when multiple agencies and departments shared responsibility for biodefense,<ref name=BartholomewOmberg /> Bolton and Azar claimed this centralization of primary authority for biodefense in the HHS would provide greater accountability.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Watson |first1=Kathryn |title=Trump administration outlines new biodefense approach |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-administration-rolling-out-new-biodefense-strategy/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CBS |date=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Reorganization and departures===\n\nIn May 2018, Bolton reorganized the executive branch's [[United States National Security Council]] (NSC), largely merging the group responsible for global [[health security]] and [[biodefense]] into a bigger group responsible for [[counter-proliferation]] and biodefense. Along with the reorganization, the leader of the global health security and biodefense group, Rear Admiral [[Timothy Ziemer]], left to join another federal agency, while [[Tim Morrison (presidential advisor)|Tim Morrison]] became the leader of the combined group.<ref name=KellyMarch20>{{cite news |last1=Kessler |first1=Glenn |last2=Kelly |first2=Meg |title=Was the White House office for global pandemics eliminated? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/20/was-white-house-office-global-pandemics-eliminated |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"disband\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/ce014d94b64e98b7203b873e56f80e9a|title=Trump disbanded NSC pandemic unit that experts had praised|author-last=Riechmann|author-first=Deb|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> There were critics of this reorganization, who referred to it as \"disbanding\" a pandemic preparedness group; and later, Trump berated a reporter for asking if the reorganization had slowed the government response.<ref name=\"disband\" /><ref>Bethania Palma, ''[https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/experts-officials-pandemic-2018 Did Experts and Officials Warn in 2018 US Couldn't Respond Effectively to a Pandemic? Such individuals have made repeated warnings about U.S. readiness in the event of a pandemic.]'' 1 April 2020 [[Snopes]]</ref> Also in 2018, [[Homeland Security Advisor]] [[Tom Bossert]] left the administration; reportedly at Bolton's request. Bossert had helped to create the Trump administration's biodefense plans, and it was his responsibility to coordinate the government's response in the event of a biological crisis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robertson |first1=Lori |last2=McDonald |first2=Jessica |last3=Farley |first3=Robert |title=Democrats' Misleading Coronavirus Claims |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/democrats-misleading-coronavirus-claims/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 3, 2020 |work=[[Factcheck.org]]}}</ref> Bossert's successor, [[Doug Fears]], and Fears' successor [[Peter J. Brown]], took over the biodefense responsibilities of the DHS. ''[[Bloomberg News]]'' reported in January 2020 that biodefense was by then a \"less prominent\" part of the Homeland Security Advisor's responsibilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Jennifer |last2=Dlouhy |first2=Jennifer A. |title=Trump Homeland Security Adviser to Leave Soon, Sources Say |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-30/trump-s-homeland-security-adviser-fears-is-said-to-leave-soon |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work =Bloomberg News |date=April 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Jennifer |title=White House Homeland Security Aide Likely to Be Reassigned |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-19/white-house-homeland-security-adviser-being-shifted-out-of-job |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Bloomberg News |date=January 20, 2020}}</ref> The NSC created a pandemic playbook (called \"Playbook for Early Response to High-Consequence Emerging Infectious Disease Threats and Biological Incidents\") in 2016 which laid out strategies and recommendations that an administration should take, including moving swiftly to fully detect potential outbreaks, securing supplemental funding and considering invoking the [[Defense Production Act of 1950|Defense Production Act]], and making sure there are sufficient personal protective equipment available for healthcare workers. The Trump administration was briefed on it in 2017, but administration officials ignored it, and it never became official policy.<ref>Dan Diamond and Nahal Toosi, ''[https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/25/trump-coronavirus-national-security-council-149285 Trump team failed to follow NSC's pandemic playbook; The 69-page document, finished in 2016, provided a step by step list of priorities\u2014which were then ignored by the administration.]'' March 25, 2020 Politico.com</ref> Azar and Morrison, then a special assistant to the President and senior director for weapons of mass destruction and biodefense on the National Security Council, listed the threat of a pandemic as the issue that worried them most at the BioDefense Summit in April 2019.<ref>Andrew Kaczynski and Em Steck ''[https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/03/politics/kfile-officials-worried-over-pandemic-last-year/index.html Top administration officials said last year threat of pandemic kept them up at night]'' CNN April 3, 2020</ref>\n\nIn other departures, [[Luciana Borio]], the National Security Council director for medical and biodefense preparedness, left her post in March 2019. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported in March 2020 that the White House would not confirm the identity of Borio's replacement.<ref name=KellyMarch20/> Meanwhile, in July 2019, Linda Quick, a U.S. CDC expert working within the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]], left her post without a replacement, as her position would have been eliminated in September 2019 due to the [[China\u2013United States trade war]]. [[Reuters]] reported Quick's departure in March 2020; her role was training Chinese field epidemiologists to respond to disease outbreaks at their hotbeds; the post had existed since 2007 or earlier.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Marisa |title=Exclusive: U.S. axed CDC expert job in China months before virus outbreak |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-china-cdc-exclusiv/exclusive-u-s-axed-cdc-expert-job-in-china-months-before-virus-outbreak-idUSKBN21910S |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> The Administration ended funding for the [[PREDICT (USAID)|PREDICT]] pandemic early-warning program in China, which trained and supported staff in 60 foreign laboratories, with field work ceasing September 2019.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/science/story/2020-04-02/coronavirus-trump-pandemic-program-viruses-detection Trump administration ended coronavirus detection program] March 2, 2020 LATimes.com</ref> The scientists tasked with identifying potential pandemics were already stretched too far and thin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/why-the-coronavirus-slipped-past-disease-detectives |title=Why the Coronavirus Slipped Past Disease Detectives; Groups of scientists tasked with identifying pandemic-prone microbes were stretched too far and thin |author=Charles Schmidt |date=April 3, 2020 |website=[[Scientific American]] |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Abandoned and delayed efforts to improve mask and ventilator supply===\n\nSince 2015, the federal government has spent $9.8 million on two projects to prevent a mask shortage in the event of a pandemic, but abandoned both projects before completion.<ref name=\"wp-masks\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/federal-government-spent-millions-to-ramp-up-mask-readiness-but-that-isnt-helping-now/2020/04/03/d62dda5c-74fa-11ea-a9bd-9f8b593300d0_story.html|title=Federal government spent millions to ramp up mask readiness, but that isn't helping now|first=Jon |last=Swaine|website=Washington Post}}</ref> The first was a contract from the [[Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Authority]] (BARDA, which in 2020 had a budget of $1.5 billion) with Halyard Health (now a subsidiary of Owens & Minor) to design a machine capable of rapid manufacture of N95-rated masks. The design, intended to solve the problem of stockpile waste and decay, was completed in 2018. Halyard requested funding to build a prototype, but this was not granted.\n\nA second BARDA contract was signed with Applied Research Associates of Albuquerque, to design an N95-rated mask that could be reused in emergencies without reduced effectiveness. Though federal reports had called for such a project since 2006, the ARA contract wasn't signed until 2017, and missed its 15-month completion deadline, resulting in the 2020 pandemic reaching the United States before the design was ready.<ref name=\"wp-masks\" />\n\nPrevious respiratory epidemics and government planning indicated a need for a stockpile of ventilators that were easier for less-trained medical personnel to use. BARDA Project Aura issued a [[request for proposals]] in 2008, with a goal of FDA approval in 2010 or 2011. A contract was awarded Newport Medical Instruments, a small ventilator manufacturer, with a target price of $3,000, much lower than more complicated machines costing over $10,000, and it produced prototypes with target FDA approval in 2013. [[Covidien]] purchased NMI and after for more money to complete the project (bringing the total cost to around $8 million) asked the government to cancel the contract, saying it wasn't profitable. The government awarded a new $13.8 million contract to [[Philips]], in 2014. The design for the Trilogy Evo Universal gained FDA approval in July 2019. The government ordered 10,000 ventilators in September 2019, with a mid-2020 deadline for the first deliveries and a deadline of 2022 to complete all 10,000. Despite the start of the epidemic in December, the capacity of the company to have produced enough to fill the full order, and the ability of the government to force faster production, the government did not reach an agreement with Philips for accelerated delivery until March 10, 2020.<ref name=\"nyt-vent\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/business/coronavirus-us-ventilator-shortage.html|title=The U.S. Tried to Build a New Fleet of Ventilators. The Mission Failed.|first1=Nicholas|last1=Kulish|first2=Sarah|last2=Kliff|first3=Jessica|last3=Silver-Greenberg|date=March 29, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"propublica-vent\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/taxpayers-paid-millions-to-design-a-low-cost-ventilator-for-a-pandemic-instead-the-company-is-selling-versions-of-it-overseas- |title=Taxpayers Paid Millions to Design a Low-Cost Ventilator for a Pandemic. Instead, the Company Is Selling Versions of It Overseas. |author1=Sebastian Rotella|author2=Patricia Callahan|author3=Tim Golden |date=March 30, 2020 |website=ProPublica.org}}</ref> By mid-March, the need for more ventilators had become immediate, and even in the absence of any government contracts, other manufacturers announced plans to make many tens of thousands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/01/824610787/fema-hadnt-ordered-ventilators-manufacturers-forged-ahead-anyway|title=FEMA Hadn't Ordered Ventilators. Manufacturers Forged Ahead Anyway|website=NPR.org}}</ref> In the meantime, Philips had been selling a commercial version, the Trilogy Evo, at much higher prices,<ref name=\"propublica-vent\" /> leaving only 12,700 in the Strategic National Stockpile as of March 15.<ref name=\"nyt-vent\" />\n\nCompared to the small amount of money spent on recommended supplies for a pandemic, billions of dollars had been spent by the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] to create and store a vaccine for [[anthrax]], and enough [[smallpox]] inoculations for the entire country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/coronavirus-strategic-national-stockpile-was-ready-but-not-for-this-135266|title=Coronavirus: Strategic National Stockpile was ready, but not for this|first=Andrew|last=Lakoff|website=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]}}</ref> Shortages in the United States and many European countries were contrasted with Finland, which has maintained medical stockpiles since the 1950s, and was able to meet demand for masks from the government supply.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/world/europe/coronavirus-finland-masks.html|title=Finland, 'Prepper Nation of the Nordics,' Isn't Worried About Masks|first1=Christina|last1=Anderson|first2=Henrik Pryser|last2=Libell|date=April 5, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Beginning of outbreak and supply shortages===\n\n{{See Also|Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\nThe first known case of COVID-19 in the U.S. was confirmed by the CDC on January 21, 2020.<ref name=CNN20200329 /> An unclassified Army briefing document, prepared February 3, on the coronavirus projected that \"between 80,000 and 150,000 could die\". The estimates also correctly stated that [[Asymptomatic carrier|asymptomatic]] people could \"easily\" [[Transmission (medicine)|transmit]] the virus, that military forces could be tasked with providing logistics and medical support to civilians, including \"provid[ing] PPE (N-95 Face Mask, Eye Protection, and Gloves) to evacuees, staff, and DoD personnel\".<ref>James LaPorta and Spencer Ackerman ''[https://www.thedailybeast.com/army-warned-in-early-february-that-coronavirus-could-kill-150000-americans Army Warned in Early February That Coronavirus Could Kill 150,000 Americans]'' April 3, 2020 [[The Daily Beast]]</ref> Trump administration officials declined an offer for congressional coronavirus funding on February 5. The officials, including HHS Secretary [[Alex Azar]], said they \"didn't need emergency funding, that they would be able to handle it within existing appropriations,\" Senator [[Chris Murphy]] recalled.<ref>Suzanne Smalley ''[https://news.yahoo.com/senator-says-white-house-turned-down-emergency-coronavirus-funding-in-early-february-003319950.html Senator says White House turned down emergency coronavirus funding in early February]'' March 27, 2020 news.yahoo.com</ref> On February{{nbsp}}7 [[Mike Pompeo]] announced the administration donated more than 35,000 pounds of \"masks, gowns, gauze, respirators, and other vital materials\" to China the same day the WHO warned about \"the limited stock of PPE ([[personal protective equipment]])\".<ref name=CNN20200329 >Dean Obeidallah [https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/29/opinions/coronavirus-personal-protective-equipment-obeidallah Trump administration sent protective medical gear to China while he minimized the virus threat to US] CNN March 30, 2020</ref>\n\n''[[National Geographic]]'' reported that as of March 3, 2020, the \"U.S. has only a fraction of the medical supplies it needs to combat coronavirus.\" An additional 300 million N95 [[Respirator|respirators]] and [[surgical mask]]s could be required to protect health workers. However, in Senate testimony, U.S. HHS Secretary Alex Azar said \"the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] has just 30 million surgical masks and 12 million respirators in reserve.\" HHS said it intends to purchase as many as half a billion respirators and surgical face masks over the next year and a half. A previous 2015 CDC study found that seven billion N95 respirators might be necessary to handle a \"severe respiratory outbreak\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Akpan |first1=Nsikan |title=U.S. has only a fraction of the medical supplies it needs to combat coronavirus.|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/science/2020/03/us-america-has-fraction-medical-supplies-it-needs-to-combat-coronavirus/? |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> March 12 the HHS placed its first order of masks and ventilators for healthcare workers of $4.8 million worth of N95 masks.<ref>Michael Biesecker ''[https://apnews.com/090600c299a8cf07f5b44d92534856bc US 'wasted' months before preparing for coronavirus pandemic]'' April 6, 2020 APNews.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/4/5/21208802/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-masks-march |title=Trump administration didn't order ventilators or masks until mid-March |publisher=Vox |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Vessel manifests maintained by [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] showed a steady flow of the medical equipment needed to treat the coronavirus being shipped abroad as recently as March 17. [[FEMA]], meanwhile, said the agency \"has not actively encouraged or discouraged U.S. companies from exporting overseas\", and has asked USAID to send back its reserves of protective gear stored in warehouses for use in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/31/pence-task-force-coronavirus-aid-157806|title=Pence task force freezes coronavirus aid amid backlash|website=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/04/01/coronavirus-medical-supplies-export |title=Key Medical Supplies Exported From U.S. to Foreign Buyers |publisher=Theintercept.com |date=2020-04-01 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' reported on March 18 that about 170,000 [[ventilators]] were in the U.S., versus an [[American Hospital Association]] estimate that 960,000 people may need them during the pandemic. The [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|shortage of ventilators]] is one reason why slowing the spread of the virus is so important. Ramping up production is challenging due to global supply chains and the complexity of the devices, with major U.S. hospitals having trouble finding more.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kliff |first1=Sarah |title=There Aren't Enough Ventilators to Cope With the Coronavirus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/business/coronavirus-ventilator-shortage.html|accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> ''Bloomberg News'' reported on March 23 that: \"NY Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] said the state, which has about 5,000 to 6,000 ventilators, might need 30,000 of them.\" China is significantly increasing ventilator production to assist other countries, with plans to supply about 14,000 non-invasive ventilators in April. The U.S. government has also called on U.S. manufacturers to assist.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hong |first1=Jishan |title=China's Factories Work 24/7 to Build Ventilators for Milan, New York|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-23/china-s-factories-work-24-7-to-build-ventilators-for-milan-ny? |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n{{further|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak New York CSA per capita cases map.svg|thumb|Confirmed cases per 10,000 residents near [[New York City]]. With around 200,000 as of April 8, the [[New York metropolitan area]] contains about half the nation's confirmed cases.]]\n\nChinese health authorities confirmed that they identified a cluster of a novel infectious coronavirus on December 31, 2019 in the city of Wuhan, officially reporting their findings on January 7, 2020. An American citizen, after traveling from Wuhan, China, to his home in Washington state, became the first U.S. case of the new virus on January 20.<ref name=nejm>[https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMoa2001191 \"First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States\"], ''The New England Journal of Medicine'', March 5, 2020</ref> The WHO declared the outbreak a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] by January 30<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boseley |first1=Sarah |title=WHO declares coronavirus a global health emergency |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/30/who-declares-coronavirus-a-global-health-emergency |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> and a [[pandemic]] by March 11.<ref name=\"nyt sports\"/>\n\nCertain European countries, including [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|Spain]], and the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]], reported on their first coronavirus cases in late January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_gennaio_30/coronavirus-italia-corona-9d6dc436-4343-11ea-bdc8-faf1f56f19b7.shtml |title=Coronavirus, primi due casi in Italia: sono due turisti cinesi |date=30 January 2020 |website=Corriere della Sera |language=it |access-date=28 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217050130/https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_gennaio_30/coronavirus-italia-corona-9d6dc436-4343-11ea-bdc8-faf1f56f19b7.shtml |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web |url=https://elpais.com/sociedad/2020/01/31/actualidad/1580509404_469734.html |title=Sanidad confirma en La Gomera el primer caso de coronavirus en Espa\u00f1a |date=31 January 2020 |website=El Pais |language=es |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131225909/https://elpais.com/sociedad/2020/01/31/actualidad/1580509404_469734.html |archive-date=31 January 2020 |access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/18198651.man-believed-chinese-national-taken-hospital-falling-ill-york-hotel/ |title=Chinese national taken to hospital after falling ill at Yorkshire hotel |date=30 January 2020 |work=Telegraph & Argus |access-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131133426/https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/18198651.man-believed-chinese-national-taken-hospital-falling-ill-york-hotel/ |archive-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> More than 3.4 million people from China, Italy, Spain, and the United Kingdom, including returning Americans, entered the U.S. in the first three months since the COVID-19 outbreak in Wuhan. From December 2019 to February 2020, 759,493 passengers arrived on American soil from China, 343,402 came from Italy, 418,848 from Spain, and about 1.9 million more arrived from Britain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Disaster in motion: 3.4 million travelers poured into US as coronavirus pandemic erupted |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/disaster-motion-34-million-travelers-poured-us-coronavirus/story?id=69933625 |work=ABC News |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Research on coronavirus genomes indicates the majority of COVID-19 cases in New York came from European travelers, rather than directly from China or any other Asian country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Studies Show N.Y. Outbreak Originated in Europe|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/us/coronavirus-live-updates.html |work=The New York Times |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In March 2020, the [[European Commission]]'s president [[Ursula von der Leyen]] and other EU leaders condemned the U.S. decision to restrict travel from the coronavirus-affected [[European Union]] to the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=EU condemns Trump travel ban from Europe as virus spreads |url=https://apnews.com/4552fd280d06cf83c63e4cc9b08fe5ce |work=Associated Press (AP) |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Donald Trump defends his European travel ban amid virus outbreak |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-donald-trump-bans-all-travel-from-mainland-europe-to-us-for-30-days-11955860 |work=Sky News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]] announced between late January and mid-March, the United States government denied entry to foreign nationals who had traveled within the past 14 days through China, Iran, the United Kingdom, Ireland, or the 26 European countries that comprise the [[Schengen Area]]. Americans returning home after traveling in these regions were required to undergo a health screening and submit to a 14-day [[quarantine]].<ref>{{cite news |title=DHS Issues Supplemental Instructions for Inbound Flights with Individuals Who Have Been in China|url=https://www.dhs.gov/news/2020/02/02/dhs-issues-supplemental-instructions-inbound-flights-individuals-who-have-been-china|accessdate=March 9, 2020 |agency=[[Department of Homeland Security]]|date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Colarossi |first1=Natalie |last2=Cranley |first2=Ellen |title=The CDC is urging residents in New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut to refrain from travel because of the coronavirus |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-government-travel-warnings-for-coronavirus-outbreak-2020-2#the-us-state-department-has-implemented-travel-restrictions-barring-most-non-us-citizens-or-permanent-residents-from-entering-the-country-from-europe-the-uk-and-ireland-6 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Such quarantines are governed by section 361 of the [[Public Health Service Act]] (42 U.S. Code \u00a7 264).<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S.C. Title 42\u2014THE PUBLIC HEALTH AND WELFARE |url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2011-title42/html/USCODE-2011-title42-chap6A-subchapII-partG.htm |website=govinfo.gov |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=myth13>{{cite web |author=Live Science Staff 10 |title=13 Coronavirus myths busted by science |url=https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-myths.html |website=livescience.com |date=March 2020}}</ref> In early March, the CDC advised Americans against non-essential travel to China, Iran, Malaysia, and the aforementioned European countries.<ref name=\"Madrigal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/how-many-americans-have-been-tested-coronavirus/607597/|title=Exclusive: The Strongest Evidence Yet That America Is Botching Coronavirus Testing|last=Madrigal|first=Robinson Meyer, Alexis C.|date=March 6, 2020|website=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref>\n\nThroughout March and early April, several state, city, and county governments imposed [[Stay-at-home order|\"stay at home\"]] [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|quarantines on their populations]] to stem the spread of the virus.<ref name=\"Norwood\">{{cite news |last1=Norwood |first1=Candace |title=Most states have issued stay-at-home orders, but enforcement varies widely |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/most-states-have-issued-stay-at-home-orders-but-enforcement-varies-widely |accessdate=9 April 2020 |publisher=PBS |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> By the middle of March, all fifty states were able to perform tests, with a doctor's approval, either from the CDC or from commercial labs in a state, but the number of available test kits remained limited,<ref name=\"theatlantic.com\">[https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/why-coronavirus-testing-us-so-delayed/607954/ \"The 4 Key Reasons the U.S. Is So Behind on Coronavirus Testing\"], Atlantic Monthly, March 15, 2020</ref> which meant the true number of people infected with the virus was a challenge to estimate with any reasonable accuracy at the time. The CDC suggested that doctors use their own judgment along with certain guidelines before authorizing a test. By March 12, diagnosed cases of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} in the U.S. exceeded a thousand, which doubled every two days to reach more than 17,000 by March 20.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/11/coronavirus-live-updates/ Live updates: As U.S. coronavirus cases top 1,000, mixed signs of recovery in China, South Korea], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', Adam Taylor and Teo Armus, March 11, 2020. Retrieved March 11, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/health/us-coronavirus-case-updates-wednesday/index.html US coronavirus cases soar past 8,500 as officials try to head off overwhelming effects], Holly Yan, Christina Maxouris and Steve Almasy, CNN, March 18, 2020</ref>\n\nAdministration officials warned on March 19 that the number of cases would begin to rise sharply as the country's testing capacity substantially increased.<ref name=\"CBSTesting\">{{cite news |last1=Kates |first1=Graham |title=Confirmed coronavirus cases will jump as testing ramps up |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-confirmed-cases-rise-tests/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |publisher=CBS |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Around this time, the United States began running 50,000 to 70,000 coronavirus tests per day.<ref name=\"GageTesting\">{{cite news |last1=Gage |first1=John |title='Transformed the testing process': Deborah Birx says US has done more coronavirus testing in eight days than South Korea in eight weeks |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/transformed-the-testing-process-deborah-birx-says-us-has-done-more-coronavirus-testing-in-eight-days-than-south-korea-in-eight-weeks |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |publisher=Washington Examiner |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 26, the total number of confirmed cases surpassed that of China with over 85,000, making the U.S. the country with the highest number of coronavirus patients in the world.<ref name=\"SA-20200326\">{{cite news |last1=Berke |first1=Jeremy |last2=McFall-Johnsen |first2=Morgan |title=USA Now Has More COVID-19 Cases Than Any Other Country in The World |url=https://www.sciencealert.com/usa-is-now-the-centre-of-the-covid-19-outbreak-as-their-case-numbers-top-italy-s |date=March 26, 2020 |work=ScienceAlert.com |accessdate=March 27, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20200326\">{{cite news |last=McNeil, Jr. |first=Donald G. |title=The U.S. Now Leads the World in Confirmed Coronavirus Cases\u2014Following a series of missteps, the nation is now the epicenter of the pandemic. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/health/usa-coronavirus-cases.html |date=March 26, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52056586 Coronavirus: US overtakes China with most cases], BBC, March 27, 2020</ref> The country reached another critical mark, as the number of positive cases surged over 100,000 the next day on March 27.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chan |first1=Christine |last2=Shumaker |first2=Lisa |last3=Maler |first3=Sandra |title=Confirmed coronavirus cases in U.S. reach 100,000: Reuters tally |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-cases/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-in-u-s-reach-100000-reuters-tally-idUSKBN21E3DA |date=March 28, 2020 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=March 28, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe COVID-19 outbreak has had varying effects on different areas of the U.S. Of the 154 known deaths in the country before March 20, 94 occurred [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington (state)|in the state of Washington]], with 35 of those [[Life Care Centers of America#Kirkland, Washington COVID-19 outbreak|at one nursing home]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/news/2020/March/20-covid.aspx |title=Additional testing capacity, adjustments at King County jails, and other COVID-19 updates from Public Health\u2014Seattle & King County for March 20, 2020 |publisher=King County |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> By late March, the toll was greatest in New York, which saw 56% of all confirmed U.S. cases on March 25.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Xu Klein |first1=Jodi |title=Coronavirus: New York Governor Andrew Cuomo says early signs show social distancing may be working |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/3077011/coronavirus-new-york-governor-andrew-cuomo-says-early-signs-show-social |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Continuing into April, the New York City metropolitan area remained the country's epicenter for the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arnold |first1=Kyle |title=American Airlines axes most flights to New York area, the country's COVID-19 epicenter |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/business/airlines/2020/04/06/american-airlines-axes-most-flights-to-new-york-city-region-the-countrys-covid-19-epicenter/ |accessdate=9 April 2020 |publisher=Dallas Morning News |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New York, New Jersey area remains epicenter of outbreak |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/video/new-york-new-jersey-area-remains-epicenter-of-outbreak-81759301893 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |publisher=NBC News |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\n\n{{further|Criticism of response to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United States government}}\n\n===Task force formation===\n\n[[File:Coronavirus_Task_Force_Press_Briefing_(49608829838).jpg|thumb|[[Mike Pence]] delivers remarks at a Coronavirus Task Force briefing on February 29, accompanied by [[Alex Azar]] and [[Anthony Fauci]]]]\n\nTrump administration officials were briefed to the coronavirus outbreak in China on January 3, 2020.<ref>Alissa Wilkinson [https://www.vox.com/2020/4/5/21208802/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-masks-march Report: The Trump administration didn't order ventilators or masks until mid-March] Vox.com April 5, 2020</ref> Health officials first substantially briefed the president about the virus on January 18, when HHS Secretary Alex Azar called Trump while he was at [[Mar-a-Lago]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abutaleb |first1=Yasmeen |last2=Dawsey |first2=Josh |last3=Nakashima |first3=Ellen |last4=Miller |first4=Greg |title=The U.S. was beset by denial and dysfunction as the coronavirus raged |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2020/04/04/coronavirus-government-dysfunction/?arc404=true |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Harris>{{cite news |last1=Harris |first1=Shane |last2=Miller |first2=Greg |last3=Dawsey |first3=Josh |last4=Nakashima |first4=Ellen |title=U.S. intelligence reports from January and February warned about a likely pandemic |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/us-intelligence-reports-from-january-and-february-warned-about-a-likely-pandemic/2020/03/20/299d8cda-6ad5-11ea-b5f1-a5a804158597_story.html |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> On January 27, then-acting chief of staff [[Mick Mulvaney]] convened a meeting in his office with White House aides in order to draw greater attention to the virus among senior officials.<ref name=Harris/>\n\nTwo days later, on January 29, President Trump established the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] to coordinate and oversee efforts to \"monitor, prevent, contain, and mitigate the spread\" of COVID-19 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-regarding-presidents-coronavirus-task-force/|title=Statement from the Press Secretary Regarding the President's Coronavirus Task Force|website=The White House}}</ref> Secretary Azar was appointed as the leader of the task force.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-2019)|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Jan29WH\" /> On February 26, Trump appointed Vice President [[Mike Pence]] to take charge of the nation's response to the virus.<ref name=NYT-Pence>{{cite news |last1=Shear |first1=Michael |last2=Weiland |first2=Noah |last3=Rogers |first3=Katie |title=Trump Names Mike Pence to Lead Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-cdc.html |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=February 26, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200227003735/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-cdc.html |archivedate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> [[FEMA]] was put in charge of procuring medical supplies on March 17.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/pritzker-illinois-states-competing-medical-supplies/index.html?fbclid=IwAR2V-qnW7rlWo8NNUZs_F6BaQDDoyURi-y1BUbLt5pp40odOt5ggZcrhs5w|title=Illinois governor says 'it's a wild west' for medical supplies because of Trump's response to states' requests|accessdate=March 23, 2020|date=March 22, 2020|author=Devan Cole}}</ref><ref>[https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/22/trump-wants-defeat-coronavirus-credit-143531?fbclid=IwAR3gFHc5e-sTTlP2uQJsE302d-7WT8KV68Hl9HO92Pzd-XBfb8DwJzR3xtM Trump wants to defeat coronavirus\u2014and make sure he gets credit] By NANCY COOK, ''Politico'', March 22, 2020. Retrieved March 23, 2020</ref>\n\n===Containment and mitigation===\n\n{{See also|Workplace hazard controls for COVID-19}}\n\nThe early phases of public health efforts for epidemics and pandemics are to contain or limit further outbreaks. Those actions often involve tracing contacts, implementing quarantines, and isolating infectious cases. They demand significant human resources and government staffing at all levels. As an outbreak grows, new facilities may need to be constructed to manage additional infectious cases.<ref name=NCBI>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525302/ \"Pandemics: Risks, Impacts, and Mitigation\"], [[National Center for Biotechnology Information]] (NCBI)</ref>\n\nNational medical organizations such as the CDC focus on both containment, to first keep the virus from spreading after its detection, and mitigation, to prevent it from spreading quickly beyond containment limits. The process of mitigating the COVID-19 pandemic attempts to extend its time frame by spreading out cases and isolating individuals, which slows the spread of the disease. By that means, it lowers the peak number of new cases, which reduces the likelihood of suddenly over-crowding doctors' offices and hospitals beyond their capacity.<ref name=cleveland>[https://www.cleveland.com/news/2020/03/mad-about-coronavirus-cancellations-heres-why-mitigating-the-curve-matters.html \"Mad about coronavirus cancellations? Here's why mitigating the curve matters\"], ''The Plain Dealer'', March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nThe risk of a truly global pandemic is limited for some diseases, such as [[Ebola]], because of the slow pace of transmission or high probability of detection and containment. COVID-19, at the other extreme, is a pathogen that has high potential to cause a severe pandemic because it easily transmits between people and remains asymptomatic for a long period, thereby lengthening the time it is infectious and not detected.<ref name=NCBI/>\n\nIn general, once a pandemic has begun within a country's borders, the government must begin taking steps to curtail interactions between infected and uninfected populations. The methods used could include isolation of infected patients, quarantine, physical distancing practices, school closures, use of personal protective equipment, and [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|travel restrictions]].<ref name=NCBI/>\n\nThe WHO on January 30 warned that \"all countries should be prepared for containment, including active surveillance, early detection, isolation and case management, [[contact tracing]] and prevention of onward spread\" of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=WHO Declares Coronavirus Outbreak A Global Health Emergency |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/01/30/798894428/who-declares-coronavirus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |publisher=NPR |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> February 25 was the first day the CDC told the American public to prepare for an outbreak.<ref>Marisa Taylor ''[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-china-cdc-exclusiv-idUSKBN21910S Exclusive: U.S. axed CDC expert job in China months before virus outbreak]'' March 22, 2020 Reuters.com</ref>\n\nAt a White House press briefing on April 1, 2020, [[Anthony Fauci|Dr. Anthony S. Fauci]] said that, even though he expected \"social distancing\" rules can eventually be relaxed even before the availability of a vaccine, a vaccine will still be necessary to end the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Noack|first=Rick|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/04/01/coronavirus-latest-news/|title=As U.S. death toll surpasses 4,600, Fauci says the real turning point in coronavirus mitigation won't happen until there's a vaccine|date=April 1, 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Wagner|first2=John|last3=Beachum|first3=Lateshia|last4=Horton|first4=Alex|last5=Miriam Berger, Brittany Shammas, Eva Dou, Felicia Sonmez, Meryl Kornfield, Candace Buckner, Michael Brice-Saddler, Sindya N. Bhanoo, Teo Armus}}</ref>\n\n====Travel and entry restrictions====\n\n{{See|Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:200318-H-NI589-120 (49679050593).jpg|thumb|A U.S. Customs and Border Protection officer checks the travel documents of a pilot arriving from an international flight]]\n\nOn January 31, President Trump imposed travel restrictions preventing foreign nationals from entering the U.S. if they had been in China within the previous two weeks. The immediate family members of U.S. citizens and permanent residents were exempt from this restriction.<ref name=\"USA Today quarantine\" /><ref name=\"AP ban\" /> By this time, three major U.S. airlines had already suspended flights between the U.S. and China,<ref name=Koenig>{{cite news |last1=Koenig |first1=David |last2=Bussewitz |first2=Cathy |last3=Pisani |first3=Joseph |title=Delta, American and United suspend flights between US, China |url=https://apnews.com/7a165f73821fdd44e321a38be005886c |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> although one of these, [[United Airlines]], continued select flights for returning Americans.<ref name=\"ChineseAirlines\" /> Major Chinese carriers did not begin suspending flights from China to the United States until three days after the announcement of the travel restrictions.<ref name=\"ChineseAirlines\">{{cite news |last1=Pham |first1=Sherisse |last2=Wang |first2=Serenitie |title=First major Chinese airliner suspends flights to the United States over coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/03/business/china-eastern-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition to restricting foreign nationals, Trump imposed a quarantine for up to 14 days on American citizens returning from [[Hubei]], the main coronavirus hotspot at the time. This was the first quarantine order the U.S. federal government had issued in over 50 years.<ref name=\"USA Today quarantine\" /><ref name=\"AP ban\">{{cite news |last1=Moritsugu |first1=Ken |last2=Miller |first2=Zeke |title=US bars foreigners coming from China for now over virus fear |url=https://apnews.com/9e22f8aabe2f454593b9f9b4c67eb31f |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Although the WHO had recommended against travel restrictions at the time,<ref>{{cite news |title=WHO says countries should keep borders open, trade & people moving despite coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-who/who-says-countries-should-keep-borders-open-trade-people-moving-despite-coronavirus-idUSKBN1ZU1C2 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=Reuters |date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> HHS Secretary Alex Azar said the decision stemmed from the recommendations of HHS health officials.<ref name=factcheck>[https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/the-facts-on-trumps-travel-restrictions/ \"The Facts on Trump's Travel Restrictions\"], ''Factcheck'', March 6, 2020</ref> Trump expanded those travel restrictions to Iran on February 29.<ref name=factcheck/>\n\nOver the following few weeks, the Trump administration imposed a number of other travel restrictions:\n\n* In mid-February, the CDC opposed allowing fourteen people who had tested positive for COVID-19 while passengers on the cruise ship ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' to be flown back to the U.S. without completing a 14-day quarantine. They were overruled by officials at the U.S. State Department.<ref name=\"ARS CDC 14\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/02/coronavirus-patients-flew-to-us-after-cdc-explicitly-recommended-against-it/|title=CDC didn't want 14 coronavirus patients flown to US\u2014it was overruled|last=Mole|first=Beth|date=February 21, 2020|website=[[Ars Technica]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228022158/https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/02/coronavirus-patients-flew-to-us-after-cdc-explicitly-recommended-against-it/|archive-date=February 28, 2020|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n* On March 12, the CDC recommended against any non-essential travel to China,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/novel-coronavirus-china|title=COVID-19 in China|publisher=CDC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> most of Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-europe|title=COVID-19 in Europe|publisher=CDC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Iran,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-iran|title=COVID-19 in Iran|publisher=CDC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Malaysia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-malaysia|title=COVID-19 in Malaysia\u2014Warning\u2014Level 3, Avoid Nonessential Travel\u2014Travel Health Notices {{!}} Travelers' Health {{!}} CDC|website=wwwnc.cdc.gov|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> and South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-south-korea|title=COVID-19 in South Korea|publisher=CDC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=USATodayBan>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/2020/03/12/coronavirus-state-department-warns-americans-reconsider-traveling-abroad/5029446002/|title=State Department warns Americans to reconsider traveling abroad due to coronavirus|last=Tate|first=Curtis|website=USA Today|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The following week, the [[U.S. Department of State]] recommended that U.S. citizens not travel abroad, while those who are abroad should \"arrange for immediate return to the United States\" unless prepared to remain abroad indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wong|first=Edward|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/us/politics/coronavirus-state-department-travel.html|title=As Pandemic Grows, U.S. Warns Americans Not to Travel Abroad|date=March 19, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 20, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/ea/travel-advisory-alert-global-level-4-health-advisory-issue.html|title=Global Level 4 Health Advisory\u2014Do Not Travel|publisher=[[United States Department of State]]|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* On March 19, the State Department suspended routine visa services at all American embassies and consulates worldwide.<ref>[https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/News/visas-news/suspension-of-routine-visa-services.html \"Suspension of Routine Visa Services\"], Dept. of State, March 20, 2020</ref>\n* By March 20, the U.S. began barring entry to foreign nationals who had been in 28 European countries within the past 14 days. American citizens, [[Green card|permanent residents]], and their immediate families returning from abroad could re-enter the United States under the new restrictions, but those returning from one of the specified countries must undergo health screenings and submit to quarantines and monitoring for up to 14 days. In addition to the earlier travel restrictions in place, Trump extended this quarantine and monitoring requirement to those coming from Iran and the entirety of China. Flights from all restricted countries are required to land at one of 13 airports where the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) has \"enhanced\" entry screenings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/news/2020/03/17/fact-sheet-dhs-notice-arrival-restrictions-china-iran-and-certain-countries-europe|title=Fact Sheet: DHS Notice of Arrival Restrictions on China, Iran and Certain Countries of Europe|date=March 17, 2020|website=Department of Homeland Security|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today quarantine\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/01/31/coronavirus-donald-trump-declares-public-health-emergency/4625299002/ |title=Trump administration declares coronavirus emergency, orders first quarantine in 50 years |last=Jackson |first=David |website=[[USA Today]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205090931/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/01/31/coronavirus-donald-trump-declares-public-health-emergency/4625299002/ |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> At least 241 foreigners (including several Canadians), who had recently traveled in China and Iran, were denied entry to the United States between February{{nbsp}}2 and March 3.<ref>{{cite news|date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=DHS denies 241 people entry at US ports and airports over coronavirus|last=Sands|first=Geneva|publisher=CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/05/politics/dhs-denies-entry-coronavirus/index.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=U.S. refuses entry to more than 100 people from Canada as a result of coronavirus measures|last=Panetta|first=Alexander|publisher=[[CBC News]] |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/us-coronavirus-border-canada-1.5487696}}</ref>\n\n====Containment efforts within the U.S.====\n\n{{See|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Montana National Guard begins COVID-19 screening around the state.jpg|thumb|April 3: [[Montana National Guard]] screen out-of-state travelers at the [[Shelby station|Amtrak station]] in [[Shelby, Montana]]]]\n\nAs part of the early efforts to contain and mitigate the pandemic within the United States, Surgeon General [[Jerome Adams]] announced in early March that local leaders would soon have to consider whether to cancel large gatherings, consider telework policies, and close schools.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/08/health-officials-coronavirus-elderly-sick-risk-123889 \"Health officials shift tone on coronavirus, say elderly and sick at risk\"], ''Politico'', March 8, 2020</ref> Over the next few weeks, a number of states imposed lockdown measures of diverse scope and severity, which placed limits on where people can travel, work and shop away from their homes.<ref name=WSJ-lockdowns>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-state-by-state-guide-to-coronavirus-lockdowns-11584749351?mod=theme_coronavirus-ribbon \"A Guide to State Coronavirus Lockdowns\"], ''The Wall Street Journal'', March 21, 2020</ref>\n\nBy March 21, governors in New York, California and other large states had ordered most businesses to close and for people to stay inside, with limited exceptions. The order in New York, for instance, exempts financial institutions, some retailers, pharmacies, hospitals, manufacturing plants and transportation companies, among others. It placed a ban on non-essential gatherings of any size and for any reason.<ref name=WSJ-lockdowns/>\n\nIn late March, Trump announced that the National Guard would be deployed to California, New York, and Washington, and FEMA would send large medical stations with thousands of beds to the three states.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/coronavirus-live-updates-us-now-highest-globally-covid/story?id=69733219|title=National Guard to deploy against coronavirus in NY, California, Washington|date=March 22, 2020|work=ABC News|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The city of Chicago said it would rent more than a thousand empty hotel rooms to house coronavirus patients who need to be isolated but do not require hospitalization.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/chicago-to-rent-out-hotel-rooms-for-coronavirus-patients-isolation-2020-3 \"Chicago will start renting more than 1,000 of its empty hotel rooms to house coronavirus patients or those awaiting test results\"], ''Business Insider'', March 23, 2020</ref> Containment and care facilities would include two Navy hospital ships.<ref name=ships/> {{USNS|Mercy|T-AH-19|6}} arrived in Los Angeles on March 27,<ref name = mercyarrives/> and {{USNS|Comfort|T-AH-20|6}} arrived in New York City on March 30.<ref name=comfortarrives/>\n\nOn March 28, the president said he had decided not to enact a tri-state lockdown of New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut, after having publicly suggested earlier in the day that he was considering such a move; instead he ordered the CDC to issue a travel advisory suggesting voluntary travel limitations in these states.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Live Updates: Trump Says a Quarantine 'Will Not Be Necessary' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/28/world/coronavirus-live-news-updates.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs April began, various state and local officials, including the mayors of New York<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2020/04/02/new-york-city-urges-all-residents-to-wear-face-coverings-in-public-1271059|title=New York City urges all residents to wear face coverings in public|first=Erin|last=Durkin|website=Politico|date=2020-04-02|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> and Los Angeles,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-02/face-masks-could-provide-coronavirus-protection-california-health-officials-say|title=Face masks could provide coronavirus protection. But there's a 'but'|date=April 2, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> and the governors or health departments of Colorado,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kdvr.com/news/coronavirus/gov-polis-wear-face-coverings-when-going-out-of-your-home/|title=Gov. Polis: Wear face coverings when going out of your home|date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Pennsylvania,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/coronavirus-update-15000-chromebooks-donated-to-phillys-charter-catholic-schools/|title=Coronavirus update: Gov. Tom Wolf asks Pennsylvanians to wear masks outdoors|website=[[WHYY-TV]]|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> and Rhode Island<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/health-dept-encourages-rhode-islanders-to-wear-cloth-masks-in-public/|title=Health Dept. encourages Rhode Islanders to wear cloth masks in public|work=[[WPRI-TV]]|publisher=[[Nexstar Media Group]]|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> encouraged residents to wear non-medical cloth face coverings while in public, as an additional measure to prevent unknowingly infecting others. The CDC issued a similar recommendation on April 3. Health officials have generally advised against the use of medical-grade personal protective equipment (such as [[surgical mask]]s and [[respirator]]s) by the general public, as they should be saved for healthcare personnel due to shortages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/u-s-expected-recommend-masks-americans-coronavirus-hotspots-n1175596|title=CDC recommends people wear cloth masks in public\u2014but Trump says he won't|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/science/story/2020-04-03/cdc-recommends-wearing-face-masks-during-coronavirus-pandemic|title=CDC recommends wearing face masks during coronavirus pandemic|date=2020-04-03|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 testing===\n\n{{See also|COVID-19 testing|Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic }}\n[[File:Full-list-cumulative-total-tests-per-million.svg|thumb|Timeline of Number of tests per million people in different countries.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) \u2013 Statistics and Research|first1=Max|last1=Roser|first2=Hannah|last2=Ritchie|first3=Esteban|last3=Ortiz-Ospina|date=March 4, 2020|journal=Our World in Data|via=ourworldindata.org}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Colorado National Guard (49673441472).jpg|thumb|Colorado National Guard, [[Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment|CDPHE]], and [[San Miguel County, Colorado|San Miguel County]] personnel assist at a drive-up testing center in [[Telluride, Colorado]]]]\n[[File:U.S. Government COVID-19 Response Plan, March 13, 2020.svg|thumb|The ''New York Times'' obtained this response plan by the HHS.]]\n\nBeyond identifying whether a person is currently infected, coronavirus testing helps health professionals ascertain how bad the epidemic is and where it is worst.<ref>[https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/13/coronavirus-testing-long-way-to-go/ \"Coronavirus testing is starting to get better\u2014but it has a long way to go\"], ''STAT'', March 13, 2020</ref> However, the accuracy of national statistics on the number of cases and deaths from the outbreak depend on knowing how many people are being tested every day, and how the available tests are being allocated. But as of late March, most countries do not provide official reports on tests performed, therefore there is no centralized WHO data on COVID-19 testing.<ref>[https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus-testing-source-data \"Coronavirus Testing\u2014Source Data\"], ''Our World of Data'', March 20, 2020</ref>\n\nWhile the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) opted to use an approach developed by Germany to test for COVID-19, the United States developed its own testing approach. The German testing method was made public on January 13, and the American testing method was made public on January 28. The WHO did not offer any test kits to the U.S. because the U.S. normally had the supplies to produce their own tests.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |last2=Knight |first2=Victoria |title=Mostly False: Joe Biden stated on March 15, 2020 in a Democratic primary debate: \"The World Health Organization offered the testing kits that they have available and to give it to us now. We refused them. We did not want to buy them.\" |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/16/joe-biden/biden-falsely-says-trump-administration-rejected-w/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In February, the U.S. CDC produced 160,000 coronavirus tests, but soon it was discovered that many were defective and gave inaccurate readings.<ref name=\"WhoriskeyMarch16\">{{cite news |last1=Whoriskey |first1=Peter |last2=Satija |first2=Neena |title=How U.S. coronavirus testing stalled: Flawed tests, red tape and resistance to using the millions of tests produced by the WHO |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/16/cdc-who-coronavirus-tests/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenen |first1=Joanne |title=How testing failures allowed coronavirus to sweep the U.S. |url=http://www.politico.com/amp/news/2020/03/06/coronavirus-testing-failure-123166 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> Although academic laboratories and hospitals had developed their own tests, they were not allowed to use them until February 29, when the FDA issued approvals for them and private companies.<ref name=\"WhoriskeyMarch16\"/> Approvals were required by federal law due to the outbreak being declared as a public health emergency.<ref name=LeeMarch21>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Timothy |title=America is finally testing for coronavirus in significant volumes |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/america-is-finally-testing-for-coronavirus-in-significant-volumes/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[Ars Technica]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, from the start of the outbreak to early March 2020, the CDC gave restrictive guidelines on who should be eligible for COVID-19 testing. The initial criteria were (a) people who had recently traveled to certain countries affected by the outbreak, or (b) people with respiratory illness serious enough to require hospitalization, or (c) people who have been in contact with a person confirmed to have COVID-19. Only on March{{nbsp}}5 did the CDC relax the criteria to allow doctors discretion to decide who would be eligible for tests.<ref name=WangMarch22>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Jessica |last2=Huth |first2=Lindsay |last3=Umlauf |first3=Taylor |last4=Wang |first4=Elbert |last5=McKay |first5=Betsy |title=How the CDC's Restrictive Testing Guidelines Hid the Coronavirus Epidemic |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-cdcs-restrictive-testing-guidelines-hid-the-coronavirus-epidemic-11584882001 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |archivedate=March 22, 2020 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 22, 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.today/tp9HA}}</ref>\n\nAs a result, the United States had a slow start in conducting widespread testing for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |title=Squandered time: How the Trump administration lost control of the coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-coronavirus-response-squandered-time/2020/03/07/5c47d3d0-5fcb-11ea-9055-5fa12981bbbf_story.html |first1=Ashley |last1=Parker | first2=Yasmeen |last2=Abutaleb |first3=Lena |last3=Sun |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cohen |first1=Jon |title=The United States badly bungled coronavirus testing\u2014but things may soon improve |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/02/united-states-badly-bungled-coronavirus-testing-things-may-soon-improve |website=Science |date=February 28, 2020 |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Fewer than 4,000 tests were conducted in the U.S. by February 27, with U.S. state laboratories conducting only around 200.<ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/> The first U.S. case of a person having COVID-19 of unknown origin (a possible indication of [[community transmission]] in the [[state of California]]) saw the patient's test being delayed for four days after being hospitalized on February 19, because he had not qualified for a test under the initial federal testing criteria.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abdalla |first1=Jihan |title=First US coronavirus case of unknown origin marks 'turning point' |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-case-unknown-origin-marks-turning-point-200227154643100.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Whereas in [[Washington state]], a group of researchers defied a lack of clearance from federal and state officials to conduct their own tests from February 25, using samples already collected from their flu study that their subjects had not given permission for COVID-19 testing. They quickly found a teenager infected with COVID-19 of unknown origin, newly indicating that an outbreak had already been occurring in Washington for the past six weeks. State regulators stopped these researchers' testing on March 2.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fink |first1=Sheri |last2=Baker |first2=Mike |title='It's Just Everywhere Already': How Delays in Testing Set Back the U.S. Coronavirus Response |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/coronavirus-testing-delays.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Achenbach |first1=Joel |last2=Mettler |first2=Katie |last3=Sun |first3=Lena H. |last4=Guarino |first4=Ben |title=Coronavirus may have spread undetected for weeks in Washington state, which reported first two deaths in U.S. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-may-have-spread-undetected-for-weeks-in-washington-state/2020/03/01/0f292336-5bcc-11ea-9055-5fa12981bbbf_story.html |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, Vice President Mike Pence, the leader of the coronavirus response team, acknowledged that \"we don't have enough tests\" to meet the predicted future demand; this announcement came only three days after [[FDA]] commissioner [[Stephen Hahn (oncologist)|Stephen Hahn]] committed to producing nearly a million tests by that week.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: White House concedes US lacks enough test kits |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51761435 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Senator [[Chris Murphy]] of Connecticut and representative [[Stephen F. Lynch|Stephen Lynch]] of Massachusetts both noted that as of March{{nbsp}}8 their states had not yet received the new test kits.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cathey |first1=Libby |title=Government coronavirus response: Trump prepared to use the 'full power' of government |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/government-coronavirus-response-updates-fauci-warns-congress-worse/story?id=69532695 |website=ABC News |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[Anthony Fauci]], the head of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]], acknowledged on March 12 that it was \"a failing\" of the U.S. system that the demand for coronavirus tests was not being met; Fauci later clarified that he believed the private sector should have been brought in sooner to address the shortfall.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kessler |first1=Glenn |title=What did Dr. Anthony Fauci say about coronavirus testing 'failing'? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/18/what-did-dr-fauci-say-about-coronavirus-testing-failing/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> By March 13, fewer than 14,000 tests had been done in the United States, reported ''[[The Atlantic]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khazan |first1=Olga |title=The 4 Key Reasons the U.S. Is So Behind on Coronavirus Testing |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/why-coronavirus-testing-us-so-delayed/607954/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe timing and availability of testing varies across countries. For example, by March 13 South Korea offered [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea#Drive-through testing site|drive-through testing centers]], which could get results the next day.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/815441078/south-koreas-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-is-fast-and-free \"South Korea's Drive-Through Testing For Coronavirus Is Fast\u2014And Free\"], NPR, March 13, 2020</ref> South Korea also had a government-funded daily testing capacity of 15,000.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/815441078/south-koreas-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-is-fast-and-free |title= South Korea's Drive-Through Testing For Coronavirus Is Fast\u2014And Free |last= Kuhn |first= Anthony |date= March 13, 2020 |publisher=NPR |access-date= March 17, 2020}}</ref> According to March 16 and 17 statistics from [[Our World in Data]], the U.S. had tested 125 people per million of their population\u2014around the same as Japan. The U.K. tested nearly 750 per million, Italy more than 2,500 per million, and South Korea more than 5,500 per million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCarthy |first1=Niall |title=U.S. Lags Behind Other Countries in Coronavirus Testing |url=https://www.statista.com/chart/21108/covid-19-tests-performed-per-million-of-the-population/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Statista]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The first COVID-19 cases in the U.S. and South Korea were identified at around the same time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCann |first1=Larry |last2=Lai |first2=Rebecca |last3=McCann |first3=Allison |title=U.S. Lags in Coronavirus Testing |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/03/17/us/coronavirus-testing-data.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Critics say the U.S. government has botched the approval and distribution of test kits, losing crucial time during the early weeks of the outbreak, with the result that the true number of cases in the United States was impossible to estimate with any reasonable accuracy.<ref name=\"theatlantic.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/13/coronavirus-testing-us|title=Why has coronavirus testing in the US been such a disaster?|date=March 13, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 15, 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 12, all fifty states were able to perform tests, with a doctor's approval, either from the CDC or from commercial labs in a state.<ref>[https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing-in-us.html \"Testing in the U.S.\"], CDC, March 13, 2020</ref> This was followed by the government announcing a series of measures intended to speed up testing. These measures included the appointment of Admiral [[Brett Giroir]] of the [[United States Public Health Service|U.S. Public Health Service]] to oversee testing, funding for two companies developing rapid tests, and a hotline to help labs find needed supplies.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/13/815363944/trump-administration-announces-measures-to-speed-coronavirus-testing \"Trump Administration Announces Measures To Speed Coronavirus Testing\"], NPR, March 13, 2020</ref> The [[FDA]] also gave emergency authorization for New York to obtain an automated coronavirus test unit that will reduce testing time to 3.5 hours.<ref>[https://nypost.com/2020/03/13/fda-issues-emergency-authorization-for-coronavirus-test/ \"FDA authorizes coronavirus test that could drastically speed up screening\"], ''New York Post'', March 13, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 13, drive-through testing in the U.S. began in [[Westchester County, New York|New Rochelle]], [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]], as New Rochelle was the U.S. town with the most diagnosed cases at that time.<ref name=\"pbs1\">{{cite news |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/new-york-launches-drive-thru-testing-site-for-covid-19 |title=New York launches drive-thru testing site for COVID-19 |publisher=PBS |location=New York, NY |date=March 14, 2020 |author=Booker, Christopher}}</ref> By March 22, drive-through testing had appeared in more than thirty states, however the [[Associated Press]] reported that \"the system has been marked by inconsistencies, delays, and [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|shortages]],\" leading to many people waiting hours or days even though they showed symptoms and were recommended by a doctor to get a test. A lack of supplies had already forced the closure of drive-through testing in Alabama, Colorado, Florida, Louisiana, New Mexico, Utah, and Virginia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Michelle |title=Chaos, Inconsistency Mark Launch of Drive-Thru Virus Testing |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2020-03-22/chaos-inconsistency-mark-launch-of-drive-thru-virus-testing |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a March 13 press conference, the Trump administration announced an effort for tests to be conducted in retail store parking lots across the country, with participating franchises including [[Walmart]], [[Target Corporation|Target]], [[CVS Health|CVS]], and [[Walgreens]]. The plan was that test data would be sent to labs to complete testing in partnership with local health departments and diagnostic labs.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-google/google-walmart-join-us-effort-to-speed-up-coronavirus-testing-idUSKBN21036R |title=Google, Walmart join U.S. effort to speed up coronavirus testing |agency=Reuters |location=New York, NY |date=March 13, 2020 |author=Sanders, Chris}}</ref> Two weeks later, five stations had been opened by the companies: Walmart two, Target none, CVS one, Walgreens one, and one more from newcomer [[Rite Aid]]. These were labelled as \"prototype sites\" by the Trump administration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dwoskin |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Bhattarai |first2=Abha |last3=Eilperin |first3=Juliet |last4=Parker |first4=Ashley |title=Coronavirus: Drive-thru testing sites promised by Trump administration nowhere to be seen |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/trump-promised-scores-of-big-box-retailers-would-offer-parking-lots-for-covid-19-testing-there-are-only-five-of-them/2020/03/27/ece8ab06-703a-11ea-aa80-c2470c6b2034_story.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |date=March 28, 2020 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n===Research into vaccine and drug therapies===\n\n{{further|COVID-19 vaccine|COVID-19 drug repurposing research}}\n{{See also|List of medical products of unproven efficacy for COVID-19}}\n[[File:President Trump at the National Institute of Health (49618032306).jpg|thumb|March 3: President Trump and [[Anthony Fauci]] visit the [[Vaccine Research Center]] and the Viral Pathogenesis Laboratory at the [[National Institutes of Health]]]]\n\nThere is currently no drug approved for treating COVID-19 either as a therapy or a vaccine, nor is there any clear evidence that COVID-19 infection leads to immunity (experts assume it does for some period).<ref>[https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00798-8 \"Coronavirus vaccines: five key questions as trials begin\"], ''Nature'', March 18, 2020</ref> As of late March 2020, more than a hundred drugs are in testing.<ref>Bob Herman [https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-treatment-vaccine-research-pharma-drugs-55a28ea3-ee91-4f77-a093-44d450470b25.html Over 100 drugs are in testing in the race to treat coronavirus] March 25, 2020 Axios</ref> In April 2020, the CDC began testing blood samples to determine if a person has been exposed to the virus, even without showing symptoms, which could provide information about immunity.<ref name=stat-1>[https://www.statnews.com/2020/04/04/cdc-launches-studies-to-get-more-precise-count-of-undetected-covid-19-cases/ \"CDC launches studies to get more precise count of undetected Covid-19 cases\"], ''STAT News'', April 4, 2020</ref>\n\nWhile most common viruses provide diverse degrees of immunity, with this new virus it is not yet known for certain whether there is absolute immunity, how long that immunity would last or whether certain people can still be reinfected even after recovering.<ref>[https://time.com/5810454/coronavirus-immunity-reinfection/ \"Can You Be Re-Infected After Recovering From Coronavirus? Here's What We Know About COVID-19 Immunity\"], ''Time'', April 3, 2020</ref> There is also concern that if this virus mutates as does the yearly influenza, there could be a new strain each year.<ref name=vox-1>[https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2020/4/5/21208630/coronavirus-cdc-blood-test-immunity-serological-cellex \"The CDC has begun testing blood for immunity against the coronavirus\"], ''Vox'', April 5, 2020</ref> In any case, learning who is protected against the disease's spread is a primary factor in deciding when people can fully return to society.<ref name=vox-1/> Until then, physical distancing is required as it has shown to slow the spread of the disease to manageable levels.<ref name=vox-2>[https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2020/3/26/21192211/coronavirus-covid-19-social-distancing-end \"Social distancing can't last forever. Here's what should come next.\"], ''Vox'', March 20, 2020</ref>\n\nAmong the labs working on a vaccine is the [[Walter Reed Army Institute of Research]], which has previously studied other infectious diseases, such as HIV/AIDS, Ebola, and MERS. Speed in developing a vaccine is a key element in the midst of the pandemic, as physical distancing, self-isolating, and closures will have to be maintained until a vaccine is developed, which could take 12 to 18 months at best, or else transmission will quickly rebound.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wan |first1=William |last2=Achenbach |first2=Joel |last3=Johnson |first3=Carolyn Y. |last4=Guarino |first4=Ben |title=Coronavirus will radically alter the U.S. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2020/03/19/coronavirus-projections-us/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> By March 18, tests had begun with a few dozen volunteers in Seattle, Washington, which was sponsored by the U.S. government. Similar safety trials of other coronavirus vaccines will begin soon in the U.S. Trials are also underway in China and Europe.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/walter-reed-researchers-join-global-search-coronavirus-vaccine-n1165806 \"Walter Reed researchers join global search for coronavirus vaccine\"], NBC News, March 21, 2020</ref> This search for a vaccine has taken on aspects of national security and global competition.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/us/politics/coronavirus-vaccine-competition.html \"Search for Coronavirus Vaccine Becomes a Global Competition\"], ''The New York Times'', March 19, 2020</ref>\n\nThe FDA has sent warning letters to at least seven retailers selling essential oils, nasal sprays, herbal remedies, and other products claiming to test for, treat, or prevent COVID-19. This is in violation of federal law, since none have been determined to be safe and effective by the FDA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824879686/feds-warns-merchants-not-make-coronavirus-treatment-claims|title=Feds Warn Merchants Against Coronavirus Treatment Claims|publisher=NPR|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 19, President Trump directed the FDA to accelerate the testing and possible use of certain medications to discover if they would help treat patients who already have COVID-19.<ref name=\"WSJ-drugs\">[https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-expected-to-detail-new-virus-therapies-but-expansion-could-be-controversial-11584629965?mod=searchresults&page=1&pos=10 \"U.S. Moves to Expand Array of Drug Therapies Deployed Against Coronavirus\"], ''The Wall Street Journal'', March 19, 2020</ref> Among potential drugs are [[chloroquine]] and [[hydroxychloroquine]], which have long been used successfully to treat [[malaria]]. In March, both hydroxychloroquine and chloroquine were already being used to treat coronavirus patients by a number of physicians under the limited [[compassionate use]] approval of the FDA or as an [[off-label]] prescription, while trials and analysis are still ongoing.<ref name=\"WSJ-drugs\" /><ref name=\"Richardson\">{{cite news|last1=Richardson|first1=Valerie|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/apr/2/hydroxychloroquine-rated-most-effective-therapy-do/|title=Hydroxychloroquine rated 'most effective therapy' by doctors for coronavirus: Global survey|date=April 2, 2020|work=[[The Washington Times]]|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}{{RS?}}</ref> On March 29, the FDA issued an [[Emergency Use Authorization]], allowing the drugs as treatments for hospitalized coronavirus patients when clinical trials are not available for them to join.<ref name=\"JustinWise\">{{cite news |last1=Wise |first1=Justin |title=FDA issues emergency-use authorization for anti-malaria drugs amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/490110-fda-issues-emergency-use-authorization-for-anti-malaria-drugs-amid |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |publisher=The Hill |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Fauci and other public health officials stress hydroxychloroquine is unproven for efficacy against COVID-19, as of early April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-hydroxychloroquine-white-house-01306286-0bbc-4042-9bfe-890413c6220d.html|title=Inside the epic White House blowup over \"game-changer\" hydroxychloroquine|first=Jonathan|last=Swan|website=Axios}}</ref>\n\t\nIn China, trials of chloroquine are underway at dozens of clinics, with early laboratory results showing that it seems to reduce the virus's rate of replication. Chloroquine has been used to treat patients with malaria for nearly a century.<ref name=LATimes-drugs>{{cite web |first1=Amina|last1=Khan|date=March 21, 2020|url-access=subscription|url=https://www.latimes.com/science/story/2020-03-21/coronavirus-treatments-where-we-are-and-what-we-know |title=Coronavirus drugs: Where we are and what we know| work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> An Arizona man died after taking [[chloroquine phosphate]] in a high-concentration formulation which is used to control growth of algae and infectious organisms in aquariums.<ref name=\"boston-therapy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/31/coronavirus-drug-clinical-trials|title=With No Proven Drug Therapies For COVID-19, Here's What Boston Hospitals Are Trying|website=wbur.org|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA closely-related drug, hydroxychloroquine, first approved in the U.S. for [[lupus]] in 1955, is typically used to treat certain [[autoimmune disease]]s.<ref name=LATimes-drugs/><ref>{{cite journal |title=New Drugs/Drug News |journal=Pharmacy and Therapeutics |date=April 2011 |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=187\u2013190, 192\u2013194 |pmid=21572774 |pmc=3086112 }}</ref> A study in the peer-reviewed medical journal ''[[Clinical Infectious Diseases]]'' published on March{{nbsp}}9 provided dosing recommendations for hydroxycholorquine as a COVID-19 treatment, and showed it to be more effective in inhibiting the virus in vitro than chloroquine.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yao |first1=X. |display-authors=etal |title=In Vitro Antiviral Activity and Projection of Optimized Dosing Design of Hydroxychloroquine for the Treatment of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2). |journal=[[Clinical Infectious Diseases]] |date=March 9, 2020 |doi=10.1093/cid/ciaa237 |pmid=32150618 |pmc=7108130 }}</ref> Doctors are currently testing hydroxychloroquine in coronavirus patients.<ref name=LATimes-drugs/> On March 20, the WHO announced a large global trial of both drugs.<ref>[https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/who-launches-global-megatrial-four-most-promising-coronavirus-treatments \"WHO launches global megatrial of the four most promising coronavirus treatments\"], [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], March 22, 2020</ref> \n\nHoarding of hydroxychloroquine, including by doctors prescribing the drug preemptively to family members, and publicity about the drug generated by President Trump caused spot shortages that endangered the health of patients using it to treat [[lupus]] and [[rheumatoid arthritis]]. Some state pharmacy boards placed limitations on prescriptions for hydroxychloroquine and related medicines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/22/hydroxychloroquine-treatment-drug-coronavirus-hoarding|title=Hoarding Of Malaria Drug Under Investigation As Potential COVID-19 Treatment Undermines Public Health Efforts, Doctors Say|website=wbur.org|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Similarly, Nevada's governor, [[Steve Sisolak]] released an executive order banning doctors from prescribing hydroxychloroquine or chloroquine as a coronavirus treatment in his state on March 24, although he later tweeted that doctors in hospitals were exempt from the prohibition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ebrahimji |first1=Alisha |title=Nevada governor limits use of anti-malaria drugs for coronavirus patients |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/us/malaria-drugs-nevada-trnd/index.html |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lapin |first1=Tamar |title=Nevada governor limits malaria drugs for coronavirus patients |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/24/nevada-governor-bans-malaria-drugs-for-coronavirus-patients/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=New York Post |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the day after Trump initially mentioned the drug, the Israeli company [[Teva Pharmaceuticals]] announced it would manufacture and donate as many doses as possible to U.S. hospitals at no charge, including six million doses by the end of the month.<ref name=TOI>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/teva-to-send-us-millions-of-malaria-pills-with-potential-to-help-covid-19/ \"Teva to send US millions of malaria pills with potential to help COVID-19\"], ''The Times of Israel'', March 20, 2020</ref> On the same day, Sandoz, a subsidiary of [[Novartis]], said it would donate up to 130 million doses of the drug if approved.<ref name=\"novartis\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Novartis CEO: Malaria drug is biggest hope against coronavirus\u2014SonntagsZeitung |url=https://news.yahoo.com/novartis-ceo-malaria-drug-biggest-071547625.html |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Yahoo News |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> [[Mylan]] also began increasing its production of the drug in response to low supplies.<ref name=\"novartis\">{{cite news |title=Novartis to donate malaria drug in fight against coronavirus |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/20/novartis-to-donate-malaria-drug-in-fight-against-coronavirus.html |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |agency=Reuters |publisher=CNBC |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The HHS reported on March 29 that the government would make available 30 million doses of hydroxychloroquine and a million doses of chloroquine recently donated to the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] for doctors to prescribe within limitations for COVID-19 patients under the FDA's Emergency Use Authorization.<ref name=\"JustinWise\" /> In a survey of 6,200 physicians in 30 countries by [[Sermo]], 23% of U.S. doctors said they treated COVID-19 patients with hydroxychloroquine. American doctors were significantly more likely to prescribe the drug only for high risk patients, while international doctors used it equally for mild and severe cases. It ranked as the third most-used treatment overall, behind [[Azithromycin]] (41%), and [[analgesics]] (56%).<ref name=\"Richardson\" />\n\nAlso being tested in research clinics is the antiviral drug [[remdesivir]].<ref name=WSJ-drugs/> It was developed to fight Ebola, although it failed to prove effective for that disease.<ref name=LATimes-drugs/> At a Coronavirus Task Force briefing on March 19, FDA Commissioner [[Stephen Hahn (oncologist)|Stephen Hahn]] noted that the FDA had made remdesivir available under compassionate use guidelines for coronavirus patients, while the FDA standard approval process was still ongoing.<ref name=March19Briefing /> In addition, the antibody rheumatoid arthritis treatment [[sarilumab]] is being tested in clinical trials in the hopes that suppressing some aspects of the immune response can help improve lung function patients who require supplemental oxygen.<ref name=\"boston-therapy\" /> Due to the emergency nature of the pandemic, former FDA commissioners Drs. [[Scott Gottlieb]] and [[Mark McClellan]] have called for the FDA to develop therapeutics and vaccines that would be exempt from some regulatory requirements.<ref name=WSJ-drugs/>\n\n===Medical supplies===\n\nOn March 15, senior federal health official Anthony Fauci said the United States had 12,700 ventilators in its national stockpile.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Knutson |first1=Jacob |title=Fauci on coronavirus: \"We'll be thankful that we're overreacting\" |url=https://www.axios.com/fauci-coronavirus-overreaction-decc88f5-ab25-4c27-86d2-aff3acea583c.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> On March 19, Vice President Mike Pence declared that the federal government had \"literally identified tens of thousands of ventilators\", but did not provide further details.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walsh |first1=James |title=Elon Musk Can't Solve This |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/car-manufacturers-alone-cant-solve-the-ventilator-crisis.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Trump told state governors that for medical equipment including respirators and ventilators, \"We will be backing you, but try getting it yourselves.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Jonathan |title=Trump to Governors on Ventilators: 'Try Getting It Yourselves' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-respirators.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 16, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200316185811/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/us/politics/trump-coronavirus-respirators.html |archivedate=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 24, Trump said state governors who wanted help from the federal government \"have to treat us well, also\", because \"it's a two-way street\"; he warned against governors arguing \"we should get this, we should get that.\"<ref name=McGrawMarch24>{{cite news |last1=McGraw |first1=Meredith |title=How to update the country on coronavirus: Thank Trump first |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/24/update-country-coronavirus-thank-trump-147625 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 24, the [[Governor of New York]], [[Andrew Cuomo]], declared that the [[state of New York]] would need 30,000 ventilators to handle the peak of the outbreak in the state, which was predicted to arrive in two weeks. Cuomo also said the federal government had sent only 400 ventilators to New York. Two days later, Trump, citing \"a feeling\", stated: \"I don't believe you need 40,000 or 30,000 ventilators.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Forgey |first1=Quint |last2=Choi |first2=Matthew |title=Trump downplays need for ventilators as New York begs to differ |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/26/trump-ventilators-coronavirus-151311 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He also said the [[Governor of Washington]], [[Jay Inslee]], \"shouldn't be relying on the federal government\"; Inslee says the President needs to enact a \"national mobilization of the industrial base in this country\" to produce medical supplies.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Zeke |last2=Colvin |first2=Jill |last3=Superville |first3=Darlene |title=Trump, rejecting blame, warns governors to be 'appreciative' |url=https://komonews.com/news/nation-world/trump-rejecting-blame-warns-governors-to-be-appreciative |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTrump signed an executive order citing provisions of the [[Defense Production Act]] on March 18, which allows the federal government a wide range of powers, including giving directions to industries on what to produce, having companies prioritize certain contracts, allocating supplies, giving incentives to industries, and allowing companies to cooperate. Initially under the act, he conferred more power over contracts and resources to the Health and Human Services Secretary and enacted provisions to prevent hoarding of medical resources.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vazquez |first1=Maegan |title=Trump invokes Defense Production Act to expand production of hospital masks and more |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/18/politics/trump-defense-production-act-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rizzo |first1=Salvador |title=Is Trump using the Defense Production Act? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/25/is-trump-using-defense-production-act/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, Trump remarked that the federal government ordered 500 million [[N95 mask]]s to be manufactured to make more private masks available and that American manufacturers were repurposing factories to manufacture masks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-briefing-nurses-covid-19-response/|title=Remarks by President Trump and Vice President Pence in a Briefing with Nurses on COVID-19 Response|website=The White House|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 21, the director of the [[Johns Hopkins Center for Health Security]] described American hospitals as already facing shortages of test kit reagents, test kit swabs, masks, gowns and gloves.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Diamond |first1=Dan |title=Short-term thinking plagues Trump's coronavirus response |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/21/short-term-thinking-trump-coronavirus-response-140883 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In a March 20 to 24 survey of 214 American mayors (who manage a total 42 million people), 85% said [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|they did not have enough]] ventilators, 92% said they did not have enough face masks, 88% said there was a shortage of other personal protective equipment, and 92% said they did not have enough test kits.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adamczyk |first1=Ed |title=U.S. mayors say they're running out of supplies to fight coronavirus |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2020/03/27/US-mayors-say-theyre-running-out-of-supplies-to-fight-coronavirus/2751585333088/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=[[United Press International]] |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On the prevalence of medical supplies, Trump said on March 29 that \"many of the states are stocked up,\" with certain hospitals \"holding ventilators, they don't want to let 'em up.\" Trump said he could not understand how demand for face masks had supposedly surged from 10,000 to 300,000 per week, saying it was \"maybe worse than hoarding\": \"Are they going out the back door?\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump blames hospitals for mask and ventilator shortages |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/29/trump-bizarrely-blames-hospitals-mask-ventilator-shortages/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVentilator manufacturers are [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|facing a shortage]] of sub-components needed to produce the ventilators, reported [[Bloomberg News]] on March 25.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Light |first1=Joe |last2=Mider |first2=Zachary |last3=Proper |first3=Ellen |title=Ventilator Makers Can Speed Up But Face Shortages of Parts |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-24/ventilator-makers-can-speed-up-but-they-face-shortages-of-parts |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Bloomberg News |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> When Trump was asked by a reporter on whether the United States would have enough ventilators as needed, he told the reporter: \"Don't be a cutie pie.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cathey |first1=Libby |title=Coronavirus government response updates: Trump signs $2T relief bill after House passage |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/coronavirus-government-response-updates-drama-house-votes-2t/story?id=69833576 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[ABC News]] |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Trump stated governors should be \"appreciative\", with his administration having \"done a job, the likes of which nobody has seen\". Trump's outlook on the governors was: \"If they don't treat you right, I don't call.\" Thus, Trump told of advising Vice President Mike Pence, \"don't call\" Washington governor Inslee and [[Michigan governor]] [[Gretchen Whitmer]]\u2014although Pence would call anyway, said Trump.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Samuels |first1=Brett |title=Trump digs in on criticism of Democratic governors |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/489949-trump-digs-in-on-criticism-of-democratic-governors |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Trump ties coronavirus decisions to personal grievances |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/27/trump-suggests-personal-grievances-factor-into-his-coronavirus-decisions/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Whitmer, who had previously argued that \"the federal government did not take this seriously early enough,\" responded that Michigan still needed personal protective equipment, ventilators, masks and test kits.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=David |last2=Collins |first2=Michael |title=Trump to Mike Pence: 'Don't call the woman in Michigan,' aka Gov. Gretchen Whitmer |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/27/coronavirus-donald-trump-tells-pence-not-call-michigan-governor/2931251001/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=USA Today |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn anonymous, informal survey of medical personnel, conducted online in late March by a [[New Jersey]] nurse, pointed out the lack of proper equipment as the main issue in current efforts, with 90 percent of respondents claiming they had been forced to work without proper [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE).<ref name=\"20200325com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous\">{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Edmund|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous.html|title=Nurses Share Coronavirus Stories Anonymously in an Online Document|date=25 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=25 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205951/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/business/media/coronavirus-nurses-stories-anonymous.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMasks, gloves, gowns, and sanitising products were soon in short supply. On April 2, 2020, ''The Washington Post'', among other news outlets, reported on the critical shortfall of [[N95 masks]]:\n{{quote|severe shortages of the N95 masks in emergency rooms and hospitals. Even [[surgical masks]], which provide some protection, are in short supply at many health-care facilities. Desperate health-care workers have resorted to unvalidated measures to find alternative methods of protecting themselves{{nbsp}}... [with] more than 500,000 physicians older than 50, representing just over half the nation's entire physician workforce. The average age of nurses in the United States is 51. A 48-year-old emergency department nurse in New York City died of covid-19 on March 24, and emergency department physicians have been reported to have developed severe covid-19 requiring intensive care in Washington state and New Jersey.<ref>{{cite news| last=Balmes| first=John R.| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/mask-shortages-are-outrageous-the-federal-government-needs-to-do-better/2020/04/02/58301064-7399-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html|title=Mask shortages are outrageous. The federal government needs to do better.| work=The Washington Post| date=April 2, 2020| access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nOn April 3 during the daily Coronavirus Task Force briefing, Trump said hospital administrators were \"communicating directly with us that their level of supplies are meeting essential needs. And at the current time, they're really thrilled to be where they are.\" Responding on ''NPR'', the [[American Hospital Association]] said their communications with hospital officials showed that hospitals \"are worried about shortages of critical medical supplies, including medication for patients and personal protective equipment, or PPE, for health care workers.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mccammon |first1=Sarah |title=Hospitals Reject Trump's Claim They Are 'Really Thrilled' With Supplies |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/05/827671323/hospitals-reject-trumps-claim-they-are-really-thrilled-with-supplies |website=NPR |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Congressional response===\n\n[[File:President Trump Signs the Congressional Funding Bill for Coronavirus Response (49627907646).jpg|thumb|March 6: President Trump, with the Secretary of HHS Alex Azar, signs the [[Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act]] into law]]\n\nOn March 6, 2020, the [[Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2020]] provided $8.3 billion to fight the pandemic. The deal includes \"more than $3&nbsp;billion for the research and development of vaccines, therapeutics and diagnostics, as well as $2.2 billion for the CDC, and $950 million to support state and local health agencies\".<ref name=\"Politico 8.3 billion agreement\">{{cite web |last1=Emma |first1=Caitlin |last2=Ferris |first2=Sarah |title=Congress strikes a deal on bipartisan $8.3B coronavirus package |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/04/house-coronavirus-funding-121065 |website=Politico |date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Trump signs $8.3 billion emergency package to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-signs-8-3-billion-emergency-package-to-combat-coronavirus/ |publisher=CBS News |date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Another bill, the [[Families First Coronavirus Response Act]] was approved on March 18. It provides paid emergency leave and food assistance be provided to affected employees, along with free testing.<ref name=\"NBC House passes\">{{cite web |last1=Moe |first1=Alex |last2=Shabad |first2=Rebecca |last3=Clark |first3=Dartunorro |title=House passes coronavirus aid package, sending bill to the Senate |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/house-vote-friday-democrats-coronavirus-relief-package-n1158306 |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[U.S. House Committee on Financial Services]], chaired by Representative [[Maxine Waters]], released a stimulus proposal on March 18 in which the [[Federal Reserve]] would fund monthly payments of \"at least $2,000 for every adult and an additional $1000 for every child for each month of the crisis\". Other elements include suspending all consumer and small business credit payments.<ref name=\"Dems_Waters\">{{cite news|last1=Waters|first1=Maxine|url=https://financialservices.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=406440|title=Waters Announces Committee Plan for Comprehensive Fiscal Stimulus and Public Policy Response to Coronavirus Pandemic|date=March 18, 2020|work=financialservices.house.gov/|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, Representative [[Rashida Tlaib]] proposed the similar \"Automatic BOOST to Communities Act\", which would involve sending pre-loaded $2,000 debit cards to every American, with $1,000 monthly payments thereafter until the economy recovers. This would be funded by the [[U.S.&nbsp;Treasury]] minting two [[trillion-dollar coin]]s. According to Tlaib, the Treasury has this authority, and it would not increase the national debt.<ref name=\"Mint_The_Coin\">{{cite news|last1=Higgins|first1=Eoin|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/21/two-1-trillion-coins-rashida-tlaib-proposal-calls-us-treasury-fund-coronavirus|title=Two $1 Trillion Coins': Rashida Tlaib Proposal Calls on US Treasury to Fund Coronavirus Recovery From US Mint|date=March 21, 2020|work=Common Dreams|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith guidance from the White House, Senate Majority Leader [[Mitch McConnell]] proposed a third stimulus package amounting to over $1&nbsp;trillion.{{efn|This included $300 billion to help small businesses with forgivable loans up to $10 million<ref name=hurdles/> and $200 billion to support industries such as airlines, cruise companies, and hotels through loans and other measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stone |first1=Peter |title=Washington lobbyists in frenzied battle to secure billion-dollar coronavirus bailouts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-washington-lobbyists-bailout |work=The Guardian |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Democrats have advocated for banning stock {{nowrap|buy-backs}} to prevent these funds from being used to make a profit.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Press |first1=Associated |title=Congress and White House resume talks on $1tn pandemic rescue deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/21/us-coronavirus-economic-rescue-trump |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>}}{{efn|It was suggested that $200\u2013500 billion would fund tax rebate checks to Americans who made between $2,500 and $75,000 in 2018 to help cover short-term costs<ref name=trillion>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Kasie |last2=Caldwell |first2=Leigh Ann |last3=Tsirkin |first3=Julie |last4=Shabad |first4=Rebecca |title=White House eyeing $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus package |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/senate-democrats-have-prepped-third-coronavirus-aid-package-n1161506 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |publisher=NBC News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Trump wants to send Americans checks 'immediately' in response to coronavirus, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-wants-to-send-money-to-americans-in-next-two-weeks-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> via one or two payments of $600 to $1,200 per adult and $500 per child.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Breuninger |first1=Kevin |title=Trump wants direct payments of $1,000 for adults, $500 for kids in coronavirus stimulus bill, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/coronavirus-trump-wants-payments-of-1000-for-adults-500-for-kids.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |publisher=CNBC |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Re |first1=Gregg |title=McConnell's coronavirus stimulus plan would provide payments of $1,200 per person, $2,400 for couples |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/mcconnell-coronavirus-stimulus-plan-payments |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=rebate/> A similar measure has been suggested by both Democrats and Republicans as a form of [[basic income]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clifford |first1=Catherine |title=Andrew Yang, AOC, Harvard professor: Free cash payments would help during coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/andrew-yang-aoc-free-ubi-cash-can-help-during-coronavirus-pandemic.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=CNBC |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lahut |first1=Jake |title=Tom Cotton is calling for Americans to get cash payments through the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-calling-for-americans-to-get-100-month-coronavirus-2020-3 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> It is currently unclear whether the rebates would be tax-free.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Konish |first1=Lorie |title=Here's how your coronavirus rescue check from the government could be taxed |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/20/heres-how-your-rescue-check-from-the-government-could-be-taxed.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNBC |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>}}{{efn|Democrats prepared a $750 billion package as a {{nowrap|counter-offer}},<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=McConnell takes reins of third coronavirus bill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488338-mcconnell-takes-reins-of-third-coronavirus-bill |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Caygle |first1=Heather |last2=Bresnahan |first2=John |last3=Ferris |first3=Sarah |title=Pelosi looks to lay down marker on next stimulus plan |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/18/nancy-pelosi-coronavirus-stimulus-plan-136142 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> which focused on expanding [[unemployment benefits]] instead of tax rebates.<ref name=rebate>{{cite news |last1=Bolton |first1=Alexander |title=Democrats balk at $1,200 rebate checks in stimulus plan |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488677-democrats-balk-at-1200-rebate-checks-in-stimulus-plan |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> A compromise plan reportedly sets aside $250 billion for tax rebates and the same amount for unemployment.<ref name=hurdles>{{cite news |last1=Mattingly |first1=Phil |title=Stimulus package could top $2 trillion as negotiators look to clear final major hurdles |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/21/politics/stimulus-package-negotiations-congress-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>}} On March 22 and 23, the $1.4 trillion package, known as the [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act]] (or CARES Act), failed to pass in the Senate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mill |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Muhyung |last3=Webb |first3=Sean |title=Coronavirus: CARES Act Vote Fails in Senate; Summary of the Tax Provisions of the Bill |url=https://content.natlawreview.com/article/coronavirus-cares-act-vote-fails-senate-summary-tax-provisions-bill |website=National Law Review |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>{{efn|The revised draft included suspending federal student loan payments for six months without interest and $20 billion in school funding;<ref>{{cite news |title=GOP's $2 Trillion Bill Adds Cash for Bailouts, States, Transit |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-23/gop-s-2-trillion-bill-adds-cash-for-bailouts-states-transit |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Democrats said the bill did not go far enough to provide healthcare and unemployment aid, and that it provided a \"slush fund\" for corporations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bresnahan |first1=John |last2=Levine |first2=Marianne |title=Dems seize on 'slush fund' to oppose Republican rescue package |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/23/democrats-slush-fund-republican-rescue-package-143565 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>}}{{efn|House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] indicated that the House would prepare its own bill, expected to exceed $2.5 trillion, as a counter-offer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=House Democrats to introduce a $2.5 trillion coronavirus stimulus plan as Senate bill stalls |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/coronavirus-updates-pelosi-to-release-stimulus-bill-as-senate-plan-stalls.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |publisher=CNBC |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pelosis-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-includes-return-of-obamaphones-climate-change-wishlist|title=Pelosi's coronavirus stimulus includes return of 'Obamaphones', other unrelated items, GOP says|last=Re|first=Gregg|date=March 23, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324041402/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pelosis-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-includes-return-of-obamaphones-climate-change-wishlist|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>}} The act was revised in the Senate, coming to $2&nbsp;trillion, including $500 billion for loans to larger businesses such as airlines, $350 billion for small business loans, $250 billion for individuals, $250 billion for unemployment insurance, $150 billion for state and municipal governments, and $130 billion for hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Raju |first1=Manu |last2=Barrett |first2=Ted |last3=Foran |first3=Clare |last4=Wilson |first4=Kristin |title=White House, Senate reach historic $2 trillion stimulus deal amid growing coronavirus fears |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/stimulus-senate-action-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> It passed unanimously in the Senate late the night of March 25.<ref name=\"CNBC Senate passes $2 trillion\">{{cite web |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=Senate passes $2 trillion coronavirus stimulus package, sending it to the House |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/25/senate-passes-2-trillion-coronavirus-stimulus-package.html |publisher=CNBC |date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On March 27, the House approved the stimulus bill, and it was signed into law by President Trump.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Zeballos-Roig |first=Joseph |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-signs-coronavirus-economic-relief-aid-bill-checks-for-americans-2020-3 |title=Trump signs the $2 trillion coronavirus economic relief bill into law, which includes checks for Americans and business loans |date=March 27, 2020 |work=Business Insider |access-date=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPresident Trump has floated using the low interest rates to [[Infrastructure policy of Donald Trump|invest in infrastructure]], including roads, bridges, and tunnels, but specifically excluding the initiatives of the Democrats' Green New Deal.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Niquette |first1=Mark |title=Trump Urges $2 Trillion for Infrastructure to Bolster Economy |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/trump-calls-for-2-trillion-infrastructure-bill-to-create-jobs |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |work=Bloomberg |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Nancy Pelosi has made similar proposals, suggesting that broadband and water projects be included.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lillis |first1=Mike |title=Democrats eye major infrastructure component in next coronavirus package |url=https://thehill.com/policy/transportation/490243-democrats-eye-major-infrastructure-component-in-next-coronavirus |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Although the Senate will not reconvene until at least April 20,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bolton |first1=Alexander |title=McConnell hits brakes on next economic stimulus package |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490358-mcconnell-hits-brakes-on-next-economic-stimulus-package |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=The Hill |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> McConnell has indicated that a fourth bill related to the virus would prioritize health care.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=McConnell says there will be a fourth coronavirus bill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/491089-mcconnell-says-there-will-be-a-fourth-coronavirus-bill |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=The Hill |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] has called for a monthly basic income to help \"every person in the United States, including the undocumented, the homeless, the unbanked, and young adults excluded from the CARES Act\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Steinhauser |first1=Paul |last2=Craft |first2=Andrew |title=Bernie Sanders calls for $2G monthly payments, rent freeze in next stimulus package |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/bernie-sandersr-2g-monthly-payments-rent-freeze-next-stimulus-package |website=Fox News |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other federal policy responses===\n\n[[File:President Trump Visits the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.webmhd.webm|thumb|start=29:13|March 6: President Trump visits the CDC]]\nOn March 3, 2020, the Federal Reserve lowered [[Federal funds rate|target interest rates]] from 1.75% to 1.25%,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-fed/in-an-emergency-move-u-s-federal-reserve-cuts-interest-rates-to-battle-coronavirus-idUSKBN20Q22F|title=In an emergency move, U.S. Federal Reserve cuts interest rates to battle coronavirus|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> the largest emergency rate cut since the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 global financial crisis]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/03/economy-coronavirus-rate-cuts/|title=Fed makes largest emergency cut to interest rates since the financial crisis|date=March 3, 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> in an attempt to counteract the outbreak's effect on the American economy. \"The coronavirus poses evolving risks to economic activity,\" the Federal Reserve said in a statement. \"In light of these risks and in support of achieving its maximum employment and price stability goals, the Federal Open Market Committee decided today to lower the target range for the federal funds rate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/03/fed-cuts-rates-by-half-a-percentage-point-to-combat-coronavirus-slowdown.html|title=Fed cuts rates by half a percentage point to combat coronavirus slowdown|last=Cox|first=Jeff|date=March 3, 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304005925/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/03/fed-cuts-rates-by-half-a-percentage-point-to-combat-coronavirus-slowdown.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, during his Oval Office address, Trump announced that he had requested a number of other policy changes:\n* He would ask Congress to provide financial relief and paid sick leave for workers who were quarantined or had to care for others.\n* He would instruct the [[Small Business Administration]] (SBA) to provide loans to businesses affected by the pandemic, and would ask Congress for an additional $50 billion to help hard-hit businesses.\n* He would request that tax payments be deferred beyond April 15 without penalty for those affected, which he said could add $200 billion in temporary liquidity to the economy.\n* He would ask Congress to provide payroll tax relief to those affected.<ref name=USAToday>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/03/11/trump-address-nation-over-u-s-response-coronavirus-pandemic/5022464002/ \"President Trump restricts 'all travel' from EU to US starting Friday\"], ''USA Today'', March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the Fed cut their target interest rate again to a range of 0% to 0.25%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/business/economy/federal-reserve-coronavirus.html|title=Fed Slashes Rates to Near-Zero and Unveils Sweeping Program to Aid Economy|last1=Smialek|first1=Jeanna|last2=Irwin|first2=Neil|date=March 15, 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref> The Fed also announced a $700 billion [[quantitative easing]] program similar to the one initiated during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]]. Despite the moves, stock index futures plunged, triggering trading limits to prevent panic selling.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/15/traders-await-futures-open-after-fed-cuts-rates-launches-easing-program.html|title=Stock futures drop\u2014hit 'limit down'\u2014even as Fed slashes rates; Dow futures off 1,000 points|last=Imbert|first=Fred|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=CNBC}}</ref> The Dow lost nearly 13% the next day, the third-largest one-day decline in the 124-year history of the index.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/15/traders-await-futures-open-after-fed-cuts-rates-launches-easing-program.html|title=Dow drops nearly 3,000 points, as coronavirus collapse continues; worst day since '87|first=Fred|last=Imbert|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=CNBC}}</ref> That day, the [[VIX]]\u2014informally known as the market \"fear index\"\u2014closed at the highest level since its inception in 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/wall-streets-fear-gauge-hits-highest-level-ever.html|title=Wall Street's fear gauge closes at highest level ever, surpassing even financial crisis peak|first=Yun|last=Li|date=March 16, 2020|publisher=CNBC}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, the Federal Reserve announced a program to buy as much as a trillion dollars in corporate [[commercial paper]] to ensure credit continued flowing in the economy. The measure was backed by $10 billion in Treasury funds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/business/economy/federal-reserve-coronavirus.html|title=Fed Unveils Emergency Lending Programs as Companies Struggle to Raise Cash|first1=Jeanna|last1=Smialek|first2=Kate|last2=Kelly|first3=Peter|last3=Eavis|date=March 17, 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref> At this point, the federal government neared agreement on a stimulus proposal including direct cash payments to Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/03/17/trump-coronavirus-stimulus-package/|title=White House expresses support for immediate cash payments to Americans as part of coronavirus stimulus package|first1=Erica|last1=Werner|first2=Jeff|last2=Stein|first3=Mike|last3=DeBonis|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> Trump said his administration was working with the Congress to provide rapid relief to affected industries. He remarked that the relief would ensure the American economy would \"emerge from the strongest economy on earth\". In addition, Trump announced that the Small Business Administration would be providing disaster loans which could provide impacted businesses with up to $2&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-meeting-tourism-industry-executives-covid-19-response/|title=Remarks by President Trump in Meeting with Tourism Industry Executives on COVID-19 Response|website=The White House|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, Trump announced that the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD) would be suspending all kinds of foreclosures and evictions until the end of April.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe week of March 19, the [[Federal Housing Finance Agency]] ordered federally-guaranteed loan providers to grant forbearance of up to 12 months on mortgage payments from people who lost income due to the pandemic. It encouraged the same for non-federal loans, and included a pass-through provision for landlords to grant forbearance to renters who lost income.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/22/819725417/the-u-s-orders-a-break-on-mortgage-payments-what-does-that-mean|title=The U.S. Orders A Break On Mortgage Payments. What Does That Mean?|publisher=NPR|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Trump announced that the Department of Education will not be enforcing standardized testing for 2020. Trump had also instructed to waive all federally held student loans for the next sixty days, which could be extended if needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-c-oronavirus-task-force-press-briefing/|title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing|website=The White House|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]] also announced that the deadline for filing federal income tax returns and making federal income tax payments due April 15, 2020, are automatically postponed to July 15, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/tax-filings-payment-due-date-extended-to-july-15-mnuchin-says|title=IRS Pushes Tax Date to July 15, Same as Payment Deadline|last=Davison|first=Laura|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The due date for filing federal gift tax and generation-skipping transfer tax returns and making the related tax payments were also automatically postponed to July 15, 2020.<ref>\"[https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/n-20-20.pdf?utm_source=Cherry+Bekaert+LLP&utm_campaign=99386b2dff-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2020_04_IRS&utm_medium=email&utm_term=0_62a95a1e10-99386b2dff-268342809 Notice 2020-20:: Update to Notice 2020-18, Relief for Taxpayers Affected by Ongoing Coronavirus Disease 2019 pandemic, Related to Gift and Generation-Skipping Transfer Tax Filing and Payment Deadlines]\". ''Internal Revenue Service''. April 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Trump announced that he had directed FEMA to provide four large federal medical stations with 1,000 beds for New York, eight large federal medical stations with 2,000 beds for California, and three large federal medical stations and four small federal medical stations with 1,000 beds for the State of Washington.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 23, the Federal Reserve announced large-scale expansion of [[quantitative easing]], with no specific upper limit, and reactivation of the [[Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility]]. This injects newly created money into a variety of financial markets including [[corporate bond]]s, [[exchange-traded funds]], [[small business loan]]s, [[mortgage-backed securities]], [[student loan]]s, [[auto loan]]s, and credit card loans. The Fed also lowered its [[repurchase agreement]] interest rate from 0.1% to 0%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/fed-announces-a-slew-of-new-programs-to-help-markets-including-open-ended-asset-purchases.html|title=The Federal Reserve just pledged asset purchases with no limit to support markets|first=Jeff|last=Cox|date=March 23, 2020|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On the same day, Trump also postponed the October 1, 2020, deadline for Americans on commercial airlines to carry [[Real ID]]-compliant documents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-23/trump-postpones-real-id-requirements-due-to-virus-concerns|title=Trump Postpones Real ID Requirements Due to Virus Concerns|last=Sink|first=Justin|date=March 23, 2020|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, President Trump announced that the federal government will use funds from the [[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act]] (CARES Act) to pay hospitals for treatment of [[Health insurance coverage in the United States|uninsured patients]] infected with the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump Administration to Pay Hospitals to Treat Uninsured Coronavirus Patients |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-administration-plans-to-pay-hospitals-to-treat-uninsured-coronavirus-patients-11585927877 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Administration says it will reimburse hospitals for treating uninsured coronavirus patients |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/491113-administration-says-it-will-reimburse-hospitals-for-treating |work=The Hill |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6 the [[United States Army]] announced that [[basic training]] would be postponed for new recruits. Recruits already in training would continue what the Army is calling \"social-distanced-enabled training\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/06/828276307/u-s-army-delays-new-recruits-basic-training-due-to-coronavirus |title=U.S. Army Delays New Recruits' Basic Training Due To Coronavirus |date=April 6, 2020 |publisher=NPR}}</ref>\n\n===Communication===\n\n{{See also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#American}}\n\n====President Trump====\nFrom January 2020 to mid-March 2020, President Trump downplayed the threat posed by COVID-19 to the United States, giving many optimistic public statements,<ref name=BlakeMarch17>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=A timeline of Trump playing down the coronavirus threat |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/12/trump-coronavirus-timeline/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 17, 2020 }}</ref> which may have been aimed at calming stock markets.<ref name=JazeeraMarch18>{{cite news |title=Analysis: US presidential politics in the time of coronavirus |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/analysis-presidential-politics-time-coronavirus-200317202843984.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>{{Original research inline|date=April 2020}} He initially said he had no worries about COVID-19 becoming a pandemic.<ref name=ManganMarch17>{{cite news |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |title=Trump dismissed coronavirus pandemic worry in January\u2014now claims he long warned about it |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/17/trump-dissed-coronavirus-pandemic-worry-now-claims-he-warned-about-it.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> He went on to state on multiple occasions that the situation was \"under control\".<ref name=BlakeMarch17/> On February 26, he said of the virus: \"It's going to disappear. One day it's like a miracle, it will disappear. And from our shores, you know, it could get worse before it gets better. Could maybe go away. We'll see what happens. Nobody really knows.\"<ref name=\":8\">{{cite news |title=Trump claimed coronavirus could 'disappear' in the United States, adding to the administration's mixed messages |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-trump-claims-covid-19-could-disappear-2020-2 |agency=Business Insider |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> On February 27, speaking of the number of infected people in the country at the time, he predicted \"the 15 within a couple of days is going to be down to close to zero.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abutaleb |first1=Yasmeen |last2=Park |first2=Ashley |last3=Dawsey |first3=Josh |title=Inside Trump's frantic attempts to minimize the coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/inside-trumps-frantic-attempts-to-minimize-the-coronavirus-crisis/2020/02/29/7ebc882a-5b25-11ea-9b35-def5a027d470_story.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> In other remarks, he expressed a focus on the number of U.S. cases; commenting about cruise ship ''[[2020 coronavirus outbreak on the Grand Princess|Grand Princess]]'', he stated his preference that infected passengers not disembark as he did not want \"to have the [U.S. case] numbers double because of one ship\".<ref name=MasonMarch9>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Jeff |last2=Holland |first2=Steve |title=Trump's focus on coronavirus numbers could backfire, health experts say |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-trump-numbers-anal/trumps-focus-on-coronavirus-numbers-could-backfire-health-experts-say-idUSKBN20W16E |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |agency=Reuters |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> He cited the relatively low number of confirmed cases in the initial stages of the outbreak, as proof of success of his travel restriction on China.<ref name=MasonMarch9/> In late February he judged the country as \"very, very ready for this, for anything\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump declares US 'very, very ready' for coronavirus; Pence to lead response |url=https://www.syracuse.com/health/2020/02/trump-declares-us-very-very-ready-for-coronavirus-pence-to-lead-response.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> while in mid-March he rated his administration's response a score of 10/10.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chalfant |first1=Morgan |title=Trump gives himself 10 out of 10 on coronavirus response |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/487883-trump-gives-himself-10-out-of-10-on-coronavirus-response |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:President Trump will address the nation LIVE at 9-00 p.m. ET..webm|thumb|right|start=|President Trump addresses the nation, March 11]<ref name=WashPost_20200331>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2020/politics/trump-coronavirus-statements/ |title=From \u2018It\u2019s going to disappear\u2019 to \u2018We WILL WIN THIS WAR\u2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 31, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401154910/https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2020/politics/trump-coronavirus-statements/ |archivedate=April 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]\nOn March 11, 2020, Trump delivered an [[Oval Office]] address on national television, just hours after the WHO declared COVID-19 a global pandemic, which caused a quick fall in financial markets. It was the second such address to the country of his presidency, the first being in January 2019, addressing illegal immigration. In his speech, Trump declared that the United States was \"suspending all travel from Europe to the United States for the next 30 days\", except travel from the United Kingdom, and including \"the tremendous amount of trade and cargo\" (post-speech, Trump said trade was still approved, while administration officials clarified that \"American citizens or legal permanent residents or their families\" were not affected). Trump also listed several economic policy proposals, and declared that insurance companies \"have agreed to waive all co-payments for coronavirus treatments\" (post-speech, [[America's Health Insurance Plans]] clarified the waivers were only for tests, not for treatments). Trump praised his administration's response to the \"foreign\" virus while stating that \"a large number of new clusters in the United States were seeded by travelers from Europe.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hohmann |first1=James |title=Clarifications after Trump's Oval Office address are emblematic of his uneven coronavirus response |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/daily-202/2020/03/12/daily-202-clarifications-after-trump-s-oval-office-address-are-emblematic-of-his-uneven-coronavirus-response/5e69c2b988e0fa101a7475b1/ |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Trump changed his tone on the outbreak to a somber one. For the first time, he acknowledged that COVID-19 was \"not under control\", the situation was \"bad\" with months of impending disruption to daily lives, and a recession might occur.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump tries to erase the memory of him downplaying the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/17/politics/fact-check-trump-always-knew-pandemic-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 16, President Trump and the Coronavirus Task Force released new recommendations based on CDC guidelines for Americans, titled \"15 Days to Slow the Spread\". These recommendations included physical distancing and hygienic instructions, as well as directions to the states in dealing with school closures, nursing homes, and common public venues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/articles/15-days-slow-spread/|title=15 Days to Slow the Spread|date=March 16, 2020|website=The White House|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump Issues Guidelines on '15 Days to Slow the Spread' |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/us/articles/2020-03-16/factbox-trump-issues-guidelines-on-15-days-to-slow-the-spread |work=U.S. News & World Report |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 17, \"I felt it was a pandemic long before it was called a pandemic.\"<ref name=\"Trump Now Claims\">{{Cite news|last=Rogers|first=Katie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/politics/trump-coronavirus.html|title=Trump Now Claims He Always Knew the Coronavirus Would Be a Pandemic|date=March 17, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 18, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He also said America will achieve total victory against the \"invisible enemy\", and called Americans to sacrifice together.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-press-briefing-5/|title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing|website=The White House|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Trump began referring to COVID-19 as the \"Chinese virus\", and as a result he was criticized by Chinese and WHO officials for creating a potential stigma against [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Chinese and Asians]]. Trump disagreed with the criticism, and said that \"China tried to say at one point\u2014maybe they stopped\u2014that it was caused by American soldiers. That can't happen.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gstalter |first1=Morgan |title=WHO official warns against calling it 'Chinese virus', says 'there is no blame in this' |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/488479-who-official-warns-against-calling-it-chinese-virus-says-there-is-no |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shinkman |first1=Paul |title=Trump Fires Back at Complaints He's Stigmatizing China Over Coronavirus |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/national-news/articles/2020-03-17/trump-refutes-claims-of-anti-chinese-stigma-in-coronavirus-reponse |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=[[US News]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Trump stopped using the term on March 23, citing the possibility of \"nasty language\" towards Asian-Americans.<ref name=\"DelaneyMarch24\">[https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/3076522/donald-trump-drops-chinese-virus-terminology-white \"Donald Trump drops 'Chinese virus' terminology in White House briefing, calls for protecting Asian-Americans\"], ''South China Morning Post'', March 24, 2020</ref> On March 26, President Trump spoke on the phone with China's President [[Xi Jinping]], when they pledged to cooperate in fighting against the pandemic. It signaled a fresh d\u00e9tente between the two countries after weeks of rising tensions.<ref name=\"phonecall\">{{cite news |last1=Leigh |first1=Karen |title=Trump, Xi Vow Virus Cooperation After Weeks of Rising Tensions |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-27/trump-touts-very-good-talk-with-xi-as-u-s-cases-surpass-china |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Trump described their conversation: \n{{quote|Just finished a very good conversation with President Xi of China. Discussed in great detail the Coronavirus that is ravaging large parts of our Planet. China has been through much and has developed a strong understanding of the Virus. We are working closely together. Much respect!<ref name=\"phonecall\" />}}\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49668784683).jpg|thumb|March 16: [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] briefs the media]]\nOn the same day, after a video call summit with the other [[G20]] leaders, Trump stated the United States was working with international allies to stop the spread of the coronavirus and to increase rapid information and data sharing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Batrawy |first1=Aya |last2=Lederer |first2=Edith M. |title=World leaders vow to coordinate virus response in video call |url=https://apnews.com/b1379fde50341508f095381191b9a71c |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter learning about a French clinical study which showed a 70% cure rate in 20 patients,<ref name=\"IrishTimes\">{{cite news |last1=Marlowe |first1=Lara |title=Coronavirus: France hoping unorthodox virologist can save world |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/coronavirus-france-hoping-unorthodox-virologist-can-save-world-1.4210278 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Elder |first1=Lane |title=Things to know about the malaria drug proposed to treat COVID-19 |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/what-hydroxychloroquine-effective-treating-coronavirus/awkTbcGymLAECtNmhyRLsO/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Trump promoted the drugs [[chloroquine]] (also known as [[chloroquine phosphate]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Medicines for the Prevention of Malaria While Traveling Chloroquine (Aralen\u2122) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/malaria/resources/pdf/fsp/drugs/Chloroquine.pdf |website=CDC.gov |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |quote=Chloroquine (also known as chloroquine phosphate) is an antimalarial medicine.}}</ref> and [[hydroxychloroquine]] as potential treatments \"by prescription\" for COVID-19 on March 19. He noted the drugs showed \"tremendous promise\" and said he was working together with Governor Cuomo to begin quickly studying and treating coronavirus patients with the drugs in New York. He also remarked on their long-term usage as medicines in the United States saying, \"the nice part is, it's been around for a long time, so we know that if it\u2014if things don't go as planned, it's not going to kill anybody.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nisen |first1=Max |title=Trump Is Overhyping Unproven Coronavirus Drugs |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/trump-is-overhyping-unproven-coronavirus-drugs/2020/03/19/ed1ff4e2-6a1a-11ea-b199-3a9799c54512_story.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |agency=Bloomberg |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=March19Briefing>{{cite web |title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-press-briefing-6/ |publisher=White House |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Fatal overdoses of these drugs have occurred, and potential side effects are also known.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vergano |first1=Dan |title=Chloroquine Is Being Touted As A Miracle Drug For Coronavirus, But There Are Reasons To Be Wary |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/danvergano/chloroquine-dangers-coronavirus?bfsource=relatedmanual |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=[[Buzzfeed News]] |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Also during the briefing, Trump falsely claimed that chloroquine had already been \"approved very, very quickly\" by the FDA as a treatment for COVID-19 (leading the FDA to clarify that it had not yet approved any COVID-19 treatments<ref name=\":9\">{{cite news |last1=Dale |first1=Daniel |title=Fact check: Trump wrongly claims FDA 'approved' drug chloroquine to treat the coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/fact-check-chloroquine-trump-fda/index.html |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> but was now allowing chloroquine for life-threatening coronavirus cases under compassionate use guidelines).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Naftulin |first1=Julia |title=The FDA is allowing two drugs to be used for 'compassionate use' to treat the coronavirus. Here's what that means. |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/chloroquine-remdesivir-compassionate-use-coronavirus-what-it-means-2020-3 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Coppock |first1=Kristen |title=FDA Announces Two Drugs Given 'Compassionate Use' Status in Treating COVID-19 |url=https://www.pharmacytimes.com/news/fda-announces-two-drugs-approved-for-compassionate-use-in-treating-covid-19 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=Pharmacy Times |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithin days of this briefing, a shortage occurred for chloroquine and hydroxychloroquine in the United States, while panic-buying occurred overseas in Africa and South Asia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rowland |first1=Christopher |title=As Trump touts an unproven coronavirus treatment, supplies evaporate for patients who need those drugs |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/20/hospitals-doctors-are-wiping-out-supplies-an-unproven-coronavirus-treatment/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parkinson |first1=Joe |last2=Gauthier-Villars |first2=David |title=Trump Claim That Malaria Drugs Treat Coronavirus Sparks Warnings, Shortages |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-claim-that-malaria-drugs-treat-coronavirus-sparks-warnings-shortages-11584981897 |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> In the [[state of Arizona]], a man died, with his wife in critical condition, after they ingested fish bowl cleaner, which contained chloroquine phosphate. The couple believed the chemical cleaner could prevent them from contracting COVID-19, although the chloroquine phosphate in fish bowl cleaners is not the same formulation found in the medicines chloroquine or hydroxychloroquine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gander |first1=Kashmira |title=Health Officials Warn Against Self-Medicating With Chloroquine for Coronavirus After Man Dies From Taking Fish Tank Cleaner |url=https://www.newsweek.com/health-officials-warn-against-self-medicating-chloroquine-coronavirus-after-man-dies-taking-fish-1493874 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The woman said she'd watched Trump's briefing in which she believed he promoted chloroquine as \"basically pretty much a cure\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galvan |first1=Astrid |last2=Cooper |first2=Jonathan J. |title=Man dead, wife critically ill after taking additive found in anti-malaria drug touted by Trump as coronavirus treatment |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/coronavirus/ct-nw-coronavirus-chloroquine-phosphate-death-20200324-nu3qrbdqcvdwjnoed44g5vcbcy-story.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |agency=Associated Press |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the same briefing, Trump also discussed remdesivir as another promising COVID-19 therapy.<ref name=March19Briefing />\n\nOn March 22, Trump indicated that he was considering scaling back physical distancing measures implemented around a week ago: \"We cannot let the cure be worse than the problem itself.\" A day later, he argued that economic problems arising from physical distancing measures will cause \"suicides by the thousands\" (without citing evidence) and \"probably more death\" than COVID-19 itself. He declared that the United States would \"soon, be open for business\", in a matter of weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clench |first1=Sam |title=Coronavirus: Donald Trump wants to 'reopen' US economy in weeks, not months |url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/coronavirus-donald-trump-wants-to-reopen-us-economy-in-weeks-not-months/news-story/42206bca2be90f0e0b02cd69fa0e7323 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[news.com.au]] |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bartz |first1=Diane |title=Trump says restrictions will lead to thousands of deaths, cites no evidence |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-trump-restrictions/trump-says-restrictions-will-lead-to-thousands-of-deaths-cites-no-evidence-idUSKBN21B34A |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |agency=Reuters |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> On March 24, Trump expressed a target of lifting restrictions \"if it's good\" by April 12, the Easter holiday, for \"packed churches all over our country\".<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news |last1=Liptak |first1=Kevin |last2=Vazquez |first2=Maegan |last3=Valencia |first3=Nick |last4=Acosta |first4=Jim |title=Trump says he wants the country 'opened up and just raring to go by Easter', despite health experts' warnings |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/24/politics/trump-easter-economy-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> However, a survey of prominent economists by the University of Chicago indicated abandoning an economic lock-down prematurely would do more economic damage than maintaining it.<ref name=\"IGM_Lockdown\"/> Law and economics scholars have argued that the lockdown is justified based on a cost-benefit analysis. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-03-26/coronavirus-lockdowns-look-smart-under-cost-benefit-scrutiny|title= Coronavirus: Lockdowns Look Smart Under Cost-Benefit Analysis |website=Bloomberg|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=3573397|title= COVID-19: Is the Cure \u201cWorse Than the Problem Itself\u201d? |website=SSRN|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> On March 29, Trump extended the federal government's guidance through April 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/29/coronavirus-latest-news/|title=Live updates: Trump says federal guidance urging social distancing will stay in place through April 30|website=The Washington Post|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Trump raised the possibility of placing a two-week enforceable quarantine on New York, New Jersey, and \"certain parts of Connecticut\" to prevent travel from those places to Florida.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haring |first1=Bruce |title=President Trump Now Considering Quarantine For NY, NJ And Connecticut |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/presidenti-trump-considering-quarantine-for-new-york-new-jersey-connecticut-1202895023/ |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The federal quarantine power is limited to preventing people reasonably believed to be infected with a communicable disease from entering the country or crossing state lines.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Parmet |first1=Wendy E. |last2=Sinha |first2=Michael S. |title=Covid-19\u2014The Law and Limits of Quarantine |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |date=March 18, 2020 |doi=10.1056/NEJMp2004211 |pmid=32187460 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Later that day, following criticism from the three governors, Trump withdrew the quarantine proposal. Instead, the CDC issued a travel advisory advising residents of the three states to \"refrain from non-essential domestic travel for 14 days effective immediately\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Live Updates: Trump Drops Idea of Quarantining New York Region |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/world/coronavirus-news.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> On March 30, Trump said the total number of Americans who would die during the epidemic could be 100,000 or more, following a statement from Fauci that 100,000 to 200,000 Americans could die of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bohn |first1=Kevin |title=Trump concedes US coronavirus death toll could be 100,000 or more |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/29/politics/trump-deaths-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n====Administration officials====\n\n[[File:President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force Brief the Press (49645645448).jpg|thumb|U.S. Surgeon General [[Jerome Adams]] speaks to the press]]\n\nDuring the early stages of the outbreak, Trump administration officials gave mixed assessments of the seriousness and scale of the COVID-19 outbreak. CDC Director Robert Redfield said in late January that \"the immediate risk to the American public is low,\" then in late February stated it would be \"prudent to assume this pathogen will be with us for some time to come\". While federal economic policy chief [[Larry Kudlow]] was declaring the COVID-19 spread being contained \"pretty close to airtight\" in late February, Dr. [[Nancy Messonnier]] (head of the National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases) and [[Anthony Fauci]] (head of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]) warned of the impending community spread of the virus in the United States, with Messonnier stating: \"Disruption to everyday life might be severe.\" Around this point, [[Stephen Hahn (oncologist)|Stephen Hahn]], the head of the FDA, warned of national medical supplies being disrupted due to the outbreak. Later in early March, the [[Surgeon General of the United States|U.S. Surgeon General]], Vice Admiral [[Jerome Adams]], declared that \"this is likely going to get worse before it gets better.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goldberg |first1=Dan |title='It's going to disappear': Trump's changing tone on coronavirus |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/17/how-trump-shifted-his-tone-on-coronavirus-134246 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> In March, while giving public briefings from the White House addressing the pandemic, many administration officials and health experts took time to thank Trump for his leadership, as he watched nearby.<ref name=McGrawMarch24/>\n\nIn February 2020, the CDC was notifying the press that it was expecting the infections to spread, and urged local governments, businesses, and schools to develop plans for the outbreak. Among the suggested preparations were canceling mass gatherings, switching to teleworking, and planning for continued business operations in the face of increased absenteeism or disrupted supply chains.<ref name=\"ABC CDC expects spread\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/coronavirus-live-updates-cdc-warns-americans-significant-disruption/story?id=69190968 |title=CDC warns Americans of 'significant disruption' from coronavirus |last=Winsor |first=Morgan |last2=Schumaker |first2=Erin |website=[[ABC News]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |last3=Nathanson |first3=Marc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226000813/https://abcnews.go.com/International/coronavirus-live-updates-cdc-warns-americans-significant-disruption/story?id=69190968 |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> CDC officials warned that widespread transmission may force large numbers of people to seek hospitalization and other healthcare, which may overload healthcare systems.<ref name=\"CDC COVID-19 Situation Summary\" /> Public health officials stressed that local governments would need assistance from the federal government if there were school and business closures.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |last1=transcript |title=Transcript: Chris Murphy on \"Face the Nation\", March 8, 2020 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/transcript-chris-murphy-on-face-the-nation-march-8-2020/ |website=Face the Nation |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> On March 23, Surgeon General Jerome Adams made several media appearances, in which he endorsed physical distancing measures and warned the country: \"This week, it's going to get bad{{nbsp}}... we really, really need everyone to stay at home [...] Every single second counts. And right now, there are not enough people out there who are taking this seriously.\"<ref name=OpryskoMarch23>{{cite news |last1=Oprysko |first1=Caitlin |last2=Forgey |first2=Quint |title='Our country wasn't built to be shut down': Trump pushes back against health experts |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/23/trump-coronavirus-lockdown-skepticism-143800 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> On March 31, the CDC released several projections of the end of the epidemic. Under the best case scenario, more Americans will die of coronavirus than in the [[Vietnam War]] and [[Korean War]] combined.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shear |first1=Michael D. |last2=Crowley |first2=Michael |last3=Glanz |first3=James |title=Coronavirus May Kill 100,000 to 240,000 in U.S. Despite Actions, Officials Say |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/us/politics/coronavirus-death-toll-united-states.html |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Peter |title=Trump Confronts a New Reality Before an Expected Wave of Disease and Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/us/politics/coronavirus-trump.html |work=The New York Times |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> On April 5, [[Anthony Fauci]] said as many as 50% of coronavirus carriers may be asymptomatic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Live Updates: Trump Again Promotes Use of Unproven Anti-Malaria Drug; Deaths in Country May Be Undercounted |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/world/coronavirus-live-news-updates.html#link-327dd1e4 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===U.S. military response===\n\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships|2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)}}\n[[File:USNS Comfort in NYC, 1 April 2020.jpg|thumb|{{USNS|Comfort|T-AH-20|6}} docked in [[Manhattan]], New York City]]\n\nAfter mid-March 2020, the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] made a major move to use the [[United States Armed Forces|U.S. military]] to add health care capacity to impacted areas. The [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] (USACE), under existing statutory authority that comes from authorizations and powers of the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (FEMA), is leasing a large number of buildings nationwide such as hotels, college dormitories, and larger open buildings to immediately convert them into hospital facilities. To assist USACE and FEMA efforts, the [[United States Army]] are dispatching medical soldiers to set up [[field hospital]]s in cities widely affected by the pandemic. Some of these facilities will have [[Intensive care unit|ICU]] capability for patients of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic]], while others will serve non-coronavirus patients to allow established hospitals to concentrate on the pandemic. A public briefing of the plan was given by Army General [[Todd T. Semonite|Todd Semonite]] on March 20, 2020. USACE will handle leasing and engineering, with contracts for rapid facility modification and setup issued to local contractors. The plan envisions that the operation of the facilities and the provision of medical staff would be entirely handled by the various U.S. states rather than the Federal government.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> One of the early and largest buildings to be converted is the [[Jacob K. Javits Convention Center]] in New York City, which was quickly being transformed into a 2,000-bed care facility on March 23, 2020.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-23/n-y-s-javits-center-to-add-2-000-beds-to-system-under-strain N.Y.'s Javits Center to Add 2,000 Beds to System Under Strain] March 23, 2020 Bloomberg L.P.. Retrieved March 26, 2020</ref>\n\nIn addition to the many popup hospitals nationwide, the [[United States Navy]] on March 18 prepared to deploy two [[hospital ship]]s, {{USNS|Mercy|T-AH-19|6}} and {{USNS|Comfort|T-AH-20|6}}, to affected areas. The ships will take in non-coronavirus patients transferred from land-based hospitals, so those hospitals can concentrate on virus cases.<ref name=ships>{{cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/Explore/News/Article/Article/2116862/hospital-ships-other-dod-assets-prepare-for-coronavirus-response/|title=Hospital Ships, Other DOD Assets Prepare for Coronavirus Response|website=U.S. Department of Defense|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> On March 22, Trump announced that ''Comfort'' would go to the East Coast and ''Mercy'' to the West Coast. He added the government may be using cruise ships.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-press-briefing-8/|title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing|website=The White House|access-date=March 24, 2020 }}</ref> ''Mercy'' arrived in Los Angeles on March 27,<ref name = mercyarrives>{{cite news|url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/coronavirus/2020/03/27/usns-mercy-arrives-in-los-angeles-to-support-covid-19-response/|title=USNS Mercy arrives in Los Angeles to support Covid-19 response|last=Correll|first=Diana Stancy|date=March 27, 2020|work=Navy Times|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> and ''Comfort'' arrived in New York City on March 30.<ref name=comfortarrives>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/usns-comfort-arrives-in-nyc-monday-to-help-hospital-with-non-coronavirus-patients/2350317/|title=Crowds Greet USNS Comfort in NYC Monday; Ship to Help Hospitals With Non-Coronavirus Patients|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, it was reported that the [[United States Department of Defense]] was working to provide 100,000 military-style nylon body bags to fulfill a request from FEMA. Only half this number was already kept in stock by the military.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/coronavirus-latest-news-covid-19-disease_n_5e848e2fc5b6a1bb7650c9e1|title=Coronavirus Live Updates: Protective Gear In National Stockpile Nearly Depleted|last=HuffPost Staff|date=April 1, 2020|website=HuffPost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, citing reduction in on-shore medical capabilities and the closure of facilities at the [[Port of Miami]] to new patients, the U.S. Coast Guard required ships in the [[Organization of the United States Coast Guard#Regional responsibilities - Areas, Districts, and Sectors|Seventh District]] (southeast and Atlantic territories) carrying more than fifty people to prepare to care for sick people onboard indefinitely, for vessels requesting medical evacuation to make arrangements with an on-shore hospital, and for foreign vessels to seek medical assistance from their country of registration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/01/825205607/coast-guard-tells-cruise-ships-with-covid-19-cases-to-stay-away-from-u-s-ports|title=Coast Guard Tells Cruise Ships With COVID-19 Cases To Stay Away From U.S. Ports|last=Chappell|first=Bill|date=April 1, 2020|website=NPR|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>[https://homeport.uscg.mil/Lists/Content/Attachments/62863/MSIB%2020-001%20COVID-19%20Cruiseship%20Medical%20Capabilities_Signed.29Mar20.pdf Marine Safety Information Bulletin 01-20, March 29, 2020]</ref> Despite earlier opposition from the governor of Florida, arrangements were made allowing {{MS|Zaandam}} and {{MS|Rotterdam}} to dock at [[Port Everglades]] on April{{nbsp}}2 after nearly two hundred people became ill with COVID-19 and four passengers died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826126190/cruise-ships-with-sick-people-to-dock-in-florida|title=Cruise Ships With Sick People Dock In Florida|last=Allen|first=Greg|date=April 2, 2020|website=NPR|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n\nThe pandemic, along with the resultant [[2020 stock market crash|stock market crash]] and other impacts, has led to increased discussion of a recession in the United States.<ref name=\"USATodayRecession\">{{cite news |title=It may feel like 2008 all over again, but here's how the coronavirus crisis is distinct |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/11/recession-heres-how-coronavirus-crises-different-2008/5012228002/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312201200/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/11/recession-heres-how-coronavirus-crises-different-2008/5012228002/ |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Experts differ on whether a recession will actually take place, with some saying it is not inevitable and others saying the country may already be in a recession.<ref name=\"USATodayRecession\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Jeff |title=Economist Alan Blinder says the US is probably already in recession |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/economist-alan-blinder-says-the-us-is-probably-already-in-recession.html |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312181138/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/economist-alan-blinder-says-the-us-is-probably-already-in-recession.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2020-03-16/us-economic-recession-coronavirus-ucla-anderson-forecast|title=US economy is now in recession, UCLA Anderson Forecast says|first1=Laurence|last1=Darmiento|url-access=subscription|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Of the economists surveyed in March by the [[University of Chicago]], 51% agreed or strongly agreed there would be a \"major\" recession caused by COVID-19, while 31% were uncertain or disagreed.<ref>{{cite news |title=IGM Economic Experts Panel Coronavirus |url=http://www.igmchicago.org/igm-economic-experts-panel |accessdate=March 16, 2020|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEconomic analysts revised their forecasts downward going into March,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/dire-forecast-us-economy-could-tank-4-in-the-second-quarter-as-nation-shuts-down-to-fight-coronavirus-2020-03-12|title=Dire forecast: U.S. economy could tank 4% in the second quarter as nation shuts down to fight coronavirus|first=Jeffry|last=Bartash|website=MarketWatch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-jpmorgan-usa/jp-morgan-slashes-forecast-for-u-s-gdp-sees-14-second-quarter-drop-idUSKBN2153HU?il=0|title=JP Morgan economist says U.S. GDP could drop 14% in second-quarter|first1=Ann|last1=Saphir|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> with [[Goldman Sachs]] estimating on March 20 that the economy could contract by as much as 24% on an annualized basis during the second quarter of 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/u-s-economy-could-contract-by-24-next-quarter-goldman-sachs-says-51584713292|title=The U.S. Economy Could Contract by 24% Next Quarter, Goldman Sachs Says|first1=Alexandra|last1=Scaggs|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020|website=barrons.com}}</ref> following their 5% decline estimate just four days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/economy/global-recession-coronavirus/index.html|title=The global coronavirus recession is beginning|first1=Julia|last1=Horowitz|date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref> [[James B. Bullard|James Bullard]], the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, estimated that GDP would halve in the second quarter.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Matthews |first1=Steve |title=Fed's Bullard Says U.S. Can Well Afford Trillions in Relief Debt |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/on-small-business/feds-bullard-says-us-can-well-afford-trillions-in-relief-debt/2020/03/30/5ea8e642-7299-11ea-ad9b-254ec99993bc_story.html |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |agency=Bloomberg |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an analysis discussed in the ''New York Times'', insurance premiums may rise by 40% next year because coronavirus costs were not taken into account when setting 2020 premiums. The total healthcare costs of treating the epidemic could be anywhere from $34 billion to $251 billion according to the analysis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abelson |first1=Reed |title=Coronavirus May Add Billions to the Nation's Health Care Bill |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/28/health/coronavirus-insurance-premium-increases.html?algo=identity&fellback=false&imp_id=351649575&imp_id=888116964&action=click&module=Science%20%20Technology&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Travel===\n\n{{external media|float=right|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qepa8bS72S8 CNBC interview with Southwest CEO Gary Kelly on March 5], YouTube video|video2=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HRFGB7VMg0k KOMO: Coronavirus Impact on Air Travel], YouTube video}}\n\nIn mid-March, most major American and foreign airlines began cutting back on domestic and international flights as a result of the sudden drop in travel demand from the pandemic and subsequent travel bans. They have phased out routes and were making frequent schedule updates.<ref name=nyt-airlines>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/travel/international-airlines-service-cuts-coronavirus.html \"Airlines Cut International Flights in Response to the Pandemic\"], ''The New York Times'', March 17, 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/12/delta-command-center-coronavirus/?arc404=true \"Inside Delta's command center the week the coronavirus devastated the airline industry\"], ''The Washington Post'', March 13, 2020</ref> Cruise lines suspended all departures from the United States on March 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cruising.org:443/news-and-research/press-room/2020/march/clia-covid-19-toolkit|title=CLIA Announces Voluntary Suspension in U.S. Cruise Operations|website=Cruise Line Industry Association}}</ref>\n\nThe outbreak produced occasional disruptions to [[air traffic control]] with [[area control center]]s in New York and Indianapolis, and airport towers at [[Midway International Airport]] in Chicago and [[McCarran International Airport]] in Las Vegas evacuated for sterilization after at least one person who had been in each tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/32680/americas-air-traffic-control-system-is-suffering-crippling-shutdowns-due-to-covid-19|title=America's Air Traffic Control System Is Suffering Crippling Shutdowns Due To COVID-19|first=Stephen|last=Walker|website=The Drive|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:President Trump and the Vice President meet with Airline CEOs about the Coronavirus (49618513938).jpg|thumb|March 4: President Trump and Airline CEOs discuss COVID-19's impact on the [[Air transportation in the United States|travel industry]]]]\n\nOn March 14, [[Amtrak]] reduced its service between Washington and Boston as the COVID-19 outbreak drastically decreased travel demand. It faced steep revenue losses during the crisis. It also asked noncritical employees \"to take time off on an unpaid basis\".<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/14/amtrak-cuts-more-trains-coronavirus-impacts-travel-demand/ \"Amtrak cuts more trains as coronavirus lessens demand\"], ''The Washington Post'', March 14, 2020</ref> By the following week, New York's subways, usually the nation's busiest, were running mostly empty, which had the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] using $1&nbsp;billion from its line of credit to stay afloat.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/in-a-week-the-coronavirus-razed-us-transit-and-rail-systems/2020/03/22/ca58a88a-6a21-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html \"In a week, the coronavirus razed U.S. transit and rail systems\"], ''The Washington Post'', March 22, 2020</ref>\n\nThe lobbying group for the airline industry, [[Airlines for America|Airlines for America (A4A)]], on March 16 called for a $50 billion subsidy, including $4&nbsp;billion for cargo services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/business-a-lobbying/487820-airline-industry-calls-for-25b-in-assistance-for|title=Airline industry calls for $50B in assistance|last=Gangitano|first=Alex|date=2020-03-16|website=The Hill|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> [[CNBC]] reports that airlines are preparing for a ban on domestic flights after President Trump said on March 14 he is considering travel curbs and acting DHS Secretary [[Chad Wolf]] said all options remained on the table when asked about a possible ban, the first since September 11, 2001. United Airlines said they expected a drop of $1.5 billion in March revenue, American Airlines said they expected to decrease domestic capacity by 20% in April and 30% in May, and Delta Air Lines told employees it would cut capacity by 40%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-makes-airlines-consider-chances-for-a-halt-to-us-flights.html|title=Coronavirus forces airlines to consider a once unthinkable possibility\u2014halting US flights|last=Josephs|first=Leslie|date=2020-03-16|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nSeveral of the largest mass transit operators in the U.S. have reduced service in response to lower demand caused by work from home policies and self-quarantines. The loss of fares and [[sales tax]], a common source of operating revenue, is predicted to cause long-term effects on transit expansion and maintenance.<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Kate |date=March 17, 2020 |title=No Bus Service. Crowded Trains. Transit Systems Struggle With the Virus. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/coronavirus-buses-trains-detroit-boston.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The [[American Public Transportation Association]] issued a request for $13 billion in emergency funding from the federal government to cover lost revenue and other expenses incurred by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lindblom |first1=Mike |last2=Groover |first2=Heidi |date=March 19, 2020 |title=Sound Transit, Metro facing big drops in funding as coronavirus downturn takes hold |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/sound-transit-metro-facing-big-drops-in-funding-as-coronavirus-downturn-takes-hold/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Many localities reported an increase in bicycling as residents sought socially distant means of getting around.<ref name=\"GristBikes\">{{cite news |last1=Anderson |first1=L.V. |title=Coronavirus has caused a bicycling boom in New York City |url=https://grist.org/climate/coronavirus-has-caused-a-bicycling-boom-in-new-york-city/ |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=Grist |date=March 13, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Financial market impacts===\n\n{{see also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:March 3, 2020 FOMC Press Conference NZ73153 (49614546592).jpg|thumb|March 3: Federal Reserve chairman [[Jerome Powell]] announces a 50 basis point (0.5% percentage point) interest rate cut in light of \"evolving risks to economic activity\"]]\n\nOn February 27, 2020, the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] (DJIA) dropped 1,191 points, the [[List of largest daily changes in the Dow Jones Industrial Average|largest single-day point drop]] in the index's history at the time; some attributed the drop to anxiety about the epidemic.<ref name=\"USA Today Dow Feb 27\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/02/27/dow-markets-plunge-correction-coronavirus/4889977002/|title=Dow plunges 1,191 points, its biggest one-day point drop, as coronavirus fears escalate|last=Menton|first=Jessica|date=February 27, 2020|website=USA Today |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> The same day, the S&P 500 logged a 4.4% decline.<ref name=\"CNBC SP 500 Feb 27\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/27/this-is-the-fastest-stock-market-correction-in-history.html |title=It took stocks only six days to fall into correction, the fastest drop in history |last=Li |first=Yun |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Since then, the record has been beaten five more times during the outbreak on March{{nbsp}}9 (2,013), March 11 (1,465), March 12 (2,353), and finally setting the current record for most points lost in a single day by losing 2,997 points on March 16. It once again fell another 1,338 points on March 18. On March 13, the stock market rebounded for the single largest one-day point gain in the market's history by gaining 1,985 points after Trump declared a state of national emergency to free up resources to combat the virus.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Winck |first1=Ben |title=Live updates: Dow rebounds sharply a day after index tanked its most since 1987 on coronavirus worries |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/stock-market-news-today-index-reaction-coronavirus-global-stimulus-measures-2020-3-1028994772 |website=Markets Insider |publisher=Insider |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dow Jones Industrial Average |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/djia |website=MarketWatch |publisher=MarketWatch |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The six business days it took for the [[S&P 500 Index]] to drop 10% (from February 20 to 27) \"marked the quickest 10% decline from an all-time high in the index's history\".<ref name=\"CNBC SP 500 Feb 27\" /> From January 21 to March 1, the DJIA dropped more than 3,500 points, equating to roughly a 13% decrease.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/28/the-dow-just-lost-12percent-in-one-week-heres-why-and-what-likely-happens-next.html |title=The Dow lost 12% in one week. Here's why and what likely happens next |last=Imbert |first=Fred |website=CNBC\u2014Markets |publisher=CNBC |access-date=March 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302072632/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/28/the-dow-just-lost-12percent-in-one-week-heres-why-and-what-likely-happens-next.html |archive-date=March 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/djia |title=Dow Jones Industrial Average\u2014Overview |website=MarketWatch |publisher=MarketWatch |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206132349/https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/djia |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStock index [[futures contract|futures]] declined sharply during Trump's March 11 address,<ref>{{cite web | title=Are you a robot? | website=Bloomberg | date=March 12, 2020 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-12/u-s-index-futures-fall-after-trump-addresses-nation-k7o2ok5g | access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average|Dow Jones]] declined 10% the following day\u2014the largest daily decline since [[Black Monday]] in 1987\u2014despite the Federal Reserve also announcing it would inject $1.5 trillion into money markets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/03/12/markets-stocks-today-coronavirus/|title=U.S. stock market suffers worst crash since 1987, as Americans wake up to a new normal of life|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> By March 18, investors were shunning even assets considered safe havens during economic crises, such as government bonds and gold, moving into cash positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/markets-enter-new-phasewhere-cash-is-all-that-matters-11584546863|title=Markets Enter New Phase\u2014Where Cash Is All That Matters|first=Paul J.|last=Davies|date=March 18, 2020|work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> By March 20, the Dow Jones was below the level when President Trump was inaugurated on January 20, 2017, having fallen 35% from its February peak.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/business/coronavirus-trump-stock-market.html |title=Stock market's gain under Trump vanishes |website=The New York Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The markets rallied between March 23 and 26, with the Dow having its best three-day gain since 1931. On March 27, the Dow fell 3.5% and the S&P 500 fell 3.2%. The Nasdaq Index also fell. Boeing fell 10%, while Exxon and Disney each fell 6%.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/stock-market-futures-open-to-close-news.html Dow tumbles more than 700 points following a massive 3-day bounce] by Fred Imbert, CNBC, March 26, 2020</ref>\n\n===Employment effects===\n\nThe number of persons filing for [[unemployment insurance]] increased from 211,000 the week ending March 7, to 281,000 for the week ending March 14, an increase of 70,000 or 33%, the largest percent increase since 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lite.cnn.com/en/article/h_95e07e22e32b448a3618b8e935c3a3bc|title=CNNBreaking News, Latest News and Videos|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Just part way through the following week, 15 states had reported nearly 630,000 claims.<ref>{{cite news |title=Initial claims|url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/ICSA |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=fred.stlousfed.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolfers |first1=Justin |last2=Bui |first2=Quoctrung |title=The Staggering Rise in Jobless Claims This Week|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/03/19/upshot/coronavirus-jobless-claims-states.html|accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> [[Goldman Sachs]] forecast that more than two million people would file the week of March 21, an unprecedented number.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. jobless claims could exceed 2 million, Goldman Says|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-20/u-s-weekly-jobless-claims-could-exceed-2-million-goldman-says|accessdate=March 20, 2020 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref> Goldman also forecast that the unemployment rate could rise towards nine percent over the second and third quarters, with much depending on the specifics of government stimulus plans.<ref>{{cite news |title=The U.S. Economy Could Contract by 24% Next Quarter, Goldman Sachs Says|url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/in-the-hunt-for-cash-here-are-5-companies-with-plenty-of-it-51584694800|accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Barrons.com}}</ref> On March 22, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis President James Bullard said the unemployment rate could hit 30 percent between April and June, worse than what it was during the [[Great Depression]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Werner |first1=Erica |last2=Kim |first2=Seung Min |last3=Bade |first3=Rachael |last4=Stein |first4=Jeff |title=Senate falls far short of votes needed to advance coronavirus bill, as clash between Republicans and Democrats intensifies |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/03/22/vast-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-limbo-crunch-times-arrives-capitol-hill/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Newmyer |first1=Tory |title=The Finance 202: An ugly economic quarter ends today. It could get worse but there are reasons to hope. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-finance-202/2020/03/31/the-finance-202-an-ugly-economic-quarter-ends-today-it-could-get-worse-but-there-are-reasons-to-hope/5e825e9d88e0fa101a7562b6/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On March 26, the Labor Department reported a record number of unemployment claims: 3.28 million (previously 695 thousand in October 1982).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/weekly-jobless-claims.html|title=Jobless claims soar past 3 million to record|last=Cox|first=Jeff|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> For the week ending March 28, 6.6 million people filed unemployment claims.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Long |first1=Heather |title=Over 10 million Americans applied for unemployment benefits in March as economy collapsed |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/04/02/jobless-march-coronavirus/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> More than ten million Americans lost their jobs and applied for government aid since mid-March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=6.6 Million Americans Filed for Unemployment Last Week |url=https://slate.com/business/2020/04/unemployment-jobs-numbers-economy-coronavirus.html |work=Slate |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=A record 10 million sought US jobless aid in past 2 weeks |url=https://apnews.com/6bc13d999a9693bd11e13286ec7655f0 |agency=Associated Press |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> During March, women, younger and less educated workers were hardest hit by job losses, 65% of which were in the leisure and hospitality sector.<ref>{{cite news |title=How the coronavirus job cuts played out by sector and demographics |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-jobs/how-the-coronavirus-job-cuts-played-out-by-sector-and-demographics-idUSKBN21M0EL |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=Reuters |date=4 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> As another 6.6 million people filed unemployment claims for the week ending April 4, former Fed Chair [[Janet Yellen]] said the unemployment rate had already reached at least 12 or 13 percent, the worst since the Great Depression.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Long |first1=Heather |last2=Van Dam |first2=Andrew |title=6.6 million Americans filed for unemployment last week, bringing the pandemic total to over 17 million |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/04/09/66-million-americans-filed-unemployed-last-week-bringing-pandemic-total-over-17-million/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Restaurant industry===\n\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States}}\n[[File:Graeter's coronavirus sign 24 March 2020.jpg|alt=Signs read \"We're open, carryout & order pickup only at this time. Get it delivered.\" and \"Please keep social distancing in mind. Keep six feet apart from one another. Please take your order to go once received. Thank you for helping us comply with government health recommendations.\"|thumb]]\n\nThe U.S. restaurant industry was projected to have $899 billion in sales for 2020 by the [[National Restaurant Association]], the main trade association for the industry in the United States.<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2020/03/20/cincinnati-restaurants-ask-feds-for-coronavirus.html|title=Cincinnati restaurants ask feds for coronavirus bailout|last=Brownfield|first=Andy|date=March 20, 2020|website=login.research.cincinnatilibrary.org|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The industry as a whole as of February 2020 employed more than fifteen million people, representing ten percent of the workforce directly.<ref name=\":02\" /> It indirectly employed close to another 10% when dependent businesses such as food producers, trucking, and delivery services were factored in, according to Ohio restaurateur Britney Ruby Miller.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nOn March 15, Ohio Governor [[Mike DeWine]] and Ohio Health Department director [[Amy Acton]] ordered the closure of all bars and restaurants to help slow the spread of the virus, saying the government \"encouraged restaurants to offer carryout or delivery service, but they would not be allowed to have people congregating in the businesses.\"<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487684-ohio-closing-all-bars-restaurants-in-response-to-coronavirus|title=Illinois, Ohio closing all bars, restaurants in response to coronavirus|last=Conradis|first=Brandon|date=March 15, 2020|website=thehill.com}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200315/coronavirus-governor-orders-ohio-bars-restaurants-to-shut-down|title=Coronavirus: Governor orders Ohio bars, restaurants to shut down|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=The Columbus Dispatch|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316153943/https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200315/coronavirus-governor-orders-ohio-bars-restaurants-to-shut-down|archive-date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The next day, Illinois, New York, New Jersey, and Maryland followed suit.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Witte|first=Griff|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-ohio-dewine-outbreak/2020/03/16/9bde6b1e-67b2-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html|title=Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine's coronavirus response has become a national guide to the crisis|date=March 16, 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=March 22, 2020|last2=Zezima|first2=Katie}}</ref>\n\nGroups of restaurateurs in New York City and Cincinnati called on governments to provide help to the nation's small and independent restaurants.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/accessibility/488670-how-nycs-restaurant-industry-is-surviving-amid|title=How NYC's restaurant industry is surviving amid coronavirus closures|last=Somvichian-Clausen|first=Austa|date=March 20, 2020|website=TheHill|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" /> On March 19 the New York group called for state governments to issue orders for rent abatements, suspension of sales and payroll taxes, and a full shutdown so business interruption insurance coverage would be triggered.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://ny.eater.com/2020/3/19/21187117/momofuku-major-food-group-starr-restaurants-relief-coronavirus-nyc|title=NYC's Top Restaurant Groups Band Together to Petition for Government Relief|last=Adams|first=Erika|date=March 19, 2020|website=Eater NY|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> On March 20 the Cincinnati group called on the federal government to provide a $225 billion bailout to the restaurant industry.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nSeveral restaurant chains altered their operating procedures to prevent the spread of the virus, including removing seating, restricting the use of condiments, and switching to [[mobile payment]] systems. Many restaurants opted to close their dining rooms and instead switch to solely take-out food service to comply with [[physical distancing]] recommendations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/food/2020/03/15/starbucks-coronavirus-changes-mobile-orders-drive-thru-closing-locations/5055192002/|title=Starbucks closing some locations and moving to a 'to go' model at other stores due to coronavirus|author=Tyko, Kelly|date=March 15, 2020|work=USA Today|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Retail===\n\n[[File:Best Buy Line I (49674924422).jpg|thumb|March 18: [[Best Buy]] lets only a limited number of people into their Union Square store in New York City]]\n\nA number of retailers, particularly grocery stores, reduced their opening hours to allow additional time to restock and deep-clean their stores.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/14/coronavirus-store-closings-hour-changes/5051282002/ |title=Stores cutting hours or closing because of coronavirus: Walmart, Apple, Nike, Albertsons, Trader Joe's, more |author=Tyko, Kelly |work=USA Today |date=March 14, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Major stores such as [[Walmart]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Albertson's]], and [[Trader Joe's]] also shortened their hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/14/coronavirus-store-closings-hour-changes/5051282002/|title=Stores cutting hours or closing because of coronavirus: Walmart, Apple, Nike, Albertsons, Trader Joe's, more|last=Tyko|first=Kelly|website=USA Today|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20200318005807/en/ Latest Walmart Store Changes to Support Associates and Customers] Business Wire</ref> Some grocery store chains, including [[Stop & Shop]] and [[Dollar General]], devoted a portion of their operating hours to serve only senior citizens.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/16/coronavirus-seniors-dollar-general-dedicates-hour-senior-shoppers/5065594002/ |title=Dollar General cuts store hours, dedicates hour to senior shoppers during coronavirus pandemic |author=Tyko, Kelly |work=USA Today |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/food/food/2020/03/16/stop-shop-gives-customers-over-60-their-own-shopping-hours |title=Stop & Shop gives customers over 60 their own shopping hours |author=Pickell, Jack |work=Boston Globe |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Many grocery stores and pharmacies began installing plexiglass sneeze guards at register areas to protect cashiers and pharmacists, and adding markers six feet apart at checkout lines to encourage customers to maintain physical distance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/coronavirus-leads-grocers-install-plexiglass-014739290.html|title=Coronavirus leads Walmart, other grocers to install plexiglass to protect employees, customers|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\nTo prevent hoarding, many supermarkets and retailers placed limits on certain products such as toilet paper, hand sanitizer, over-the-counter medication, and cleaning supplies.<ref name=\"hoarding\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/15/trump-no-hoarding-coronavirus-grocery-stores-130771 |title=Trump urges no hoarding as coronavirus panic strains grocery stores |author=McCrimmon, Ryan |work=Politico |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> However, the [[Food Marketing Institute]] announced that its supply chain was not strained and all products would be available in the future.<ref name=\"hoarding\"/> Major retail chains started hiring tens of thousands of employees to keep up with demand, including Walmart (150,000), [[CVS Pharmacy]] (50,000), Dollar General (50,000), and [[7 Eleven]] (20,000).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexandrasternlicht/2020/03/20/whos-hiring-in-the-coronavirus-economy-2736-increase-for-warehouse-handler-7-eleven-adds-20000-postings-more/|title=Updated: Instacart To Hire 300,000 New Shoppers, CVS And Dollar General Add 50,000 Jobs Each\u2014Who's Hiring In Coronavirus Economy|first=Alexandra|last=Sternlicht|website=Forbes|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n[[Sheetz]] convenience stores began offering free meals to children in need at select stores in Maryland, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania and West Virginia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/sheetz-offering-free-kids-meals-to-help-during-coronavirus-pandemic.html|title=Sheetz offering free kids meals to help during coronavirus pandemic|date=April 1, 2020|website=[[The Patriot-News]]}}</ref> A daily senior shopping hour, checkout line distancing markers, hand washing and sanitizer for employees, disinfecting wipes for customers to use on carts, and a ban on reusable bags became mandatory in Massachusetts on March 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/doc/grocery-and-pharmacy-store-order/download|title=Order of the Commissioner of Public Health, March 25 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Many stores began limiting the number of people inside at a time, to increase the typical distance between customers, resulting in outdoor lines with people spaced six feet apart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/target-lowes-home-depot-to-limit-the-number-of-customers-inside-to-combat-spread-of/article_ac5e4948-761a-11ea-b0ce-47befba7acaa.html|title=Target, Lowe's, Home Depot to limit the number of customers inside to combat spread of COVID-19|website=WDRB}}</ref>\n\n===Shipping facilities===\n\nSince consumers were increasingly relying on online retailers, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] planned to hire another 100,000 warehouse and delivery workers and raise wages $2 per hour through April. They also reported shortages of certain household staples.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/amazon-to-hire-100000-warehouse-and-delivery-workers.html Amazon to hire 100,000 more workers and give raises to current staff to deal with coronavirus demands] by Annie Palmer, CNBC, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\nA March 21 article in the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' reported that employees at [[United Parcel Service|UPS]], [[FedEx]], and [[XPO Logistics|XPO]] often have been pressured not to take time off, even with symptoms such as fever and cough consistent with coronavirus. Public health authorities say the risk is relatively low to customers receiving packages, in part because coronavirus does not live for very long on cardboard, but it most certainly is a danger for employees on crowded conveyor belts.<ref>[https://www.chicagotribune.com/coronavirus/ct-nw-nyt-coronavirus-package-delivery-employees-sick-20200321-kpijftkmlba3zodkmvtmhxojs4-story.html 'Terrified' package delivery employees are going to work sick], Chicago Tribune (New York Times), March 21, 2020.</ref>\n\nAt its warehouses, Amazon has stopped exit screenings, as well as group meetings at the beginning of shifts, and has staggered shift times and break times. The company also announced it would provide up to two weeks of pay to all employees diagnosed with coronavirus or placed into quarantine, but presumably not for employees who merely have symptoms of fever and cough.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/21/jeff-bezos-memo-about-coronavirus-safety-at-amazon-warehouses.html?&qsearchterm=Read%20the%20memo%20Jeff%20Bezos%20sent%20to%20Amazon%20employees%20about%20coronavirus%20safety%20at%20warehouses Read the memo Jeff Bezos sent to Amazon employees about coronavirus safety at warehouses], CNBC, updated March 22, 2020.</ref> Amazon workers complained paid medical leave was difficult to obtain because of limited access to COVID-19 testing, and some petitioned the company to extend paid leave to elderly and medically vulnerable workers without a positive test.<ref name=\"kentucky\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/26/822045229/amazon-closes-kentucky-warehouse-after-workers-test-positive|title=Amazon Closes Kentucky Warehouse After Workers Test Positive|publisher=NPR|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> As small numbers of workers have tested positive for COVID-19, various Amazon warehouses have closed for sanitization, including one in Kentucky for several days.<ref name=\"kentucky\" /> Amazon workers at the [[Staten Island]] warehouse and some [[Instacart]] workers nationwide separately announced strikes for March 30, demanding access to personal protective equipment, better sick pay, hazard pay for Instacart orders, and a longer closure of the Staten Island warehouse for cleaning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/30/823767492/amazon-instacart-grocery-delivery-workers-strike-for-coronavirus-protection-and-|title=Amazon, Instacart Grocery Delivery Workers Demand Coronavirus Protection And Pay|publisher=NPR|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Production of emergency supplies===\n\n{{See also|Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic }}\n\nIn response to shortages, some alcoholic beverage facilities started manufacturing and distributing alcohol-based [[hand sanitizer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/21/817976872/white-house-to-give-an-update-on-coronavirus-tests-response|title=Pence Tests Negative For COVID-19; 'Hundreds Of Millions' Of Face Masks in Production|publisher=NPR|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[General Motors]] opened its manufacturing, logistics, and purchasing infrastructure for use by Ventec, a manufacturer of medical ventilators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/news/32691/general-motors-becomes-first-us-automaker-to-aid-in-ventilator-production-ramp-up|title=General Motors Becomes First US Automaker Committed to Ventilator Production Ramp-Up|first=James|last=Gilboy|website=The Drive|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> As medical mask manufacturers hired hundreds of new workers and increased output,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/23/metro/honeywell-will-start-making-n95-face-masks-its-smithfield-ri-plant-adding-500-jobs/|title=Honeywell will start making N95 face masks at its Smithfield, R.I., plant, adding 500 jobs |website=Boston Globe|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> in response to urgent requests from hospital workers, volunteers with home sewing machines started producing thousands of non-medical masks that can be sterilized and re-used. Fabric was bought privately or donated by [[Joann Fabrics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/22/metro/mask-making-projects-are-popping-all-over-crafters-mobilize-against-coronavirus/|title=Mask-making projects are popping all over as crafters mobilize against coronavirus |website=Boston Globe|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The CDC recommended the use of homemade masks (preferably in combination with a full-face splash shield) only as a \"last resort\" when no other respiratory protective technologies were available, including reused professional masks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/ppe-strategy/face-masks.html|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Bauer Hockey]] began manufacturing face shields for medical applications on March 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/25/sports/hockey-company-bauer-joins-coronavirus-fight-by-producing-face-shields/|title=New Hampshire-based hockey company Bauer joins coronavirus fight by producing face shields |website=Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nSome U.S. officials and commentators criticized the outsourcing of critical materials\u2014like the production of essential medical supplies\u2014to China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Break with China? Top Trump aide eyes an opening with coronavirus |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/26/trump-china-trade-coronavirus-117531 |work=Politico |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson: Spread of coronavirus is revealing a 'terrifying situation' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/tucker-carlson-coronavirus-pandemic-terrifying-situation-china-drugs |publisher=Fox News Channel |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Surge in medical personnel===\n\nSeveral states and non-profit groups started recruiting retired medical personnel to increase staffing in hospitals and at temporary facilities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5810120/retired-health-care-workers-coronavirus/|title=Who Are the Retired Health Care Workers the U.S. is Calling On To Help With the Coronavirus Response?|website=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/31/nation/preparing-coronavirus-surge-massachusetts-is-recruiting-retired-doctors-nurses-respiratory-therapists/|title=Preparing for a surge in cases, Mass. recruits retired doctors, nurses, respiratory therapists |website=Boston Globe}}</ref> Some jurisdictions granted emergency medical licenses to inactive doctors and incoming resident and interns, and expanded the tasks nurses were allowed to do.<ref name=\"ma-mar27\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/27/baker-out-of-state-quarantine|title=Baker Asks Visitors To Self-Isolate For Two Weeks\u2014Or Not Come at All|website=wbur.org}}</ref>\n\n===Other financial effects===\n\n[[File:President Trump Meets with Banking Leaders (49649253478).jpg|thumb|President Trump with representatives of the [[Banking in the United States|banking industry]], March 11]]\n\nIn February 2020, the American companies [[Apple Inc.]] and [[Microsoft]] began lowering expectations for revenue because of supply chain disruptions in China caused by the virus.<ref name=\"Forbes MSFT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/waynerash/2020/02/27/microsoft-warning-is-a-harbinger-of-coronavirus-impact-on-business-and-the-economy/ |title=Microsoft Warning Is A Harbinger Of Coronavirus Impact On Business and the Economy |last=Rash |first=Wayne |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=February 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228072030/https://www.forbes.com/sites/waynerash/2020/02/27/microsoft-warning-is-a-harbinger-of-coronavirus-impact-on-business-and-the-economy/#628fd0f07449 |archive-date=February 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a February 27 note to clients, [[Goldman Sachs]] said it expects no earnings growth for U.S. companies in 2020 as a result of the virus, at a time when the consensus forecast of Wall Street expected \"earnings to climb 7%\".<ref name=\"CNBC Goldman\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/27/goldman-sees-zero-earnings-growth-for-us-companies-this-year-because-of-coronavirus.html |title=Goldman sees zero earnings growth for US companies this year because of coronavirus |last=Fitzgerald |first=Maggie |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> On March 20, 2020 as part of an [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] filing, [[AT&T]] cancelled all [[Share repurchase|stock buyback]] plans included a plan to repurchase stock worth $4&nbsp;billion during the second quarter. The reasons AT&T gave for the cancellation was to invest the money into its networks and in taking care of its employees during the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/news/att-coronavirus-material-cancels-stock-buyback-plan-1203540168/ |title=AT&T Warns Coronavirus Financial Impact 'Could Be Material', Nixes $4 Billion Stock-Buyback Plan |last=Spangler|first=Todd |date=March 20, 2020 |website=Variety |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the economic damage caused by the pandemic, some economists have advocated for financial support from the government for individual Americans and for banks and businesses.<ref name=\"NYT_Golden\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/opinion/coronavirus-economy.html?action=click&module=Opinion&pgtype=Homepage|title=Can We Stop a Coronavirus Recession?|last=Golden |first=Ian|website=The New York Times|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Mankiw_Blog\">{{cite web |url=http://gregmankiw.blogspot.com/2020/03/thoughts-on-pandemic.html|title=Thoughts on the Pandemic|last=Mankiw|first=Greg|website=gregmankiw.blogstpot.com|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Others have objected to government intervention on the grounds that it would alter the role of the [[Federal Reserve]] and enshrine [[moral hazard]] as a defining market principle.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Petrou |first1=Karen |title=Federal Reserve should not try to fight the coronavirus |url=https://www.ft.com/content/d3bf5890-5ba0-11ea-b0ab-339c2307bcd4 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Telemedicine===\n\nThe COVID-19 pandemic has led to a sharp increase in the use of [[telemedicine|telemedical services]] in the United States, specifically for COVID-19 screening and triage.<ref name=\"Telemedicine demand\">{{cite web |author1=Leah Rosenbaum |title=The Coronavirus Has Created A Surge Of Telemedicine Demand. GoodRx Now Lets Consumers Compare Services |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leahrosenbaum/2020/03/26/the-coronavirus-has-created-a-surge-of-telemedicine-demand-goodrx-now-lets-consumers-compare-services/ |work=Forbes |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Telemedicine surge + Ro's service\">{{cite web |author1=Lauren Clason |title=Telehealth visits surge along with coronavirus cases |url=https://www.rollcall.com/2020/03/24/telehealth-visits-balloon-along-with-coronavirus-cases/ |website=Roll Call |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 26, 2020, [[GoodRx]] launched a telemedicine price comparison platform<ref name=\"GoodRx telemedicine price comparison platform\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Assessments |url=https://www.goodrx.com/treatment/coronavirus |publisher=GoodRx |accessdate=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> that lists the prices of COVID-19 assessments by telemedicine provider and state.<ref name=\"Telemedicine demand\" /> {{As of|2020|3|29|df=US}}, three companies are offering free telemedical screenings for COVID-19 in the United States: [[K Health]] (routed through an AI [[chatbot]]), [[Ro (company)|Ro]] (routed through an AI chatbot), and GoodRx (offered through its HeyDoctor platform).<ref name=\"GoodRx telemedicine price comparison platform\" /><ref name=\"Free COVID-19 providers\">{{cite web |author1=Leah Rosenbaum |title=Worried That You Have Coronavirus? Here's How To See A Doctor For Free in Your Home |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leahrosenbaum/2020/03/18/worried-that-you-have-coronavirus-heres-how-to-see-a-doctor-for-free-in-your-home/ |work=Forbes |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Telemedicine surge + Ro's service\" /><ref name=\"Ro Chatbot\">{{cite web |author1=Leah Rosenbaum |title=Worried About Coronavirus? Now You Can Text Message A Chatbot With Questions |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/leahrosenbaum/2020/03/12/worried-about-coronavirus-now-you-can-text-message-a-chatbot-with-questions/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>{{citation overkill|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Timing of removing economic lockdowns===\n\nOn March 24, Trump expressed a target of lifting restrictions \"if it's good\" by April 12, the Easter holiday, for \"packed churches all over our country\".<ref name=\"auto2\"/> However, a survey of prominent economists by the [[University of Chicago]] indicated abandoning an economic lock-down prematurely would do more economic damage than maintaining it.<ref name=\"IGM_Lockdown\">{{cite news |title=IGM Economic Experts Panel-Policy for the COVID-19 Crisis|url=http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/policy-for-the-covid-19-crisis/|accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=igmchicago.org |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' reported on March 24 that: \"There is, however, a widespread consensus among economists and public health experts that lifting the restrictions would impose huge costs in additional lives lost to the virus\u2014and deliver little lasting benefit to the economy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Shutdown Spotlights Economic Cost of Saving Lives|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/business/economy/coronavirus-economy.html|work=The New York Times |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Bill Gates]] said: \"It's very tough to say to people, 'Hey keep going to restaurants, go buy new houses, ignore that pile of bodies over in the corner, we want you to keep spending because there's some politician that thinks GDP growth is what counts'{{nbsp}}... It's hard to tell people during an epidemic{{nbsp}}... that they should go about things knowing their activity is spreading this disease.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Bill Gates says the US missed its chance to avoid coronavirus shutdown and businesses should stay closed|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/bill-gates-us-missed-its-chance-to-avoid-coronavirus-shutdown.html|publisher=CNBC |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 29, Trump extended the federal physical distancing recommendations until the end of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/30/822448199/how-15-days-became-45-trump-extends-guidelines-to-slow-coronavirus|title=How 15 Days Became 45: Trump Extends Guidelines To Slow Coronavirus|publisher=NPR|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism of proposed remedies===\nIn late March 2020, Nobel Prize-winning economist [[Joseph Stiglitz]] stated Congress was not ready to send out checks now (to individuals) and then if the crisis goes on another four weeks, or six weeks, to send out a second batch of checks. He states the U.S. economy was not in great shape to begin with, for example, with overall growth for March 2020 expected to be less than 2%. The main problem will be that people can't go to work because of fear of the virus. And regarding a welfare safety net, he writes, \"America has the weakest social protection of almost any of the advanced countries and so we're having to patch in a kind of social protection system on the fly and it's going to be really hard and that means the recovery is going to be very difficult.\"<ref>[https://wcbs880.radio.com/articles/news/stiglitz-discusses-possible-economic-fallout-of-coronavirus \"Nobel Prize-Winning Economist Fears Coronavirus Impacts Will Be Worse Than 1929 Fallout\"]. WCBS News Radio. March 24, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Social impacts==\n\nTo minimize the spread of infection, public health officials and political figures have initiated steps to isolate infected patients, impose quarantines, and recommend or require physical distancing during group activities, including the closing of schools, retail stores, workplaces, sports events, and leisure activities such as dining and movies.\n\n===Lockdowns===\n\n{{main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA stay-at-home order county map.svg|thumb|right|300px|States, territories, and counties that issued a [[stay-at-home order]]:\n{{legend|#045a8d|Came into effect between March 15 and 21}}\n{{legend|#2b8cbe|Came into effect between March 22 and 28}}\n{{legend|#74a9cf|Came into effect between March 29 and April 4}}\n{{legend|#a6bddb|Came into effect between April 5 and 11}}\n'''[[Commons:Data:Stay-at-home orders in the United States.map|Full map including municipalities]]''']]\n\nIn extreme instances, a number of cities and states have imposed lockdown measures which limit where people can travel, work and shop away from their homes:\n* California. The Governor has ordered everyone to stay at home except to get food, care for a relative or friend, obtain health care, or go to an \"essential job\". People working in critical infrastructure sectors may continue to go to their jobs, but should try to keep at least six feet apart from anyone else. Indoor restaurants, bars and nightclubs, entertainment venues, gyms and fitness studios are closed, although some restaurants can still provide take-out meals. Gas stations, pharmacies, grocery stores, convenience stores, banks and laundry services remain open.<ref name=WSJ-lockdowns/>\n* New York. Non-essential businesses must shut down their in-office personnel functions, with the exception of financial institutions, retailers, pharmacies, hospitals, news media, manufacturing plants and transportation companies, among others. Casinos, gyms, theaters, shopping malls, amusement parks and bowling alleys are to be closed. \"Non-essential gatherings\" of any size and for any reason are temporarily banned, and in public, people must keep at least six feet away from each other. Residents 70 and older and people with compromised immune systems or underlying illnesses must remain indoors (unless exercising outside), wear a mask in the company of others and prescreen visitors by taking their temperature.<ref name=WSJ-lockdowns/>\n\nSimilar restrictions to varying degree have been imposed in [[Illinois]], [[Texas]], [[Nevada]], [[New Jersey]] and Florida, including the shutting down of hotels.<ref name=lockdowns-2>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-deaths-surpass-10-000-globally-11584698319?cx_testId=3&cx_testVariant=cx_2&cx_artPos=1#cxrecs_s \"Illinois, New York, California, Nevada Tighten Restrictions to Fight Coronavirus\"], ''The Wall Street Journal'', March 20, 2020</ref> {{As of|2020|04|02|alt=As of April 2}}, about 297 million people, or about 90% of the population, are under some form of lockdown in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=About 90% of Americans have been ordered to stay at home. This map shows which cities and states are under lockdown |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-map-stay-at-home-orders-lockdowns-2020-3 |work=Business Insider |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\"\n|+Regions with a lockdown order or advisory<ref name=\"nyt-mervosh-lu-states\">{{cite news |last1=Mervosh |first1=Sarah |last2=Lu |first2=Denise |title=See Which States and Cities Have Told Residents to Stay at Home |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-stay-at-home-order.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!State\n!Date enacted\n|-\t\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Alabama\n|April 4, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Alaska\n|March 28, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Arizona\n|March 31, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |California\n|March 19, 2020\n|-\t\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Colorado\t\n|March 26, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Connecticut\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Delaware\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\t\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Florida\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Hawaii\t\n|March 25, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Idaho\n|March 25, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Illinois\n|March 21, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Indiana\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Kansas\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Kentucky{{efn|name=Advisory|Advisory order}}\n|March 26, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Louisiana\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Maine\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Maryland\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Massachusetts{{efn|name=Advisory}}\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Michigan\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Minnesota\n|March 27, 2020\t\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Mississippi\n|April 3, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Missouri<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joplinglobe.com/coronavirus/missouri-governor-announces-statewide-stay-at-home-order/article_3a15cc62-75f7-11ea-958c-7f92f9cfeec7.html|title=Missouri governor announces statewide stay-at-home order|last=JG Staff|date=April 3, 2020|website=The Joplin Globe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|April 6, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Montana\n|March 28, 2020\t\n|-\t\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Nevada\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |New Hampshire<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmur.com/article/live-at-3-sununu-gives-update-on-covid-19/31941704#|title=Gov. Chris Sununu issues stay-at-home order for New Hampshire|author=Adam Sexton|publisher=WMUR|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\t\n|March 27, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |New Jersey\n|March 21, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |New Mexico\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |New York\n|March 22, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |North Carolina\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Ohio\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Oregon\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Pennsylvania\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Rhode Island\n|March 28, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |South Carolina\n|April 7, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Tennessee\n|March 31, 2020\n|-\t\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Texas\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Vermont\t\n|March 25, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Virginia\n|March 30, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Washington\n|March 23, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Washington, D.C.\n|April 1, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |West Virginia\n|March 24, 2020\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left; |Wisconsin\t\n|March 25, 2020\n|}\n\n===Educational impacts===\n\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}\n[[File:Stevens Elementary School during COVID epidemic 05.jpg|thumb|Playground at a Seattle elementary school, closed due to the epidemic]]\n\n{{As of|2020|04|10|df=US}}, at least 124,000 public and private schools had closed nationwide, affecting at least 55.1 million students, with most schools in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and all five inhabited territories closed statewide.<ref name=\"EdWeekMap\">{{cite web |title=Map: Coronavirus and School Closures |url=https://www.edweek.org/ew/section/multimedia/map-coronavirus-and-school-closures.html |website=Education Week |publisher=Editorial Projects in Education |access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Of these, 19 states and three territories closed school buildings for the remainder of the school year.<ref name=\"EdWeekMap\" /> As schools shift education to online learning, there are concerns about student access to necessary technology, absenteeism, and accommodations for special needs students.<ref>{{cite news|title=As School Moves Online, Many Students Stay Logged Out|last1=Goldstein|first1=Daniel|last2=Popescu|first2=Adam|last3=Hannah-Jones|first3=Nikole|date=April 6, 2020|work=The New York Times|location=New York City, New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/us/coronavirus-schools-attendance-absent.html|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> School systems also looked to adjust grading scales and graduation requirements to mitigate the disruption caused by the unprecedented closures.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grading Students During the Coronavirus Crisis: What's the Right Call?|last=Sawchuk|first=Stephen|date=April 1, 2020|work=Education Week|location=Bethesda, Maryland|url=https://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2020/04/01/grading-students-during-the-coronavirus-crisis-whats.html|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTo ensure poor students continued to receive lunches while schools were closed, many states and school districts arranged for \"grab-and-go\" lunch bags or used school bus routes to deliver meals to children.<ref>{{cite news|title=Schools Scramble to Feed Students After Coronavirus Closures|date=March 14, 2020|agency=Associated Press|work=U.S. News & World Report|location=Washington, D.C.|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/health-news/articles/2020-03-13/schools-scramble-to-feed-students-after-coronavirus-closures|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> To provide legal authority for such efforts, the [[U.S. Department of Agriculture]] waived several school lunch program requirements.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 6201 Update\u2014USDA Issues Nationwide Child Nutrition Waivers|date=March 21, 2020|author=<!--no byline-->|website=News|publisher=School Nutrition Association|location=Arlington, Virginia|url=https://schoolnutrition.org/news-publications/news/2020/usda-issues-nationwide-child-nutrition-waivers/|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA large number of higher educational institutions canceled classes and closed dormitories in response to the outbreak, including all members of the [[Ivy League]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Conor |title=Online classes, travel bans: How the Ivy League is responding to the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.thedp.com/article/2020/03/penn-coronavirus-ivy-league-online-classes-travel |website=thedp.com |accessdate=March 29, 2020 }}</ref> and many other public and private universities across the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Columbia, Harvard, NYU, and other major US colleges and universities that have switched to remote classes and are telling students to move out of dorms to prevent the spread of the coronavirus |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/major-colleges-and-universities-going-remote-over-coronavirus-fears |website=Business Insider |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Many universities also expanded the use of pass/fail [[Academic grading in the United States|grading]] for the Spring 2020 semester.<ref>{{cite news|title=#Pass/Fail Nation|last=Burke|first=Lilah|date=March 19, 2020|work=Inside Higher Education|location=Washington, D.C.|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/03/19/colleges-go-passfail-address-coronavirus|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDue to the disruption to the academic year caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, the [[United States Department of Education|U.S. Department of Education]] approved a waiver process, allowing states to opt-out of standardized testing required under the [[Every Student Succeeds Act]].<ref name=\"NPR-DOE\">{{cite news|title=Education Dept. Makes Changes To Standardized Tests, Student Loans Over Coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|last=Nadworny|first=Elissa|work=Corona Virus Daily|publisher=NPR|location=Washington, D.C.|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/20/818977484/education-dept-makes-changes-to-standardized-tests-student-loans-over-coronaviru|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> In addition, the [[College Board]] eliminated traditional face-to-face [[Advanced Placement exams]] in favor of an online exam that can be taken at home.<ref>{{cite web|title=AP Updates for Schools Impacted by Coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|author=<!--no byline-->|work=AP Central|publisher=The College Board|location=New York City|url=https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/about-ap/news-changes/coronavirus-update|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The College Board also cancelled [[SAT]] testing in March and May in response to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|title=SAT Coronavirus Updates|date=<!--no date-->|author=<!--no byline-->|publisher=College Board|url=https://pages.collegeboard.org/natural-disasters|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Similarly, April [[ACT (test)|ACT exams]] were rescheduled for June 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=ACT Reschedules April 2020 International ACT Test Date to June|website=ACT Newsroom & Blog|date=March 19, 2020|url=http://leadershipblog.act.org/2020/03/act-reschedules-april-2020.html|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Department of Education also authorized limited [[student loan]] relief, allowing borrowers to suspend payments for at least two months without accruing interest.<ref name=\"NPR-DOE\" />\n\n===Prison impacts===\n\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on prisons#United States}}\n\nAs COVID-19 was spreading to several prisons in the U.S., some states and local jurisdictions began to release prisoners considered vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51947802|title=US jails begin releasing prisoners amid pandemic|date=March 19, 2020|work=BBC News|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\nTo reduce transmission, the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] started a near-lockdown for all prisoners on April 1, for at least 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/31/824917318/prisoners-across-country-will-be-confined-for-14-days-to-cut-coronavirus-spread|title=Prisoners Across U.S. Will Be Confined For 14 Days To Cut Coronavirus Spread|website=NPR.org}}</ref>\n\n===Xenophobia and racism===\n\n{{main|List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United States}}\n[[File:Chinatown2.JPG|thumb|[[Chinatown, Houston|Houston's Chinatown]] experienced a reduction in business early during the outbreak when there were still few cases.]]\n\nThere have been [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United States|incidents of xenophobia and racism]] against Chinese Americans and other Asian Americans.<ref name=\"NYT Racism\">{{cite news |last1=Tavernise |first1=Sabrina |last2=Oppel Jr |first2=Richard A. |title=Spit On, Yelled At, Attacked: Chinese-Americans Fear for Their Safety |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/chinese-coronavirus-racist-attacks.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hobbs |first1=Tawnell D. |title=Feds Sound Alarm Over Claims of Asian Discrimination in Schools |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/feds-sound-alarm-over-claims-of-asian-discrimination-in-schools-11583591069 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Wall Street Journal |date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chiu |first1=Allyson |title=Trump has no qualms about calling coronavirus the 'Chinese Virus.' That's a dangerous attitude, experts say. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/03/20/coronavirus-trump-chinese-virus/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Fear of coronavirus fuels racist sentiment targeting Asians |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-03/fear-panic-around-the-coronavirus-fuels-racist-sentiment |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Officials decry anti-Asian bigotry, misinformation amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-03/feinstein-decries-unconscionable-racism-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> It was reported that Asian Americans were purchasing firearms in response to the xenophobia arising from the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3076395/asian-americans-are-stocking-guns-protect-themselves|title=Asian-Americans stock up on guns and ammo during coronavirus pandemic|date=March 24, 2020|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The FBI issued an alert that [[neo-Nazi]] and [[white supremacist]] groups were encouraging members to, if they contract it, spread the virus via \"bodily fluids and personal interactions\" with Jews and police officers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/white-supremacists-encouraging-members-spread-coronavirus-cops-jews/story?id=69737522|title=White supremacists encouraging their members to spread coronavirus to cops, Jews, FBI says|website=ABC News|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Excerpt|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|fragment=ChineseVirus|nohat=y}}\n\n===Racial disparities===\n\n[[ProPublica]] conducted an analysis of the racial composition of COVID-19 cases in [[Milwaukee County, Wisconsin]] dating through the morning of April 3. They noted that [[African Americans]] comprised nearly half of the county's cases and 22 of the county's 27 deaths.<ref name=\"ProPublica MKE race\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.propublica.org/article/early-data-shows-african-americans-have-contracted-and-died-of-coronavirus-at-an-alarming-rate | title=Early Data Shows African Americans Have Contracted and Died of Coronavirus at an Alarming Rate |work=[[ProPublica]] | date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nSimilar trends have been seen in regions with sizable African American populations, especially in [[Deep South]] states such as Alabama, Georgia, and Louisiana (which reported on April{{nbsp}}6 that 70% of its reported deaths had involved African Americans), and areas such as Michigan (33% of cases and 41% of deaths as of April 6), and the city of [[Chicago]] (1,824 of its 4,680 confirmed cases, and 72% of deaths as of April 5).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52194018|title=Coronavirus wreaks havoc in US black communities|date=2020-04-07|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Zanolli|first=Lauren|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/08/black-americans-coronavirus-us-south-data|title=Data from US south shows African Americans hit hardest by Covid-19|date=2020-04-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> It has been acknowledged that African Americans were more likely to have poor [[Habitability|living conditions]] (including dense urban environments and [[Poverty in the United States|poverty]]), employment instability, chronic [[Comorbidity|comorbidities]] influenced by these conditions, and little to no health insurance coverage\u2014factors which can all exacerbate its impact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nola.com/news/coronavirus/article_ad6caecc-7905-11ea-b8ad-7ff3f62ac403.html|title=Here's why these 13 Louisiana parishes have some of the highest coronavirus death rates in the U.S.|last=Russel|first=Gordon|website=NOLA.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Eligon|first=John|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/us/coronavirus-race.html|title=Black Americans Face Alarming Rates of Coronavirus Infection in Some States|date=2020-04-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/us/coronavirus-black-americans-race/index.html|title=Why black Americans are at higher risk for coronavirus|last=Levenson|first=Eric |website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nThe CDC has not yet released national data on coronavirus cases based on [[Race (human categorization)|race]]; following calls by Democratic lawmakers and the [[Congressional Black Caucus]], the CDC told ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' that it planned to release data on racial composition of cases.<ref name=\"thehill-disproportionate\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/491518-black-latino-communities-suffering-disproportionately-from-coronavirus|title=Black, Latino communities suffering disproportionately from coronavirus, statistics show|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=2020-04-07|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/491864-cbc-calls-on-cdc-to-report-racial-data|title=Congressional Black Caucus calls on CDC to report racial data|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-04-08|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n===Event cancellations===\n{{See also|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Starbucks COVID-19 Response.jpg|thumb|right|On March 4, Starbucks announced that it would no longer fill reusable cups at its U.S. and Canadian stores.<ref>{{cite news|last=Williams|first=Rossann|url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2020/managing-courageously-through-the-dynamics-of-covid-19/|title=Managing Through the Dynamics of COVID-19|date=March 4, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305115156/https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2020/managing-courageously-through-the-dynamics-of-covid-19/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|agency=[[Starbucks]]}}</ref>]]\n\nTechnology conferences such as Apple Inc.'s [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference|Worldwide Developers Conference]] (WWDC),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/apple-wwdc-moved-to-online-only-cancels-in-person-event.html|title=Apple moves WWDC developers conference online due to coronavirus|last=Leswing|first=Kif|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[E3 2020]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/03/e3-2020-has-been-canceled/|title=It's official: E3 2020 has been canceled [Updated]|last=Machkovech|first=Sam|date=March 11, 2020|website=Ars Technica|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311022503/https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/03/e3-2020-has-been-canceled/|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Facebook F8]], [[Google I/O]] and Cloud Next,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/27/21156308/facebook-f8-developer-conference-cancelled-coronavirus-concern-covid-19|title=Facebook cancels F8 developer conference due to coronavirus concerns|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=February 27, 2020|website=The Verge|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311202715/https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/27/21156308/facebook-f8-developer-conference-cancelled-coronavirus-concern-covid-19|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> and Microsoft's MVP Summit<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/microsoft-cancels-mvp-summit-due-to-covid-19-coronavirus-fears/|title=Microsoft cancels MVP Summit due to COVID-19 coronavirus fears|last=Foley|first=Mary Jo|publisher=ZDNet|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303080934/https://www.zdnet.com/article/microsoft-cancels-mvp-summit-due-to-covid-19-coronavirus-fears/|archive-date=March 3, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/2/21162185/google-microsoft-io-2020-build-tech-conference-coronavirus|title=Google and Microsoft just canceled two conferences ahead of their major ones|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=March 2, 2020|website=The Verge|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311202715/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/2/21162185/google-microsoft-io-2020-build-tech-conference-coronavirus|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> have been either cancelled or have replaced in-person events with [[internet streaming]] events.\n\nOn February 21, Verizon pulled out of an [[RSA Security|RSA]] conference, joining the ranks of AT&T Cybersecurity and IBM.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsaconference.com/novel-coronavirus-update|title=Novel Coronavirus Update|date=January 26, 2020|website=RSA Conference|access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref> On February 29, the [[American Physical Society]] cancelled its annual March Meeting, scheduled for March 2\u20136 in [[Denver]], Colorado, even though many of the more than 11,000 physicist participants had already arrived and participated in the day's pre-conference events.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Castelvecchi|first1=Davide|date=March 2, 2020|title=Coronavirus fears cancel world's biggest physics meeting|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00609-0|url-status=live|journal=Nature|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00609-0|pmid=32203350|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191008/https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00609-0|archive-date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 6, the annual [[South by Southwest]] (SXSW) conference and festival scheduled to run from March 13 to 22 in [[Austin, Texas]], were cancelled following after the city government declared a \"local disaster\" and ordered conferences to shut down for the first time in 34 years.<ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200306-2020-event-update-city-of-austin-cancels-sxsw-march-events\">{{cite press release|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|title=2020 Event Update: City of Austin Cancels SXSW March Events|agency=[[South by Southwest|SXSW]]|url=https://www.sxsw.com/2020-event-update/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306220834/https://www.sxsw.com/2020-event-update/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200306-sxsw-canceled-due-to-coronavirus-after-austin-declares-local-disaster\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/sxsw-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus.html|title=SXSW canceled due to coronavirus after Austin declares 'local disaster'|last=Graham|first=Megan|date=March 6, 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306220022/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/sxsw-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> The cancellation is not covered by insurance.<ref name=\"us-covid-19-sxsw-pledges-future-credit-if-you-bought-a-badge-this-year\">{{cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/business/20200307/sxsw-pledges-future-credit-if-you-bought-badge-this-year|title=SXSW pledges future credit if you bought a badge this year|last1=Sechler|first1=Bob|date=March 7, 2020|work=[[The Austin American-Statesman]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308082915/https://www.statesman.com/business/20200307/sxsw-pledges-future-credit-if-you-bought-badge-this-year|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200306-sxsw-cancellation-not-covered-by-insurance\">{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/news/2020-03-06/sxsw-cancellation-not-covered-by-insurance/|title=SXSW Cancellation Not Covered by Insurance; Communicable diseases, viruses, and pandemics not part of policy|last=Curtin|first=Kevin|date=March 6, 2020|work=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307070427/https://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/news/2020-03-06/sxsw-cancellation-not-covered-by-insurance/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, 73,716 people attended the conferences and festivals, directly spending $200 million and ultimately boosting the local economy by $356 million, or four percent of the annual revenue of the region's hospitality and tourism economic sectors.<ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200307-loss-of-sxsw-gut-punch-for-some-austin-businesses\">{{cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/business/20200307/loss-of-sxsw-gut-punch-for-some-austin-businesses|title=Loss of SXSW a gut punch for some Austin businesses|last1=Sechler|first1=Bob|last2=Hawkins|first2=Lori|date=March 7, 2020|work=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308063805/https://www.statesman.com/business/20200307/loss-of-sxsw-gut-punch-for-some-austin-businesses|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 7, 2020|last3=Novak|first3=Shonda}}</ref><ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200306-austin-cancels-sxsw-over-coronavirus-declares-local-disaster\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/486371-austin-cancels-sxsw-over-coronavirus-declares-local-disaster|title=Austin cancels SXSW over coronavirus, declares 'local disaster'|last1=Seipel|first1=Brooke|date=March 6, 2020|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]], Washington, D.C.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307155608/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/486371-austin-cancels-sxsw-over-coronavirus-declares-local-disaster|archive-date=March 7, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the cancellations of the [[Ultra Music Festival]] in Miami and SXSW in Austin, speculation began to grow about the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] festival set to begin on April 10 in the desert in [[Indio, California]].<ref name=\"us-covid-19-petitions-for-and-against-cancelling-coachella-are-circulating-online\">{{cite web|url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/life/2020/03/06/coronavirus-update-petitions-and-against-cancelling-coachella-appear/4975706002/|title=Coronavirus update: petitions for and against cancelling Coachella are circulating online|last=Blueskye|first=Brian|date=March 6, 2020|work=[[The Desert Sun]], Palm Springs, Calif.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308012351/https://www.desertsun.com/story/life/2020/03/06/coronavirus-update-petitions-and-against-cancelling-coachella-appear/4975706002/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"us-covid-19-will-coronavirus-cancel-coachella-riverside-county-public-health-officer-says-not-yet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/news/2020/03/05/coronavirus-cancel-coachella-county-official-says-not-yet/4958589002/|title=Will coronavirus cancel Coachella? Riverside County public health officer says not yet|last1=Atagi|first1=Colin|last2=Plevin|first2=Rebecca|date=March 5, 2020|work=[[The Desert Sun]], Palm Springs, Calif.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308012446/https://www.desertsun.com/story/news/2020/03/05/coronavirus-cancel-coachella-county-official-says-not-yet/4958589002/|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020|last3=Daniels|first3=Melissa}}</ref> The annual festival, which has attracted some 125,000 people over two consecutive weekends, is insured only in the event of a ''[[force majeure]]'' cancellation such as one ordered by local or state government officials. Estimates on an insurance payout range from $150 million to $200 million.<ref name=\"us-covid-19-20200307-amid-growing-coronavirus-concerns-locals-are-torn-over-coachella-festival-coming-to-their-town\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-07/coachella-festival-coronavirus-cancellation-locals-indio-palm-springs|title=Amid growing coronavirus concerns, locals are torn over Coachella festival coming to their town|last1=Brown|first1=August|date=March 7, 2020|work=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308005709/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-07/coachella-festival-coronavirus-cancellation-locals-indio-palm-springs|archive-date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n====Publishing====\n\nThe scale of the COVID-19 outbreak has prompted several major publishers to temporarily disable their paywalls on related articles, including [[Bloomberg News]], ''[[The Atlantic]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', and ''[[The Seattle Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jerde |first=Sara |date=March 12, 2020 |title=Major Publishers Take Down Paywalls for Coronavirus Coverage |url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/major-publishers-take-down-paywalls-for-coronavirus-coverage/ |work=[[Adweek]] |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CJR\">{{cite news |last=Allsop |first=Jon |date=March 13, 2020 |title=How the coronavirus could hurt the news business |url=https://www.cjr.org/the_media_today/coronavirus_news_business_advertising.php |work=[[Columbia Journalism Review]] |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe pandemic is predicted to have a dire effect on local newspapers, many of which were already severely struggling beforehand.<ref name=\"CJR\"/> Several [[Alternative newspaper|alt weekly]] newspapers in affected metropolitan areas, including ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]'' in Seattle and ''[[Austin Chronicle]]'', have announced layoffs and funding drives due to lost revenue. Advertisements concerning public events and venues accounted for a majority of revenue for alt-weekly newspapers, which was disrupted by the cancellation of large public gatherings.<ref name=\"CJR\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Scire |first=Sarah |date=March 12, 2020 |title=\"This time is different\": In Seattle, social distancing forces The Stranger to make a coronavirus plea |url=https://www.niemanlab.org/2020/03/this-time-is-different-in-seattle-social-distancing-forces-the-stranger-to-make-a-coronavirus-plea/ |publisher=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]] |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Online advertisements also dropped to avoid running ads next to coronavirus coverage,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/27/822428352/pandemic-threatens-local-papers-even-as-readers-devour-their-coverage|title=Pandemic Threatens Local Papers Even As Readers Devour Their Coverage|website=NPR.org}}</ref> and physical mass distribution of non-subscription newspapers became less profitable as many establishments closed and pedestrian traffic on sidewalks and transit stations greatly diminished.\n\n====Film====\n\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n\nMost U.S. cinema chains, where allowed to continue operating, reduced the seating capacity of each show time by half to minimize the risk of spreading the virus between patrons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/movie-theater-chains-limiting-salescoronavirus-1203534095/|title=Movie Theaters Cut Seating Capacity Over Coronavirus|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=March 13, 2020|website=Variety|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Audience limits, as well as mandatory and voluntary closure of cinemas in some areas, led to a total North American box office sales the lowest since October 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/vin-diesel-bloodshot-i-still-believe-the-hunt-weekend-box-office-coronavirus-1202882333/|title=Weekend Box Office Plunges To 22-Year Low At $55M+, Theater Closings Rise To 100+ Overnight As Coronavirus Fears Grip Nation\u2014Sunday Final|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=March 15, 2020|work=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, numerous theater chains temporarily closed their locations nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/coronavirus-movie-theaters-shutdown-alamo-drafthouse-cineplex-odeon-amc-1202885115/|title=Coronavirus Theater Closures in U.S./Canada Hit 3K As Alamo Drafthouse & Others Go Dark: \"This News ... Is Devastating\"|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=March 17, 2020|work=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> A number of Hollywood film companies have suspended production and delayed the release of some films.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/feature/movie-productions-postponed-coronavirus-hollywood-films-1202882857/|title=Coronavirus: Movies That Have Halted Or Delayed Production Amid Outbreak|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=March 16, 2020|work=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2020-03-12/coronavirus-movies-cancelled-postponed|title=Here are all the movie releases that have been postponed due to coronavirus|date=March 17, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 16, 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n====Television====\n\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television}}\n\nA large number of television programs began to suspend production in mid-March due to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2020-03-17/hollywood-production-has-shut-down-what-that-means-for-thousands-of-workers|title=Hollywood production has shut down. Why thousands of workers are feeling the pain|date=2020-03-17|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/tv-shows-coronavirus-delayed-suspend-production-witcher-lord-of-the-rings-fargo-snl/|title=All the TV Productions Suspended or Delayed Due to Coronavirus Pandemic (Updating)|last=Maglio|first=Tony|last2=Nakamura|first2=Reid|date=2020-03-30|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09|last3=Maas|first3=Jennifer|last4=Baysinger|first4=Tim}}</ref>\n\n[[News broadcasting|News]] programs and most [[talk show]]s have largely remained on-air, but with changes to their production to incorporate coverage of the pandemic, and adhere to CDC guidelines on physical distancing and the encouragement of remote work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/17/fox-and-friends-social-distancing-133619|title=The president's favorite morning show starts social distancing|last=Forgey|first=Quint|website=Politico|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/tv-news-coronavirus-coverage-today-cbs-news-1203535596/|title=From Big Debate to 'Today', Coronavirus Forces Quick Change for TV News|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|date=March 16, 2020|website=Variety|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/abc-news-coronavirus-amy-robach-strahan-sara-keke-1203536909/|title=ABC Will Suspend 'Strahan, Sara & Keke' in Favor of Coronavirus News Show|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Most [[late-night talk show]]s and [[news comedy]] programs began returning to air in late-March, adopting formats that see their hosts presenting the program from their homes rather than in a studio, and featuring celebrity interviews and/or music performances conducted via videoconferencing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/the-daily-social-distancing-show-with-trevor-noah-comedy-central-coronavirus-pandemic-1202889491/|title='The Daily Social Distancing Show with Trevor Noah' To Air On Comedy Central During Coronavirus Pandemic|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|date=2020-03-21|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/full-frontal-with-samantha-bee-tv-return-date-coronavirus-pandemic-1202890332/|title='Tonight Show' Returning With Hybrid Episodes & New Guests\u2014Update|last=Petski|first=Denise|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=2020-03-23|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-real-time-with-bill-maher-set-hbo-return-dates-amid-coronavirus-crisis-1202891648/|title='Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' & 'Real Time With Bill Maher' Set HBO Returns Amid Coronavirus Crisis|last1=Petski|first1=Nellie |last2=Andreeva |first2=Denise|date=2020-03-24|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|last3=Petski|first3=Denise}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/jimmy-kimmel-stephen-colbert-seth-meyers-late-night-coronavirus/|title=Late night returns: Stephen Colbert, Jimmy Kimmel, Seth Meyers host from home|website=EW.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/jimmy-kimmel-live-time-slot-remain-1205-am-first-week-back-on-television-nightline-coronavirus-covid-19-1202894653/|title='Jimmy Kimmel Live!' To Remain At 12:05 AM In First Week Back On Television Amid COVID-9 Pandemic|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=2020-03-27|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nQuarantine and remote work efforts, as well as interest in updates on the pandemic, have resulted in a larger potential audience for television broadcasters\u2014especially for news programs and news channels. Nielsen estimated that by March 11 television usage had increased by 22% week-over-week. It was expected that [[streaming service]]s would see an increase in usage, while potential economic downturns associated with the pandemic could accelerate the market trend of [[cord cutting]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Edmund|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/business/media/coronavirus-television-netflix.html|title=Glued to TV for Now, but When Programming Thins and Bills Mount ...|date=March 17, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 19, 2020|last2=Koblin|first2=John|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/03/tv-viewership-advertising-coronavirus-analysis-1202218603/|title=Analysts Warn TV Viewership Increases Won't Stop Financial Hit from Coronavirus|last=Hersko|first=Tyler|date=March 18, 2020|website=IndieWire|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Draper|first=Kevin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/sports/sports-television-coronavirus.html|title=When Coronavirus Turns Every Sports Channel into ESPN Classic|date=March 16, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 19, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\n''The Hollywood Reporter'' observed gains in average viewership for some programs between March{{nbsp}}9 and April 2, with the top increases including ''[[The Blacklist (TV series)|The Blacklist]]'' (31.2% gain in average audience since March 9), ''[[20/20 (American TV program)|20/20]]'' (30.8%), ''[[America's Funniest Home Videos]]'' (27.2%), ''[[60 Minutes]]'' (26.7% above average without [[NFL on CBS|NFL]] lead-outs, and the largest gain in the [[key demographic]]), and ''[[Shark Tank]]'' (24%).<ref name=\"thr-longgame\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/60-minutes-blacklist-lead-quarantine-viewing-gains-1288507|title=TV Long View: The Shows With the Biggest Quarantine Viewing Gains|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> These effects have also been seen on syndicated programs,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/wheel-fortune-dr-oz-score-big-ratings-gains-quarantines-1288979|title='Wheel of Fortune,' 'Dr. Oz' Score Big Ratings Gains During Quarantines|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and the [[Big Three television networks|Big Three networks]]' daytime [[soap opera]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2020/03/31/soaps-ratings-daytime-quarantine-y-and-r/|title=Daytime Soaps Surge: B&B, Days, GH and Y&R Experience Significant Ratings Boosts as America Quarantines|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|last2=Ausiello|first2=Michael|date=2020-03-31|website=TVLine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[WarnerMedia]] reported that [[HBO Now]] saw a spike in usage, and the most viewed titles included documentary ''Ebola: The Doctors' Story'' and the 2011 film ''[[Contagion (2011 film)|Contagion]]'' for their resonance with the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/hbo-now-usage-leaps-40-amid-coronavirus-crisis-warnermedia-posts-viewership-gains-with-titles-like-ebola-contagion-1202891495/|title=HBO Now Usage Leaps 40% Amid Coronavirus Crisis; WarnerMedia Posts Viewership Gains With Titles Like 'Ebola' & Contagion'|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=March 24, 2020|work=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sports {{anchor|Impact on sports}}===\n\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n[[File:Sacramento Kings game postponed, 2020-03-11.jpg|alt=A large screen announcing the game canceled|thumb|The NBA was the first major sports league to suspend operations, including clearing out this March 11 game between the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] and [[Sacramento Kings]].]]\n\nA suspension of games for various time periods were announced by almost all professional sports leagues in the United States on March 11 and 12, including the [[National Basketball Association]] (which had a player announced as having tested positive),<ref name=\"wsj-sportsshutdown\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ncaa-medical-chief-says-testing-shortage-threatens-march-madness-11584030721|title=The Day Sports Shut Down|date=March 12, 2020|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> [[National Hockey League]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/nhl-suspends-regular-season-due-coronavirus-concerns/|title=NHL suspends regular season due to coronavirus concerns|work=[[Sportsnet]]|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[Major League Baseball]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/sports/mlb/mets/2020/03/16/coronavirus-mlb-delays-season-indefinitely-amid-cdc-restrictions/5061192002/|title=MLB delays season indefinitely after CDC announces restrictions amid coronavirus fears|first=Justin|last=Toscano|website=North Jersey}}</ref> and [[Major League Soccer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/concacaf-champions-league/story/4073261/concacaf-champions-league-suspended-liga-mx-take-coronavirus-measures|title=CONCACAF, Liga MX take coronavirus measures|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/12/major-league-soccer-suspends-season-for-30-days-amid-concern-over-coronavirus.html|title=Major League Soccer suspends season for 30 days amid concern over coronavirus|last=Kimball|first=Spencer|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[College athletics]] competitions were similarly cancelled by schools, [[Athletic conference|conferences]] and the [[NCAA]]\u2014which cancelled all remaining championships for the academic year on March 12. This also resulted in the first-ever cancellation of the NCAA's popular [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|\"March Madness\" men's basketball tournament]] (which had been scheduled to begin the following week) in its 81-year history.<ref name=\"wsj-sportsshutdown\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/march-madness-ncaa-tournament-canceled-coronavirus|title=No shining moments: NCAA basketball tournaments are canceled for the first time|date=March 13, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|url-access=subscription|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/coronavirus-updates-ncaa-cancels-championship-competition-for-all-winter-and-spring-sports/|title=Coronavirus updates: NCAA cancels championship competition for all winter and spring sports|website=CBSSports.com|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 BNP Paribas Open|2020 Indian Wells Masters]] tennis tournaments were cancelled on March 10.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rothenberg|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/sports/coronavirus-indian-wells-canceled.html|title=Indian Wells Tennis Tournament Canceled Because of Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 8, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 10, 2020|last2=Clarey|first2=Christopher|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[ATP Tour]] and [[WTA Tour]] have both suspended competition until late April, which has also led to the cancellation of the [[Miami Open (tennis)|Miami Open]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/tennis/51841130|title=Coronavirus: ATP Tour shuts down for six weeks because of outbreak|date=March 12, 2020|work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[NASCAR]] on March 13 postponed the races at [[Atlanta Motor Speedway]] and announced on March 16 that it will postpone all race events until May 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/16/nascar-schedule-update-statement-race-coronavirus/|title=NASCAR statement: All race events through May 3 postponed|date=March 16, 2020|work=NASCAR.com|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[IndyCar Series]] similarly announced the cancellation of all races through the end of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibj.com/articles/indycar-series-canceling-all-races-before-month-of-may-in-indy|title=IndyCar series canceling all races before Month of May in Indy|website=Indianapolis Business Journal|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[PGA Tour]] played the first round of the [[2020 Players Championship]] on March 12, and said subsequent rounds and tournaments would be held without spectators,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/12/pga-tour-wont-allow-fans-for-foreseeable-future-due-to-coronavirus.html|title=PGA Tour won't allow fans for foreseeable future due to coronavirus|last=Golden|first=Jessica|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> but later cancelled the rest of the tournament and subsequent events through early-May.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/here-are-all-the-golf-tournaments-that-have-been-canceled-or-postponed-due-to-the-coronavirus|title=Here are all the golf tournaments that have been canceled or postponed due to the coronavirus|last=Herrington|first=Ryan|website=Golf Digest|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28894497/pga-tour-cancels-players-championship-first-round|title=Players Championship scrapped after 1st round|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[LPGA Tour]] similarly cancelled all events through April.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28893923/lpga-reschedule-3-events-including-first-major-ana-inspiration|title=LPGA postpones 3 events, including first major|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Two [[Men's major golf championships|men's majors]], the Masters and PGA Championship, were postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28897249/augusta-national-announces-masters-postponed-played|title=Augusta announces Masters will be postponed|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===Religious services===\n\n{{seealso|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n[[File:COVID-19 NC church closure.jpg|thumb| ]]\n\nAmidst the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic, many churches, mosques, synagogues and temples have suspended religious services to void the spread of disease.<ref name=churchesmosques>{{cite news|title=The great shutdown 2020: What churches, mosques and temples are doing to fight the spread of coronavirus|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/world/churches-mosques-temples-coronavirus-spread/index.html|publisher=[[CNN News]]}}</ref> Many religious organizations continued to do charitable work (e.g. deliver food) during the pandemic.\n\nDespite the pandemic, many American religious organizations continue to operate their [[food bank|food pantries]]. Churches offered bags filled with meat and toilet paper rolls for needy families.<ref name=\"Dias2020\">{{cite news |last1=Dias |first1=Elizabeth |title=A Sunday Without Church: In Crisis, a Nation Asks, 'What Is Community?' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/us/churches-coronavirus-services.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Many [[mosque]]s have closed for prayers but continued to run their food bank.<ref>{{cite news|title='We see this as our responsibility': Muslims fundraise for Americans impacted by coronavirus|url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-us-muslim-help-vulnerable-impacted-covid19|publisher=[[Middle East Eye]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=An Imam Leads His Congregation Through the Pandemic|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/on-religion/an-imam-leads-his-congregation-through-the-coronavirus-pandemic|work=[[The New Yorker]]|author=Eliza Griswold|quote=The mosque was no longer hosting daily prayer, since disinfecting the carpet four times a day had proved to be an overwhelming amount of work. But it was still giving out food to those who needed it.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Muslim communities delivering food, medication to sick and elderly during coronavirus pandemic|url=https://www.pennlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/muslim-communities-delivering-food-medication-to-sick-and-elderly-during-coronavirus-pandemic.html|date=2020-03-20|website=pennlive.com}}</ref> The [[National Cathedral]] of the United States, which belongs to [[the Episcopal Church]], donated more than five thousand [[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 surgical masks]] to hospitals of Washington D.C., which were in shortage during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Gryboski2020\">{{cite web |last1=Gryboski |first1=Michael |title=National Cathedral donates 5,000 respirator masks to DC hospitals |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/national-cathedral-donates-5000-respirator-masks-to-dc-hospitals.html |work=[[The Christian Post]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Other churches, such as the [[Church of the Highlands]], an evangelical Christian megachurch, have offered free [[COVID-19 testing|COVID-19 tests]] in their parking lots.<ref name=\"RFBF2020\">{{cite web |title=Amazon Adds Jobs and Megachurch Helps with Covid-19 Testing |url=https://religiousfreedomandbusiness.org/2/post/2020/03/amazon-adds-jobs-and-megachurch-helps-with-covid-19-testing.html |publisher=Religious Freedom & Business Foundation |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany churches have suspended in-person worship services, moving worship to radio, television and online services, while others have offered drive-in services.<ref>{{cite web |title=Westerville church offering 'drive in' service |url=https://www.10tv.com/article/westerville-church-offering-drive-service-2020-mar |publisher=[[WBNS-TV]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Some state orders against large gatherings, such as in Ohio and New York, specifically exempt religious organizations.<ref>{{cite web|website=Newsweek|title=U.S. CHURCHES HOLD PUBLIC SUNDAY SERVICES DESPITE CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK: 'THIS IS DANGEROUS' |date=March 23, 2020|author=Jason Murdock|url=https://www.newsweek.com/church-sunday-service-open-despite-coronavirus-covid19-health-advice-social-distancing-1493756}} [https://www.citybeat.com/news/blog/21124035/one-of-greater-cincinnatis-largest-churches-continues-services-despite-coronavirus One of Greater Cincinnati's Largest Churches Continues Services Despite Coronavirus] City Beat (Cincinnati), March 24, 2020</ref> Colorado Springs Fellowship Church insists it has a constitutional right to defy a state closure order.<ref>[https://krdo.com/news/2020/03/24/colorado-springs-church-says-it-has-constitutional-right-to-open-defying-state-health-order/ Colorado Springs church says it has Constitutional right to open, defying state health order] By Chelsea Brentzel, KRDO, March 24, 2020</ref> Evangelical college [[Liberty University]] of Lynchburg, Virginia, moved its classes online but called its 5,000 back to campus despite Governor [[Ralph Northam |Ralph Northam's]] (D) order to close all non-essential businesses.<ref>[https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/489212-liberty-university-welcomes-back-students-amid-covid-19-outbreak?fbclid=IwAR3n2vjm37_qmm97yyvEzyllibSINsUTRwtB083ZDJ5zuUbNKZFSXfdFb-Y Liberty University welcomes back students despite coronavirus] BY MARTY JOHNSON, The Hill, March 24, 2020</ref> Rev. [[Rodney Howard-Browne]] of the River at Tampa Bay Church in Florida was arrested and fined on March 30 for violating coronavirus-related bans on large gatherings. He had encouraged crowds as large as five hundred over the weekend and argued that churches should get exemptions as essential services.<ref>{{cite web|website=boston.com/The Washington Post|title=Florida sheriff charges megapastor who kept church open, said closings are for 'pansies'|date=March 30, 2020|author=Michelle Boorstein|accessdate=March 30, 2020 |url=https://www.boston.com/news/national-news-2/2020/03/30/florida-sheriff-charges-megapastor-who-kept-church-open-said-closings-are-for-pansies}}</ref>\n\nBy March 20, every [[Catholic Church in the United States|Roman Catholic]] diocese in the United States had suspended the public celebration of Mass and [[Dispensation (canon law)|dispense]]d with the obligation to attend [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] on the [[Lord's Day]], as had the [[Personal Ordinariate of the Chair of Saint Peter]]. The [[Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church]] in the United States also suspended public Divine Liturgies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Do we have Mass? Coronavirus closures and dispensations in US dioceses|agency=[[Catholic News Agency]]|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/do-we-have-mass-coronavirus-closures-and-dispensations-in-us-dioceses-96801}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter|title=Suspension of public Masses|first=John Francis|last=Doerfler|authorlink=John Francis Doerfler|recipient=Brothers and Sisters in Christ|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Marquette]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020 |url=https://dioceseofmarquette.org/images/files/Communications/03-17-20_SuspensionofpublicMasses.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter|title=Decree\u2014suspending liturgical services & other activities|first=Curtis J.|last=Guillory|authorlink=Curtis J. Guillory|recipient=Sisters and Brothers in Christ|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Beaumont]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.dioceseofbmt.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Decree-3-18-2020-English.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter|title=Public Mass suspended|first=Peter F.|last=Christensen|authorlink=Peter F. Christensen|recipient=the Catholic Faithful of the Diocese of Boise|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Boise]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020 |url=https://www.catholicidaho.org/media/1/sUS%20mAS%20E%26S.pdf|format=PDF}} {{cite letter|title=Decree for Protocols Regarding Coronavirus-19 COVID-19|first=Patrick|last=Zurek|authorlink=Patrick Zurek|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Amarillo]]|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.amarillodiocese.org/protocols-regarding-coronavirus-english}}</ref><ref>{{cite letter|title=Instruction regarding Protocols in Response to the Presence of COVID-19 in the Diocese of El Paso|first=Mark J.|last=Seitz|authorlink=Mark J. Seitz|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of El Paso]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.elpasodiocese.org/bishops-letter-for-covid-19.html}} {{cite web|title=Coronavirus Precautions|publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Fort Worth]]|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://fwdioc.org/coronavirus-precautions|quote=The circumstances current in our community are such that attendance at Mass borders on an impossibility and thus there is no obligation to attend.}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2020, Bishop Elaine JW Stanovsky of the Pacific Northwest Annual Conference of the [[United Methodist Church]] issued a statement that would be updated no later than the start of [[Holy Week]], which directed \"the local churches of any size and other ministries in the states of Alaska, Idaho, Oregon and Washington to suspend in-person worship and other gatherings of more than 10 people for the next two weeks.\"<ref name=\"Bloom2020\">{{cite web |last1=Bloom |first1=Linda |title=Churches adapting to COVID-19 restrictions |url=https://www.umnews.org/en/news/churches-adapting-to-covid-19-restrictions |publisher=United Methodist News Service |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Many parts of the [[Methodist Church]]es, which uphold [[Sunday Sabbatarianism|Sunday Sabbatarian]] teaching, have transitioned their church services online; ninety percent of the parishes within the Pacific Northwest Annual Conference of the United Methodist Church, for example, are now offering worship via internet livestream.<ref name=\"Bloom2020\"/> In the state of Kansas, the Democratic governor, [[Laura Kelly]] responded to a prime source of spread of the disease by banning religious services attended by more than 10 people. The Republican-dominated Legislative Coordinating Council, gave itself the power to overturn her orders and did so on a party-line, 5-2 vote, supported by the Republican Attorney General. On April 11, convening on an expedited basis, the Kansas Supreme Court reinstated her orders.<ref>[https://www.kmbc.com/article/kansas-supreme-court-says-executive-order-banning-religious-service-of-more-than-10-people-stands-governor-laura-kelly-covid-19-coronavirus/32114710# Kansas Supreme Court says executive order banning religious service of more than 10 people stands], ''[[KMBC-TV|KMBC]]'', April 11, 2020. Retrieved April 12, 2020.</ref>\n\n\nOn March 24, President Trump said, in regard to Easter (April 12), \"Wouldn't it be great to have all the churches full? You'll have packed churches all over our country. I think it'll be a beautiful time.\" As of March 25, many churches were not prepared to risk reopening, and most churches were predicted to remain closed on Easter.<ref>{{cite web|website=Washington Examiner|title=Churches won't be 'packed' for Easter despite Trump call|author=Nicholas Rowan|date=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/churches-wont-be-packed-for-easter-despite-trump-call}}</ref>\n\nStarting from March 13, mosques in America began to suspend [[Jumuah|Friday congregational prayers]].<ref name=WaPoMosque/> The [[Islamic Society of North America]] and [[Islamic Medical Association of North America]] had both recommended the suspension of services.<ref name=churchesmosques/><ref name=WaPoMosque>{{cite news|title=Mosques cancel Friday prayers as leaders face a dilemma of whether to close|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/religion/2020/03/13/dilemma-facing-religious-leaders-when-close-doors-during-pandemic/|publisher=[[Washington Post]]}}</ref> The [[Islamic Cultural Center of New York]] shut all activities at its building, and instead offered its classes via the internet.<ref>{{cite news|title=Praying in time of COVID-19: How world's largest mosques adapted|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/praying-time-covid-19-world-largest-mosques-adapted-200406112601868.html|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\nAlthough most churches aired [[Palm Sunday]] worship via broadcast media or gathered together for drive-in services, some congregations gathered for Holy Week services under the religious exemptions allowed in many areas, while a minority defied the ban on mass gatherings in other areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/04/us/ap-virus-outbreak-closing-churches.html|title=New Coronavirus Limits Bring New Religious Freedom Tension|date=4 April 2020|work=The New York Times |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/640290/defiant-pastors-palm-sunday-church/|title=Christian pastors hold packed services on Palm Sunday to 'fight Satan' despite exploding virus death toll|first=Lucy|last=Sherriff|date=5 April 2020|work=The Sun|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/us/church-services-palm-sunday-coronavirus-trnd/index.html|title=Churches hold Palm Sunday services despite state bans on gatherings|first1=Melissa|last1=Alonso|first2=Deanna|last2=Hackney|first3=Theresa|last3=Waldrop|date=5 April 2020|publisher=Cable News Network|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-church-services-outbreak/2020/04/05/7f5b63cc-7773-11ea-90ad-819caa48d39f_story.html|title=Coronavirus creates conflict for churches, where gatherings can be dangerous but also provide solace|first1=Scott|last1=Wilson|first2=Michelle|last2=Boorstein|first3=Arelis|last3=Hern\u00e1ndez|first4=Lori|last4=Rozsa|date=5 April 2020|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/05/pastors-vow-to-host-palm-sunday-mass-during-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=Defiant pastors vow to host Palm Sunday mass during coronavirus pandemic|first=Vincent|last=Barone|date=5 April 2020|publisher=New York Post|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sikh]] Center of New York prepared more than 30,000 home-cooked meals for Americans in self-isolation amid the novel coronavirus outbreak. The Sikh community was approached by [[Mayor of New York City|New York's Mayor]] office for food packages that were handed out to several distributing federal agencies in the area.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/trending-news/story/coronavirus-sikh-volunteers-prepare-over-30-000-meal-packets-for-americans-in-self-isolation-1659059-2020-03-24 |title=Coronavirus: Sikh volunteers prepare over 30,000 meal packets for Americans in self-isolation |work=India Today |date=24 March 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/world/2020/mar/24/covid-19-new-york-sikhs-prepare-over-30000-free-meal-packets-for-americans-in-self-isolation-2120894.html |title=COVID-19: New York Sikhs prepare over 30,000 free meal packets for Americans in self-isolation |work=The New Indian Express |date=24 March 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Public response==\n\n[[File:2020-03-06 \u2014 Coronavirus \u2013 Flyers at Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport wearing facemasks.jpg|thumb|Passengers wearing facemasks at [[Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport]]]]\nOpinion polling showed a significant partisan divide regarding the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/15/21180506/coronavirus-poll-democrats-republicans-trump|title=A new poll shows a startling partisan divide on the dangers of the coronavirus|first=Zeeshan|last=Aleem|date=March 15, 2020|website=Vox}}</ref> [[NPR]], [[PBS NewsHour]] and Marist found in their mid-March survey that 76% of Democrats viewed COVID-19 as \"a real threat\", while only 40% of Republicans agreed; the previous month's figures for Democrats and Republicans were 70% and 72% respectively.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Allyn |first1=Bobby |last2=Sprunt |first2=Barbara |title=Poll: As Coronavirus Spreads, Fewer Americans See Pandemic As A Real Threat |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/17/816501871/poll-as-coronavirus-spreads-fewer-americans-see-pandemic-as-a-real-threat |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=NPR |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> A mid-March poll conducted by NBC News and ''The Wall Street Journal'' found that 60% of Democrats were concerned someone in their family might contract the virus, while 40% of Republicans expressed concern. Nearly 80% of Democrats believed the worst was yet to come, whereas 40% of Republicans thought so. About 56% of Democrats believed their lives would change in a major way due to the outbreak, compared to 26% for Republicans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/meet-the-press/sixty-percent-believe-worst-yet-come-u-s-coronavirus-pandemic-n1159106 |title=Sixty percent believe worst is yet to come for the U.S. in coronavirus pandemic; Public attitudes about the coronavirus response are split along partisan lines in a new NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll |publisher=NBC News |author=Mark Murray |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> A mid-March poll by the [[Kaiser Family Foundation]] found that 83% of Democrats had taken certain precautions against the virus, compared to 53% of Republicans. The poll found that President Trump was the least-trusted source of information about the outbreak, at 46% overall, after the CDC, WHO, state and local government officials, and the news media, although 88% of Republicans expressed trust in the president, second only to their trust in the CDC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/business/2020/03/democrats-republicans-coronavirus-trump.html|title=Democrats Are Being Much, Much More Careful About the Coronavirus Than Republicans|first=Jordan|last=Weissmann|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[Slate (magazine)]]}}</ref>\n\n{{Excerpt|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Other countries|fragment=USA Politics|nohat=1}}\n\n==Medical aid to the United States==\n\nChinese billionaire [[Jack Ma]] has donated coronavirus test kits and face masks to the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chinese billionaire Jack Ma is shipping coronavirus test kits and masks to the U.S. |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jack-ma-coronavirus-test-kits-chinese-billionaire-alibaba-shipping-masks-supplies-to-united-states-donating/ |publisher=CBS News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Russia sent a cargo plane with ventilators and face masks which the U.S. paid for.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Holland|first=Steve|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-russia-usa-idUSKBN21K34Z|title=U.S. paying Russia for entire planeload of coronavirus equipment: U.S. official|date=2020-04-02|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-11|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> Kremlin spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] said that \"when offering assistance to US colleagues, [Putin] assumes that when US manufacturers of medical equipment and materials gain momentum, they will also be able to reciprocate if necessary.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Russian plane takes off for US with coronavirus help on board |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/russian-plane-takes-coronavirus-aboard-200401065932015.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Where Has Russia Sent Coronavirus Aid Around the World? |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/04/01/where-has-russia-sent-coronavirus-aid-around-the-world-a69825 |work=[[The Moscow Times]] |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> According to Russia's RBC business daily, the company that manufactures the ventilators that were delivered by Russia is under U.S. sanctions.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reuters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/03/world/europe/03reuters-health-coronavirus-russia-usa-sanctions.html|title=Russian Ventilators Shipped to U.S. Made by Firm Under U.S. Sanctions: RBC|date=April 3, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 3, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[India]] has agreed to export [[Hydroxychloroquine]] to the United States, after being requested to do so by the U.S. president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-04-07/india-ship-hydroxychloroquine-u-s|title=India says it will ship hydroxychloroquine to U.S. after Trump threatens retaliation|date=2020-04-07|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> However, there were contraindications in the utilization of Hydroxychloroquine, especially in the cases of those who have preconditions such as heart disease, psoriasis or diabetes. The drug label advises that hydroxychloroquine should not be prescribed to individuals with known hypersensitivity to [[4-aminoquinoline]] compounds.<ref name=PlaquenilLabel>{{cite web | title=Plaquenil- hydroxychloroquine sulfate tablet | website=DailyMed | date=3 January 2020 | url=https://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/drugInfo.cfm?setid=34496b43-05a2-45fb-a769-52b12e099341 | access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> There are a range of other contraindications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pdr.net/drug-summary/Plaquenil-hydroxychloroquine-sulfate-1911|title=Plaquenil (hydroxychloroquine sulfate) dose, indications, adverse effects, interactions|website=pdr.net|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.webmd.com/drugs/2/drug-5482/hydroxychloroquine-oral/details|title=Drugs & Medications|website=webmd.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n{{gallery\n| File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United States (Density).svg|Map of states and territories in the U.S. with number of confirmed cases ({{As of|2020|04|10|lc=y|df=US}})\n{{legend|#D3D3D3|None confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|<2,500 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|2,500\u20139,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|10,000\u201349,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|50,000\u2013150,000 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#500000|>150,000 confirmed}}\n| File:COVID-19 Pandemic Deaths in the United States (Density).svg|Map of states and territories in the U.S. with number of confirmed deaths ({{As of|2020|04|10|lc=y|df=US}})\n{{legend|#D3D3D3|None confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|<50 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|50\u201399 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|100\u2013499 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|500\u20135,000 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#500000|>5,000 confirmed}}\n| File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United States by counties (Confirmed).svg|Confirmed COVID-19 cases by county ({{As of|2020|04|10|lc=y|df=US}})\n| File:Lab-specimens-tested.jpg|Number of tests done per day in the United States by the CDC and public health labs (private labs are not included).<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing-in-us.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>{{br}}\u00a7 Data during this period are pending.\n|title=}}\n\nThe following numbers are based on CDC data. However, CDC data is incomplete. In most U.S. locations, testing for some time was performed only on symptomatic people with a history of travel to Wuhan or with close contact to such people.<ref name=\"Madrigal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/925233|title=Persons Evaluated for 2019 Novel Coronavirus\u2014US, Jan 2020|website=Medscape|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"McFall_testing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/new-york-man-denied-coronavirus-test-japan-trip-fever-cough-2020-3|title=A New York City man wasn't tested for the coronavirus even though he had symptoms and had gone to Japan. It highlights the troublingly limited scope of US testing.|first=Morgan|last=McFall-Johnsen|website=Business Insider|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> A quarantined nurse in California, showing symptoms of COVID-19 but without a travel history, said she was denied testing by the CDC in early March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/08/u-s-response-to-the-covid-19-coronavirus-moves-from-containment-to-mitigation|title=US response to the COVID-19 coronavirus moves from 'containment' to 'mitigation'|date=March 8, 2020|first=Jonathan|last=Shieber|work=TechCrunch}}</ref> CDC testing protocols did not include non-travelling patients with no known contact with China until February 28.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/27/health/us-cases-coronavirus-community-transmission/index.html|title=The CDC has changed its criteria for testing patients for coronavirus after the first case of unknown origin was confirmed|first1=Sarah |last1=Moon |first2=Holly |last2=Yan |first3=Jen |last3=Christensen |first4=Christina|last4=Maxouris|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original CDC-developed tests sent out on February{{nbsp}}5 turned out to be faulty.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/trumps-misplaced-blame-on-obama-for-coronavirus-tests/|title=Trump's Misplaced Blame on Obama for Coronavirus Tests|first=Jessica|last=McDonald|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On February 29, the FDA announced that labs would be allowed to do their own in-house testing immediately, independently of CDC testing, as long as they complete an emergency use authorization (EUA) within 15 days.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\"/> In Washington, state regulators at one point told health care workers to stop testing previously collected samples from an existing non-COVID19 flu study.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/world/coronavirus-news.html|title=U.S. Cases of Coronavirus Surpass 1,000; British Health Minister Is Infected|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 18, the CDC reported that 37,824 specimens had been tested for COVID-19, 4,484 of which were tested by CDC labs, and 33,340 tested by U.S. public health labs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html|title=Testing in the U.S.|date=March 16, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316204847/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The number of deaths is also probably an undercount, as it leaves out some Americans who tested positive but did not have the virus listed on their death certificates, and others who died without being tested. The CDC says it will issue an official estimate of coronavirus deaths in 2021\u2014current estimates may not be reliable.<ref name=\"Kliff+Bosman\">{{cite news |last1=Kliff |first1=Sarah |last2=Bosman |first2=Julie |title=Official Counts Understate the U.S. Coronavirus Death Toll |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/us/coronavirus-deaths-undercount.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation estimates a peak in deaths per day by April 15, with a total of about 80,000 deaths in the United States due to coronavirus by August.<ref>{{cite web|website=The Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME)|url=https://covid19.healthdata.org/projections|title=COVID-19 Projections|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Number of non-repatriated cases by date {{anchor|State number of reported cases by date}}===\n\n{{main|Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States medical cases}}\n<!--Template for Graph:Chart is at [[Template:Graph:Chart]]-->\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=700\n|height=400\n|colors=#FF4343\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|yAxisTitle=N